<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> International Court Concerned About Legality of NATO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 2 (Xinhua)-- A British Committee said on Wednesday
that the International Court of Justice at the Hague had expressed
the "profound concern" about the legality of NATO's military
actions against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
The Committee for Peace in the Balkans, chaired by Alice Mahon,
a Parliamentary Member (MP) from the Labour Party, said in a
statement that the profound concern would be "reflected by the
hundreds of thousands of demonstrators world-wide who will march
on Saturday, 5 June against NATO bombing."
</P>
<P>
Although the International Court of Justice considered itself,
for technical reasons, "not competent" to judge Yugoslavia's
application against NATO bombing, it is of note that presiding
Judge Christopher Weeramantry said that the action "raises very
serious issues of international law," the statement noted.
</P>
<P>
The committee said its statement echoed the many legal voices
who have challenged the legality of NATO's action, including that
the action is in clear breach of the United Nations Charter, that
NATO has targeted civilians in violation of the Geneva Conventions
and that NATO leaders have authorised the use of poisonous weapons
calculated to cause unnecessary suffering, such as depleted
uranium ammunition and cluster bombs.
</P>
<P>
It said the committee was planning a demonstration against NATO
bombing in London.
</P>
<P>
"Thousands of people will add the expression of their own
concern to that of the International Court, by demonstrating in
London on Saturday 5 June," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The Committee for Peace in the Balkans, which was established
in 1991 to promote peace and reconciliation in the former Yugoslav
nations, also strongly criticized NATO's bombing of the hospital
at Surdulica on Monday.
</P>
<P>
"This action is yet another blatant and brutal assertion of US
power, using NATO as its missile," it quoted Playwright Harold
Pinter, who was scheduled to speak at Saturday's demonstration, as
saying. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
