<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ugandan Economy Experiences Dramatic Recovery: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan President Yoweri Museveni
said that the national economy has undergone dramatic recovery
since 1986 due to the good policies of the National Resistance
Movement (NRM), the ruling party.
</P>
<P>
He made these remarks when opening the fourth session of the
sixth Parliament at the International Conference Center here
Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The recovery has been recorded in macro-economic stabilization,
 liberalization, privatization, infrastructure and social services
 development.
</P>
<P>
The inflation rate was as high as 20 percent in 1986 when the
ruling party came to power. Now it has dropped to 5 percent. The
country's gross domestic product (GDP) has more than doubled in
the past 10 years.
</P>
<P>
The economic growth averages 5.6 percent in the past decade and
a rate of 7.8 percent is projected for the current financial year
ending by the end of this month.
</P>
<P>
Although the minimum goals have been achieved, he noted, the
government still needs to transform the fundamental character of
the neo-colonial- dependent economy.
</P>
<P>
He said that the long-term target of the government is to
ensure transformation of the neo-colonial economy into a modern,
integrated and self-sustaining national economy.
</P>
<P>
The 55-year-old president listed education, infrastructure,
health and security continue to the areas of priority for the
government in the years to come. 
</P>
</TEXT>
