<HEADLINE> DRC Minister Appeals Son to Abandon Rebellion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, June 2 (Xinhua) -- The Democratic Republic of
Congolese (DRC) Minister of Industry and Economy Bemba Saolona,
father of one of rebel leaders fighting to oust President Laurent
Kabila, appealed to Ugandan President Yoweri Museveni Tuesday to
convince his son to abandon rebellion.
</P>
<P>
The minister, one of the six members of the visiting delegation
from Kinshasa, made known his appeal at a press conference, the
New Vision paper reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
He said his son, leader of the Congolese Liberation Army (MLC)
fighting in the northern part of the country, was trained by
Ugandans as a soldier.
</P>
<P>
The minister, a millionaire in the mineral-rich country, was
jailed for some days by Kabila on suspicion of dealing with rebels
who control nearly half of Africa's third largest country. He was
released and made minister in March at the height on an offensive
by MLC in northwestern DRC.
</P>
<P>
The junior Bemba, however, said that he was fighting to stop
the injustice in the country, adding that his father's political
line does not in the least affect his cause. 
</P>
</TEXT>
