<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Calls for More U.N. Role in Kosovo Peace Efforts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 2 (Xinhua) -- A senior Chinese diplomat
said Wednesday that the United Nations should play an important
role in seeking a political settlement to the Kosovo crisis, and
called for an immediate end to the on-going NATO bombing to pave
the way for a political solution.
</P>
<P>
Shen Guofang, deputy Chinese permanent representative to the
United Nations, told the Security Council that "We hold, as
always, it is the only way out for a solution to the Kosovo crisis
to resume the United Nations role in the peace process."
</P>
<P>
Shen made the remarks at the close-door Security Council
session to hear the briefing by Sergio Vieira de Mello, U.N.
undersecretary-general for humanitarian affairs, on the findings
in his recent visit to Kosovo and other parts of Yugoslavia. U.N.
Secretary-General Kofi Annan was present at the meeting.
</P>
<P>
"The Security Council should play an important role in the
process of a political solution, and we appreciate the efforts by
the Secretary-General in this regard," he said.
</P>
<P>
"It would be of great sadness for all its Member States if the
United Nations remains a onlooker on the important issue
concerning war and peace at a time when the air strikes has
entered 71st day," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We reject any effort to marginalise the United Nations, nor do
we accept that the United Nations is only limited to its role in
addressing humanitarian problems and the post-war reconstruction,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
"We once again called upon NATO to immediately end its bombing
to pave the way for a political solution," he said, adding that
efforts should be made to strengthen a U.N. task force headed by
the Deputy U.N. Secretary-General, Louise Frechette.
</P>
<P>
"What is most important is that the task force should not only
discuss the contingent plan and post-war reconstruction, but also
should concentrate on discussing how to promote a ceasefire and
seek a political solution," he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Shen said, "The Chinese Mission condemns all
violence in Kosovo, and deplores the bombing and destruction of
numerous civilian houses and shops, and sympathizes with more than
7,000,000 Kosovar refugees."
</P>
<P>
"We maintain that the rights of all ethnic groups in Kosovo
should be protected, and those refugees have the right to return
home in safety at an early date," he said.
</P>
<P>
Shen said that he was also concerned at the fact that NATO is
creating the most serious humanitarian catastrophe since the end
of the World War II in the Balkans under the pretext of
humanitarianism.
</P>
<P>
The bombing caused a lot of deaths among innocent civilians,
and destroyed Yugoslavia's economic infrastructure, he said,
adding that all these can not justify what NATO is saying about
its motives of bombing.
</P>
<P>
NATO, without the authorisation of the U.N. Security Council,
unilaterally launched air strikes on Yugoslavia, a sovereign and
independent member, on March 24, thus violating the U.N. Charter
and international law.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
