<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 18:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pro-Israeli Militia Retreats from Most of Jezzine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, June 2 (Xinhua) -- The pro-Israeli South Lebanon
Army (SLA) Wednesday evacuated 24 villages around Jezzine in south
Lebanon and may complete its withdrawal from the town by the end
of this week after 14 years of occupation.
</P>
<P>
Security sources said that the SLA militiamen are congregated
in the center of Jezzine and other four villages to await the
final pullout to the Israeli occupied border zone in south
Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Witnesses said Lebanese police units crossed into the Jezzine
district before dawn to patrol the villages already vacated by
the SLA.
</P>
<P>
But, the tension in the town is still high while most of the
city's shops, cafes, cinemas and businesses are closed for the
second consecutive day, residents reached by telephone said,
adding that journalists are not allowed to enter the town.
</P>
<P>
The militia's withdrawal, which began Monday night, came under
the pressure of Hezbollah' attacks that have killed more than 100
militiamen and wounded about 400 others around Jezzine in the
past 14 years.
</P>
<P>
The 2,500-strong SLA, established in 1985, is financed and
trained by Israeli forces to help patrol the security zone set up
by Israel in south Lebanon in 1985 with the claimed aim of
protecting its northern flank from Lebanese guerrillas's
cross-border attacks.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian-backed Hezbollah, or Party of God, has been
leading a war of attrition trying to oust the Israeli occupation
forces and its proxy SLA out of the country.
</P>
<P>
Jezzine, just north of the zone, has been under control of the
militia since 1985.
</P>
<P>
Although Israeli warplanes provided air cover, the retreating
SLA met with Hezbollah's intensified attacks, in which three
militiamen were killed and another wounded in the past two days.
</P>
<P>
Israeli forces retaliated by staging dozens of air raids on
Hezbollah targets close to the withdrawal route, wounding three
Syrian workers and a Lebanese woman.
</P>
<P>
The escalating tensions prompted the United States to send out
appeals to Syria, the main power broker in Lebanon, Lebanon and
Israel for stringent restraint so that the withdrawal would be
completed smoothly. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
