<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ugandan Depositors of Closed Banks Assured of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan President Yoweri Museveni
has assured depositors of closed banks that they would get back
their money.
</P>
<P>
In his State of Nation Address delivered at the opening of the
fourth session of the Parliament here Wednesday afternoon, the
president said that there will have to be an audit to establish
what is owed to depositors.
</P>
<P>
On the recent closure of some commercial banks, Museveni said
that only banks which adhere to the regulations governing banking
will be allowed to exist.
</P>
<P>
He rejected any attempt to politicize the closure of banks,
saying that the banks were closed because they were insolvent and
not for any other reason.
</P>
<P>
The Bank of Uganda has closed the International Credit Bank,
Transafrica Bank, Greenland Bank and the Cooperative Bank because
of mismanagement and insolvency in the last 10 months, leaving
many depositors of these banks crying for their money.
</P>
<P>
The closure of banks sent waves of panic among the general
public who do not know which bank is safe and sound.
</P>
<P>
The government, however, regards this as an indication that the
banking sector is getting healthier and better for the economy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
