<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Giant Company to Close Down Platinum Projects in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 2 (Xinhua) -- International mining giant Broken
Hill Proprietary Company Limited (BHP) Wednesday announced in
Harare that it is pulling out of the Hartley and Mhondoro platinum
joint ventures in Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
The Australian company cited negative cash flows experienced
since operation started in 1996 as the major reason for the
pull-out.
</P>
<P>
President of BHP in Zimbabwe John Grubb told a press conference
that operational and financial under-performance at Hartley
platinum, 80 km west of the capital, was primarily caused by the
unstable ground conditions.
</P>
<P>
He said this resulted in expensive safety problem, loss of
reserves and the unacceptable dilution of ore.
</P>
<P>
He said the company was consulting with the Zimbabwean
government and other interested parties on the fate of 3,573
workers and about 800 contract workers.
</P>
<P>
The platinum project began in 1996 as the largest single
investment since the country got independence in 1980.
</P>
<P>
Grubb said BHP had put in 585 million U.S. dollars and had only
realized 40 million U.S. dollars revenue on sales.
</P>
<P>
"This is purely a geological problem which has affected the
quality of the ore and caused us to spend more money on safety
measures," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
