<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 18:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Water Shortage Affects Iraqi Agriculture: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Iraq warned on Wednesday that the
severe shortage of water now facing the country will dangerously
affect its agriculture.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi Irrigation Undersecretary Abdul Jabbar Salman told a
news conference that the irrigation of Iraqi agriculture relies
heavily on rivers and canals which are in urgent need of
dredging.
</P>
<P>
Salman said the silt deposited in the riverbeds makes it
difficult for water to reach cultivated lands.
</P>
<P>
He said that Iraq needs 700 excavators to dredge these rivers
and canals, adding that Iraq has only 200 excavators, and they
are in poor conditions and need repairing.
</P>
<P>
He criticized the U.N. Sanctions Committee for delaying and
hindering the approval of contracts concluded by the Irrigation
Ministry, adding that only 27 contracts out of 70 were approved
by the committee.
</P>
<P>
A total of 113 million U.S. dollars were allocated for the
Irrigation Ministry in the five phases of the U.N. oil-for-food
program, said Salman, adding that only 23 million dollars worth
of contracts had been approved by the Sanctions Committee.
</P>
<P>
These contracts were signed with foreign companies to purchase
equipment, machines, pumps and spare parts that are badly needed
for the agriculture sector, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
