<DOCNO> XIE19990603.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Government Will Not Control Prices </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 2 (Xinhua) -- The Zimbabwean government will not
announce prices of basic commodities yet because dialog between
industry and other stakeholders is still in progress, a senior
official said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Minister of the Industry and Commerce Ministry Obert
Mpofu said that the government could only resort to price controls
when all other channels have failed.
</P>
<P>
"There is absolutely no need to gazette prices yet because
negotiations are in progress," the Zimbabwe News Agency quoted
Mpofu as saying.
</P>
<P>
Mpofu's remarks came at a time of reports that prices of the
staple maize-meal could increase by about 90 percent.
</P>
<P>
The government discarded the system of price controls in the
early 1990s when it opted for trade liberalization.
</P>
<P>
However, because of escalating prices of basic commodities like
maize- meal, sugar, cooking oil and flour, the government late
last year set up a National Economic Consultative Forum to study
the pricing mechanism for basic commodities in the country to make
food stuffs affordable for consumers.
</P>
<P>
Although the government has not officially announced prices,
threats to do so have been issued by several ministries to force
manufacturers to keep prices of essential goods affordable.
</P>
<P>
The International Monetary Fund and the World Bank have already
 expressed concern at the government's threats to revert to price
controls. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
