<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 18:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Denies Support for Turkish PKK Rebels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Iranian Foreign Ministry spokesman
Hamid Reza Asefi on Wednesday dismissed allegations on Tehran's
support for Turkey's outlawed Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK).
</P>
<P>
Terming the allegations as "baseless," Asefi said that the PKK
had no training base or medical camp on the Iranian soil as raised
during the on-going trial of the PKK leader Abdullah Ocalan, the
Islamic Republic News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
He said that these claims were aimed at tarnishing the cordial
relations existing between Iran and Turkey.
</P>
<P>
There is a good level of understanding and cooperation on
security matters to prevent possible misuse by opposition elements
of either country's territory against the other, he said.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian spokesman said that the arrangements agreed upon
by Iran and Turkey to look into incidents involving security
matters along their common border have continued to be actively
enforced based on mutual trust.
</P>
<P>
Turkey's Ankara Security Court No. 2 on Monday started the
trial of Ocalan on charges of treason, during which Ocalan listed
Iran as one of the collaborators of his group.
</P>
<P>
The PKK has been fighting a 15-year-long war for an independent
Kurdish state in southeastern Turkey, which has claimed over
37,000 lives since August 1984. 
</P>
</TEXT>
