<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNSCOM Recommends Sending Team to Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Chief U.N. weapons inspector
Richard Butler on Wednesday recommended sending a team to Iraq to
dispose of chemical and biological samples left behind in Iraq by
his staff last December.
</P>
<P>
In a letter to the United Nations Security Council, Butler,
Executive Chairman of the United Nations Special Commission in
charge of dismantling Iraq's weapons of mass destruction, said
materials left behind in the laboratory based in Baghdad's Canal
Hotel consists of tiny quantities of chemical agents used to
calibrate equipment and "do not represent a threat, even in case
of an accident."
</P>
<P>
Butler said the materials were left behind because he
originally believed inspectors would gone back to Iraq soon after
the U.S.-led military strikes against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Russia called an emergency meeting of the Security Council
Tuesday to discuss the chemical substances Butler made some
explanations at the meeting, saying that the chemical substances
were of no danger.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council requested Butler submit a report to
give further information about the matter.
</P>
<P>
UNSCOM has not gone back to Iraq to resume its work since
the U.S.-led military strikes against the country last December
and Iraq has vowed not to cooperate with it any longer.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council has been sharply divided on its policy
towards Iraq. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
