<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Macedonia Says More NATO Troops Let in but not for Invasion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Macedonian Prime
Minister Ljubco Georgievski said on Wednesday that Macedonia
agrees to let in up to 30,000 NATO troops, but they should not be
used as an invasion force against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a joint press conference after meeting U.S.
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, Georgievski said that if
NATO decides to launch an invasion against Yugoslavia, Macedonia
will have to debate it.
</P>
<P>
"I have to say that in the Republic of Macedonia, there is a
parliamentary position that its territory should not be used for
attacks on any of the neighbors," he told reporters.
</P>
<P>
He added that other countries on the Balksans had the same
position. "I have to remind you that this is not only Macedonia in
the Balkans that have the same position."
</P>
<P>
Even members of the alliance like Greece and Hungary held the
same position.
</P>
<P>
"If it comes to a change in the NATO position to use ground
troops we will be following the debate, and when the proposal
comes, we will have to put the proposal to the Macedonian
parliament again," he said.
</P>
<P>
Macedonia currently has 16,000 NATO troops on its territory as
a nucleus for the Kosovo force and has been working closely with
the Western alliance in giving shelter to almost 250,000 ethnic
Albanians from Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
"We participate in the operation as no other country does,
first hosting the 16,000 NATO troops and now, according to the
latest request by Mr. Solana (NATO Secretary-General), I believe
that this figure will rise up to 30,000," the prime minister said.
</P>
<P>
Albright assures him that Macedonia will receive more economic
aid from the United States.
</P>
<P>
"For our part we will work to see that Macedonia continues to
receive the full political and economic support it needs in these
very difficult times," Albright added.
</P>
<P>
Albright said a supplemental spending bill passed by Congress
in May provided 22 million U.S. dollars in economic assistance for
Macedonia and 15 million U.S. dollars in technical assistance.
</P>
<P>
U.S. State Department spokesman James Rubin said Macedonian
agreement was important but not a big surprise.
</P>
<P>
"It's part of what's necessary to get the deployment started
early to move quickly in the event that President Milosevic
finally accepts NATO's terms," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
