<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: S. African Poll Peaceful </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 2 (Xinhua) -- The second democratic general
election in South Africa is peaceful although the process has been
slow across the country.
</P>
<P>
The voting is running smoothly and a high turnout is expected
as long queues are reported at polling stations.
</P>
<P>
Fears that a flood of unregistered voters would arrive at
polling stations and demand to vote, did not materialize.
</P>
<P>
Across the country, only small hitches were reported. Some
stations opened late, others did not have voting materials on time
and officials reported problems with their "zip-zip" bar code
scanning equipment.
</P>
<P>
No serious disruptions were reported in so-called "flash
points". Voting in the highly volatile KwaZulu-Natal Midlands was
not overshadowed by two shooting incidents in Richmond overnight,
where two women were killed.
</P>
<P>
In the flash point of Nongoma, an Inkatha Freedom Party
stronghold, voting proceeded peacefully under the watchful eye of
a strong security force contingent deployed in and around the
town, according to South African Press Association (SAPA).
</P>
<P>
In Lydenburg, Mpumalanga, police found and detonated what they
thought was a bomb placed near a school being used as a polling
station but it later turned out to be just a commonplace parcel.
</P>
<P>
In parts of Johannesburg, large numbers of people had begun
queuing from as early as 4:00 a.m. (0200 GMT) and the country's
largest black townships of Soweto were quiet.
</P>
<P>
In Pretoria, there was no sign of voter apathy with long queues
observed in traditionally white areas and black townships alike.
</P>
<P>
In townships like Mamelodi, Soshanguve and Mabopane, voters
said they did not mind queuing for long hours to make their cross.
 Many arrived at 5:00 a.m., and some even spent the night outside
polling stations.
</P>
<P>
Voting got off to a brisk start in the Western Cape although at
some stations ballot papers arrived late.
</P>
<P>
All 1,309 polling stations in the province were open and
functioning by 1:00 p.m. and the police reported that all was well
despite political tension between African National Congress (ANC)
and United Democratic Movement in some areas.
</P>
<P>
In North-West Province, thousands of people stood in queues
long before voting stations opened. A few voting stations in the
Kuruman area opened later than scheduled, but no serious problems
were reported.
</P>
<P>
In the Umtata area of the Transkei in the Eastern Cape, voters
began lining up at polling stations well before they opened.
</P>
<P>
In Free State, all polling stations were in operation by noon,
SAPA quoted provincial electoral officer Chris Mepha as saying.
</P>
<P>
He said since the Free State was a "low-risk" area and a high
level of political tolerance existed, no serious politically
motivated problems were anticipated.
</P>
<P>
President Nelson Mandela made his mark early in the morning at
the Transvaal Automobile Club near his home in Houghton,
Johannesburg.
</P>
<P>
He said the excitement was less intense this time than it was
in 1994. "It is a very wonderful occasion."
</P>
<P>
Later in the morning, during a visit to the Independent
Electoral Commission results center in Pretoria, he praised the
commission, saying that the election appeared to be well prepared.
</P>
<P>
ANC President Thabo Mbeki, who seems set to be the next state
president, cast his vote in Pretoria shortly after 7:00 a.m.
</P>
<P>
The president-in-waiting said that the low level of violence in
the run up to the election was a good omen for a free and fair
outcome.
</P>
<P>
Inkatha Freedom Party leader Mangosuthu Buthelezi, touring
Pretoria voting stations in his capacity as Home Affairs Minister,
said that he was very impressed with the electorate because they
had come out in large numbers to vote.
</P>
<P>
"I am very encouraged by what I see," Buthelezi said. "I would
like to congratulate the voters because they have made me very
proud."
</P>
<P>
The very first result of the vote is expected late Wednesday
night and the final result will be announced by the Independent
Electoral Commission within seven days.
</P>
<P>
South Africa has 22.8 million eligible voters, of whom more
than 18 million had registered for Wednesday's vote.
</P>
<P>
At stake are 400 seats in the National Assembly and seats in
provincial legislatures, which vary from province to province with
the population.
</P>
<P>
South Africa is using the electoral system called proportional
representation, under which a political party's representation in
parliament is in proportion to the percentage of votes it receives
in the election.
</P>
<P>
The state president will be elected by parliamentarians, and
provincial premiers by provincial legislators.
</P>
<P>
Polling stations across the country were opened at 7:00 a.m.
and will be closed at 9:00 p.m.
</P>
<P>
However, according to the Independent Electoral Commission
regulations, voters already in the queue by 9:00 p.m. will be
allowed to vote. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
