<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. African Voters Queuing After Dark </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Large numbers of voters
continued to queue outside polling stations across South Africa
after dark, but officials ruled out an extension of the poll to
accommodate late comers, South African Press Association (SAPA)
reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Independent Electoral Commission spokesman Victor Dlamini said
in Pretoria that polls would be kept open for voters already in
queues by the 9:00 p.m. (1900 GMT) deadline to allow them to cast
their ballots, but late comers would not be admitted.
</P>
<P>
The electoral official confirmed long queues were still waiting
to vote, particularly in densely populated areas in Gauteng and
KwaZulu-Natal, and said the police and army would be requested to
beef up security after dark outside these stations.
</P>
<P>
"We do expect that by 9:00 p.m. we will be dealing with the
tail end of the process," he said.
</P>
<P>
After nightfall, thousands of people were still queuing outside
polling stations in Alexandra, a large black township north of
Johannesburg.
</P>
<P>
SAPA quoted an electoral commission presiding officer as saying
that the process was time consuming as illiterate people needed
help when casting their vote.
</P>
<P>
There were also security concerns as Alexandra is one of the
most dangerous areas in the country.
</P>
<P>
Reports from around two-thirds of the 14,650 polling stations
throughout the country at 4:00 p.m. showed around 24 percent of
the country's 18.3 million registered voters had cast their
ballots, and optimistic electoral officials said the first results
would start coming in by 11:00 p.m. (2100 GMT), just two hours
after the scheduled close of polls.
</P>
<P>
Officials of the Independent Electoral Commission and several
political leaders interpreted the long queues as a sign of a high
turnout, and observers called the poll peaceful.
</P>
<P>
Safety and Security Minister Sydney Mufamadi said not a single
incident of poll-related violence had marred the country's second
democratic polls by 6:00 p.m. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
