<HEADLINE> Barak Reiterates Wish to Include Likud in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister-elect
Ehud Barak Wednesday reiterated that he wants to include the
right-wing Likud Party in his new government.
</P>
<P>
Barak made the remarks after meeting with Ariel Sharon,
Likud's temporary leader, in Tel Aviv over forming a broad-based
coalition government.
</P>
<P>
In a statement, Barak noted that he will resume the peace
process immediately after he sets up the new government.
</P>
<P>
He also said that he wishes to meet U.S. President Bill
Clinton and leaders of other Middle East countries immediately
following the establishment of the government.
</P>
<P>
Sharon, outgoing Foreign Minister of the Likud government,
said that his meeting with Barak was constructive and
negotiations between the two parties will continue.
</P>
<P>
In Israel's May 17 elections, Barak, leader of the left-wing
One Israel coalition, won a landslide victory over outgoing Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
Barak has said that he wants to form a wide coalition
government with the support of more than 90 Knesset (parliament)
members.
</P>
<P>
Likud, which won 19 seats in the 120-seat Knesset, is still
split over whether to join the coalition.
</P>
<P>
Some Likud officials said the party will be given a chance to
exert impact on the final-status talks with the Palestinians if it
joins the coalition, while others insisted that it could be
easier for the party to expedite a recovery program as an
opposition force. 
</P>
</TEXT>
