<HEADLINE> Poor Living Conditions in Ethiopian Urban Center </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, June 2 (Xinhua) -- An Ethiopian government
official said here Wednesday that the proportion of the people who
have access to piped clean water, regular garbage disposal and
health care facilities in Ethiopian urban centers is low.
</P>
<P>
Less than half of all households in 10 current regional state
capitals have access to potable water, General Manager of the
Ethiopian Urban Planning Institute, Solomon Kassaye told the
on-going six-day workshop on integrated strategic planning by
urban local authorities in eastern and southern Africa.
</P>
<P>
"Only a quarter of the units are in neighborhood equipped with
drainage infrastructures and a third lacked private or shared
water facilities," the Ethiopian News Agency quoted Solomon as
saying.
</P>
<P>
The general manager said with rapid annual urban growth rate
ranging from five to six percent and a stagnant income, urban
poverty has become a serious phenomenon in Ethiopia.
</P>
<P>
Available jobs in labor market are scanty and as a result
unemployment is extremely high, Solomon said, adding that "at
present unemployment rate in the capital is about 38 percent."
</P>
<P>
Representatives and pertinent officials from Kenya, Tanzania,
Uganda, Zambia, Zimbabwe, Mozambique, Malawi, South Africa,
Namibia and Ethiopia, are attending the workshop which will end on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The workshop is aimed at enhancing the technical and management
 capacities of participants dealing with urban policy issues.
</P>
</TEXT>
