<HEADLINE> Oman, UAE Sign Gas Memorandum </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Oman Wednesday signed a gas
memorandum of understanding with the United Arab Emirates (UAE).
</P>
<P>
Oman signed the deal with UAE Offets Group (UOG), which will
enable it to receive an expected 300 to 600 million standard
cubic feet (9 to 18 million cubic meters) of gas a day.
</P>
<P>
"The signing marks the start of a process aimed at formalizing
a long-term arrangement to supply Oman with an anticipated 300 to
600 standard cubic feet of gas per day," said a statement issued
by the investment group UOG.
</P>
<P>
The memorandum was signed in Oman's capital Muscat by Omani
Minister of Petroleum and Natural Gas Mohammed al-Ramhi and UOG
Chairman Mohammed Saif Al Mazroui.
</P>
<P>
"The gas will ensure that we can meet anticipated demand for
energy in Oman well into the next century," said al-Ramhi.
</P>
<P>
"Through security of energy supply we can create a platform
for encouraging local business to expand and for attracting
investment into Oman from overseas," he added.
</P>
<P>
The supply of gas to Oman will be part of the UOG's Dolphin
Regional Gas Network project which is a portfolio of gas-related
activities.
</P>
<P>
Oman's involvement in the project will include the
construction of pipelines in the country.
</P>
<P>
UOG said the Dolphin project would require investments
estimated at 8 to 10 billion U.S. dollars over the next six to
seven years.
</P>
<P>
It involves the development of Qatar's gas plants and is aimed
at transporting gas from Qatar to the whole region through new
gas distribution networks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
