<HEADLINE> Romania's Main Opposition Criticizes NATO For Bombing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, June 2 (Xinhua) -- The NATO's bombings were not an
adequate way to solve the Kosovo crisis, said on Wednesday Ion
Iliescu, president of the Party of Social Democracy of Romania.
</P>
<P>
The leader of the main Opposition made the remark on his
meeting with Lord Russel-Johnston, the visiting President of the
Parliamentary Assembly of the Council of Europe. The meeting
occasioned the two dignitaries an opinion exchange about the
Kosovo conflict and the NATO's intervention in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
Iliescu stressed that he was disappointed with the fact that
the military operations in Yugoslavia had taken place in the name
of certain principles. "We expected NATO to behave differently",
the former President of Romania said, adding that worldwide there
were much more serious situations than that in Kosovo and NATO did
not bother to interfere.
</P>
<P>
Lord Russell-Johnston did not share Iliescu's views. He
resumed, once again, the stance the British and U.S. officials had
previously voiced on the Kosovo topic.
</P>
<P>
The Yugoslav war's effects, the stop in the traffic on the
Danube and in the billateral commercial ties add now to the
economic hardships Romania are facing, Iliescu also said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
