<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> COMESA Moving Fast Into Free Trade Area </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Secretary-General of the Common
Market for Eastern and Southern Africa (COMESA), Erastus Mwencha,
said here Wednesday that the sub-region is moving fast into a
free-trade area without any tariff or non-tariff barriers in trade
of both goods and services.
</P>
<P>
Mwencha said this at a regional seminar on competition policy,
trade and development, which is aimed at ensuring efficiency
autonomy and flexibility in the enforcement of competition law and
policy in the member states.
</P>
<P>
The secretary-general said that in view of encouraging cross
border investment within the sub-region, the COMESA members have
set October 31, 2000, as the target date for achieving a free
trade area and the year 2004 for transforming into a customs
union.
</P>
<P>
Mwencha disclosed that by the end of May 1999, three countries
had already reduced their tariff by 90 percent, seven countries by
80 percent, one country by 70 percent, and other three by 60
percent while a further two have been allowed not to effect
reductions until the year 2000 due to their unique economic
situation.
</P>
<P>
The regional seminar is funded by both the United Nations
Development Fund and the United Nations Conference for Trade and
Development. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
