<HEADLINE> Kenya Values Sino-Kenyan Economic Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Kenya values its ecomonic
cooperation and trade with China, Kenyan Minister of Industrial
Cooperation Andrew Kiptoon said here Wednesday when meeting a
Chinese business and trade delegation.
</P>
<P>
"Over the years, Kenya has benefited from several
Chinese-funded projects, the most remarkable one being the Moi
International Sports Complex in Nairobi," Kiptoon said.
</P>
<P>
Kiptoon welcomed China's plan of establishing a trade and
investment center in Nairobi, saying that "we encourage the
Chinese friends to realize the proposal and even consider setting
up enterprises in Kenya."
</P>
<P>
"Kenyans have information that the Chinese technology is
appropriate to Kenya and the costs are relatively lower than those
from other parts of the world," he said. "We hope Chinese friends
to take advantage of the industrialization process which Kenya is
undergoing."
</P>
<P>
He also appealed Chinese businessmen to help Kenya improve its
irrigation technology and development of herbal medicine on
malaria, a tropical disease and the top killer in Kenya.
</P>
<P>
Xu Bingjin, head of the delegation organized by the Chinese
Ministry of Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation, said during
the talks that the Sino- Kenyan economic cooperation and trade
have enjoyed a sustained expansion, with a trade volume in 1998
standing at 120 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
"China has provided Kenya with assistance of 564 million yuan
(about 70 million dollars) without setting any political
pre-conditions," Xu said.
</P>
<P>
Xu also said that there is great potential in the bilateral
economic cooperation and trade, adding that the Chinese government
has encouraged its entrepreneurs to invest in Kenya in forms of
equipment, technology, management or setting up processing and
assembling projects. 
</P>
</TEXT>
