<DOCNO> XIE19990603.0029 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank Says More Efforts Needed to Better </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 2 (Xinhua) -- After several decades of falling
poverty in East Asia, the World Bank reported Wednesday that the
financial crisis has caused a substantial surge in the region's
poverty rate, and recommended that international financial rescue
packages be better balanced to cushion the poor from the worst
effects of crises.
</P>
<P>
"Progress in income poverty reduction has probably stalled in
the latter half of the 1990s amongst large groups of the poor,
with the exception of China," the bank said in a report entitled
"World Bank Poverty Update".
</P>
<P>
"In all three key areas of income poverty, health and basic
education, there will need to be a substantial increase in
progress, compared with trends of the late 1990s, if the
international development targets are to be achieved," the report
said.
</P>
<P>
According to the World Bank, in 1987, 1.2 billion people lived
on less than one U.S. dollar per day; in 1993, that number was
closer to 1.3 billion. In 1999, if the proportion of people living
in poverty has remained the same as in 1993, there could be 1.5
billion people living in abject poverty at the dawn of the new
millennium.
</P>
<P>
Latest survey results based on national poverty lines, not the
one dollar per day lines, confirmed the impact of the financial
crisis on the poor in East Asia has been very severe, the bank
said.
</P>
<P>
Estimates for Indonesia indicate an increase of around 10
percentage points in the incidence of poverty, corresponding to
something like 20 million newly poor people, the equivalent of a
medium-sized country. Significant increases in poverty took place
in urban Korea, and to a lesser extent in Thailand.
</P>
<P>
The combined effect of lower commodity prices, conflict, and in
some cases, bad weather has been to cut growth in Sub-Saharan
Africa. The growth of gross domestic product (GDP) in 1998 appears
to have below the rate of population growth, implying a decline in
per capita income in the region.
</P>
<P>
The prospects for Latin America are clouded by the crisis in
Brazil, but per capita GDP growth was significant in 1997 and
still positive, albeit lower, in 1998, the bank said.
</P>
<P>
Sharp declines in growth and increases in poverty are also
anticipated in Russia, the Ukraine, and Romania. Negative GDP per
capita growth and an increase in poverty are also expected in the
Middle East and North Africa.
</P>
<P>
"In sum, the global picture that emerges at the end of the
1990s is one of stalled progress, as a result of the East Asian
crisis, rising numbers of poor people in India, continued rises in
Sub-Saharan Africa, and a sharp worsening in Europe and Central
Asia," Michael Walton, director of the World Bank's Poverty
Reduction and Economic Management, said at a press conference.
</P>
<P>
Given the human impact of the crisis on the lives of millions
of people in East Asia and other developing and transition
countries, the World Bank stressed that rescue packages must be
better designed in the future to protect the poor, the sick, and
the elderly from the worst effects of crisis.
</P>
<P>
"Without an adequate safety net in place before a crisis hits,
the poor are likely to be hurt disproportionately. Accordingly,
setting up safety nets in good times may be the only effective way
to protect the poor during crises," said the bank. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990603.0030 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
