<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Parties Invited to Formulate Election </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's Electoral Supervisory
Commission (ESC) is inviting all political parties to a meeting
this month to formulate a code for parliamentary elections next
year.
</P>
<P>
This is the first time local political parties have been asked
to cooperate in efforts to ensure elections are held
democratically.
</P>
<P>
ESC Chairman Peter Hatendi Wednesday told the Zimbabwe News
Agency that political parties needed to agree and adhere to some
democratic electoral principles to ensure free participation of
both candidates and voters.
</P>
<P>
He acknowledged that his commission did not have statutory
powers to compel parties to draw up the code of conduct.
</P>
<P>
But he appealed to politicians' "morality" to strive for peace
"before, during and after polling and declaration of results" in
the municipal elections scheduled for August and parliamentary
polls expected early next year.
</P>
<P>
He said the drive behind the commission's invitation to parties
was the violent trends in Zimbabwe elections which, judging from
the few incidents already witnessed, were feared to increase and
become more dangerous during the forthcoming elections.
</P>
<P>
The commission predicted that the forthcoming elections would
be more competitive than previous ones. But this, Hatendi said,
could be verified with the response from the parties to his
invitation.
</P>
<P>
The parties are expected to have registered for the meeting by
June 16 after which the date of the meeting would be set.
</P>
<P>
"Such a meeting could allow parties to open up and iron out
some of the issues that have been sticking in previous elections
which were boycotted by some parties," he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
