<HEADLINE> Nobel Laurreate: No Difference Between Hitler and NATO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Nobel prize winner for literature
Alexander Solzhenitsin on Monday condemned the NATO airstrikes
against Yugoslavia, saying he sees no difference between NATO's
behavior and that of Hitler.
</P>
<P>
"Yugoslavia shows where humanity is headed. In terms of
morality we are on the way down, not up," the Interfax news agency
quoted the Russian writer as saying.
</P>
<P>
The International Court in The Hague, which has indicted
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic for war crimes, "has for a
long time been a circus, I believe, because they do what they are
told to do... I do not respect the International Court in the
Hague because it has been showing bias for decades," Solzhenitsin
said.
</P>
<P>
"I can see that under some pretext a European country has been
suffering destructive strikes for a third month before the eyes of
humanity," he said. "International law has been cast away, the
United Nations has been cast away."
</P>
<P>
"NATO is teaching the entire planet a lesson, saying 'This is
the way we will punish.' NATO wants to impose its order on the
world and Yugoslavia is needed as a terrible example."
Solzhenitsin said.
</P>
<P>
The Yugoslav crisis will not lead to World War III, "but may
lead to NATO tyranny over the planet," the author said.
</P>
<P>
Solzhenitsin, 80, was awarded the Nobel prize for literature in
1970. 
</P>
</TEXT>
