<HEADLINE> Three Iraqi Civilians Injured in U.S. Bombardment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Three Iraqi civilians were injured
on Wednesday in the U.S. and British bombardment of civilian
facilities and military camps, an Iraqi military spokesman
announced.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that at 11:00 (0700 GMT), 11 formations of
enemy warplanes coming from Turkish airspace violated northern
Iraqi airspace over the provinces of Dohuk, Neineva and Erbil.
</P>
<P>
He said that the enemy formations bombed civilian facilities
and military camps in Neineva province, injuring three civilians,
adding that Iraqi anti-aircraft units repulsed the enemy planes
at 14:05 (1005 GMT).
</P>
<P>
Thirty-three formations of enemy planes coming from Saudi and
Kuwaiti bases violated southern Iraqi airspace over Thi-Qar,
Misan, Basra and Muthana provinces at 11:03 (0703 GMT) and 16:53
(1253 GMT), said the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
He added that since the U.S. and British airstrikes against
Iraq last December, their warplanes have made 5,933 sorties in
the so-called southern no-fly zone and 1,478 sorties in the
northern no-fly zone.
</P>
<P>
The U.S.-led western allies imposed the no-fly zones in Iraq
following the 1991 Gulf War with a claimed aim of protecting the
Kurds in the north and the Shiite Muslims in the south from
"Baghdad's suppressions."
</P>
<P>
Since last December's U.S. and British bombardment of Iraq,
their warplanes have been regularly attacking Iraqi military and
civilian targets in the no-fly zones, causing severe civilian
casualties and property damage."
</P>
<P>
Iraq has declared that it does not recognize these restricted
zones and vowed to continue confronting any allied plane violating
its airspace. 
</P>
</TEXT>
