<HEADLINE> Outlook for Wheat Trade in 1999/2000: IGC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON June 2 (Xinhua) - World wheat trade has been fairly
static for some 3 years, largely as a result of better than
anticipated supplies and slower than anticipated consumption
growth in several major importers, the International Grains
Council (IGC) said.
</P>
<P>
In its latest issue of Grain Market Report, the IGC said, some
recovery is forecast in 1999/00, largely as a result of crop
shortfalls in Near East Asia, especially Iran and due to some
expected tightening of supplies in China.
</P>
<P>
The global figure could approach 100 m.tons, up from 93.5m.
estimated for 1998/99. The amount of wheat provided is likely to
fall from the above average amount provided in 1998/99, although
in some cases shipment are likely to continue into the next year,
The IGC added.
</P>
<P>
A sharp decline in the level of carry-out stocks in some major
importing countries would normally increase the likelihood of
imports. China, in particular, was able to build up stocks
following bumper 1996 and 1997 crops, according to the IGC.
</P>
<P>
While China is unlikely to resort to large-scale wheat
purchases in 1999/00, imports are forecast to increase to some 4 m.
tons in order to keep pace with slowly rising use, the report
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
