<HEADLINE> UK Manufacturing Shows Recovery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON June 2 (Xinhua) - Strong evidence has emerged of a
recovery in UK manufacturing, with healthy consumer demand helping
to lift companies' output, according to a leading survey
released Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
However, in spite of the boost for output, the activity index
composited by the Chartered Institute of Purchasing and Supply
(CIPS), stayed below the break-even level.
</P>
<P>
The index rose to 49.4 from 48.1 in April on a scale where any
number below 50 means recession. Nevertheless, it is the seventh
consecutive improvement.
</P>
<P>
The CIPS survey said orders, both at home and for export, were
growing. Output growth accelerated last month and is growing at
its fastest rate for almost two years.
</P>
<P>
The survey is the latest in a string of surveys to suggest
economic growth is on course for recovery, following interest rate
cuts.
</P>
<P>
The institute said the increase in manufacturing output in May,
the second consecutive monthly rise, was driven almost entirely by
higher production of consumer goods.
</P>
<P>
Peter Thomson, CIPS director general, said an improvement in
the global economy had led to an increase in export orders despite
a further appreciation of sterling. 
</P>
</TEXT>
