<HEADLINE> UK Tabloid Newspaper Demanded Apology over Sophie Photo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 2 (Xinhua) -- The British press watchdog, the
Press Complaints Commission (PCC), ordered The Sun on Wednesday to
repeat its apology for publishing a topless picture of Prince
Edward's fiancee Sophie Rhys-Jones.
</P>
<P>
The decade-old photograph of Rhys-Jones appeared in last
Wednesday's newspaper -- ahead of the couple's marriage later this
month.
</P>
<P>
The Buckingham Palace called the publication "premeditated
cruelty", and made a formal protest to the Press Complaints
Commission hours after the paper hit the streets.
</P>
<P>
It called the story in the newspaper a "gross invasion of
privacy", and made the complaint under section three of the
industry's code of practice, regarding privacy.
</P>
<P>
The next day after the photograph appeared, The Sun issued a
full-page apology to Rhys-Jones, admitting that it had been wrong
to publish the picture, but denying it had acted with "deliberate
cruelty".
</P>
<P>
The paper also announced that it had decided to donate all
profits from the syndication of its pictures to charities of her
choice.
</P>
<P>
Disc jockey Kara Noble, who took the photograph, was sacked
from London commercial radio station Heart 106.2 after the photo
was published. 
</P>
</TEXT>
