<HEADLINE> U.S. Says Ball in Belgrade's Court Despite Difference </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 2 (Xinhua) -- The United States said on
Wednesday that the ball is now in Belgrade's court although the
West-Russian plan on Kosovo has not resolved all differences on
what kind of peacekeeping force would go into Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Russian envoy Viktor Chernomyrdin and Finnish President Martti
Ahtisaari for the European Union, will fly to Belgrade on
Wednesday to put their ideas to Yugoslav leader Slobodan
Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
"We think the areas of agreement are sufficiently large, broad
and deep for a joint trip (by Chernomyrdin and Ahtisaari). The
international community is as united as it can possibly be," U.S.
State Department spokesman James Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
"We are pleased that arrangements have been made for them to
travel together to Belgrade and present a solution.
</P>
<P>
"The big 'if' is whether this united front -- the United
States, Russia and the European Union -- will achieve the
necessary answers from President Milosevic. But the ball is
clearly in his (Milosevic's) court," he added.
</P>
<P>
However, the spokesman said that differences still remain
between Russia and the West on the international force that is
to be deployed in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
In Bonn, Chernomyrdin said that the NATO troops will be under
NATO command, while the Russian troops will be controlled by the
Russian command.
</P>
<P>
Rubin said it was "an open question" whether Russia would
participate in sending peacekeepers under NATO command and with
NATO at its core as demanded by the allies.
</P>
<P>
"We insist that the force have NATO command and control and a
NATO structure. The open question is whether Russia can find a way
to participate."
</P>
<P>
But the Clinton administration would not object to adoption of
a resolution by the United Nations to endorse the peacekeeping
plan after a settlement to protect returning refugees, the
spokesman said. 
</P>
