<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. New Home Sales Rise Strongly in April </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 2 (Xinhua) -- U.S. sales of new homes
increased a strong 9.2 percent in April, the Commerce Department
reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The increase in sales of new single-family homes followed four
straight months of declines, the Department said. The big rise
pushed sales of new homes to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of
978,000 units last month, the second highest level on record. The
all-time high was a sales rate of 985,000 units set last November.
</P>
<P>
The April's 9.2 percent gain caught analysts by surprise. Many
of them have been predicting a slowdown in this sector because
mortgage rates have been climbing up in recent weeks. A national
survey of mortgage rates showed them hitting 7.23 percent for the
past two weeks, the highest level in 18 months.
</P>
<P>
However, existing home sales declined in April by 3.3 percent,
that drop was from a record high set in March.
</P>
<P>
The Wednesday's report also showed that the surge in demand was
accompanied by a rise in prices. The median price of all new homes
sold last month climbed 3 percent to a record 159,500 U.S.
dollars.
</P>
<P>
All regions of the country except the West enjoyed strong
increases in sales last month.
</P>
<P>
In the Midwest, sales rose 33.5 percent to an annual rate of
211,000 units. Sales were up 17.1 percent to a rate of 89,000
units in the Northeast and climbed 7.5 percent to a rate of
429,000 units in the South.
</P>
<P>
The West, jumping 22.9 percent in March, suffered a drop of 5.3
percent in April to an annual rate of 249,000 units.
</P>
<P>
The April's strong pace of sales meant that it would take only
3.7 months to exhaust the existing supply of unsold homes, a
record low for this figure. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
