U.S.-led NATO staged unabated bombing in Yugoslavia for more than
70 days, a U.N. statement said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The statement, issued by a U.N. spokesman, said, "At the
invitation of His Holiness Pope John Paul II, the
Secretary-General is travelling to Rome to meet with the Pope, in
order to assess the situation in the Balkans and the prospects for
resolving the crisis and building peace in the region."
</P>
<P>
The meeting will take place in the Vatican at 1:00 p.m. (11:00
GMT) on Thursday, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
"The Secretary-General remains firmly committed to promoting a
solution to the Kosovo crisis that allows refugees and displaced
persons to return swiftly to their homes and that enables
inhabitants of Kosovo and the region to live in conditions of
peace and security with full respect for the civil, political and
human rights of all," said the statement.
</P>
<P>
"He sees his meeting with His Holiness as an important
opportunity to exchange views on the moral and political issues
underling the crisis in Kosovo," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The Pope sent a personal letter to Annan in April to invite the
U.N. chief to discuss the Kosovo conflict, which broke out in
February last year after ethnic Albanians have been fighting with
Serbs for independence.
</P>
<P>
The Pope has made several calls for peace in Yugoslavia since
NATO, without the authorization of the U.N. Security Council,
unilaterally began its bombing campaign on March 24 in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
The meeting will be taking place as the international
community is calling upon NATO to stop the bombing, which
violates the U.N. Charter and international law immediately to
give peace a chance. 
