<HEADLINE> Bangladeshi Govt Urged to Resist "Conspiracy" Against Its Industrialization </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, June 2 (Xinhua) -- A Bangladeshi industrialist on
Wednesday urged the government to beware of an "international
conspiracy" against the industrialization of the country.
</P>
<P>
Salman F. Rahman, chairman of the Bangladesh Textile Mills
Association (BTMA), said some of the country's development
partners while pressing for opening up its economy for the private
sector only look after the interest of the private sector of their
own countries.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference jointly organized by five associations of
the country's textiles sector, including the Bangladesh Garment
Manufacturers and Exporters Association, the BTMA chairman,
without naming anybody, said those donors even try to tarnish the
image and capacity of the local private entrepreneurs by leveling
charges of incapability and insincerity against them.
</P>
<P>
Reiterating the top-most importance of establishing an adequate
number of backward linkage industries to help the success of the
country's garment and textile industries after the year 2004,
Rahman censured a recent study of the International Finance
Corporation (IFC) on Bangladesh.
</P>
<P>
The study on the textiles sector of Bangladesh carried out by
the IFC, an affiliate of the World Bank, said the country does not
need backward linkage industries, and the consultants of the
report asked the IFC not to invest in Bangladesh for the purpose.
</P>
<P>
He called on the government and the people to help protect the
national interest in this regard.
</P>
<P>
The textiles sector has become the largest foreign exchange
earner of the country, which contributes to about 70 percent of
the country's total export earnings. 
</P>
</TEXT>
