<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Quarter of Voters Turn out in S. Africa By </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 2 (Xinhua) -- More than 4.2 million, or 23
percent, of South Africa's registered voters had cast their
ballots by 4 p.m. (1400 GMT) Wednesday, provisional statistics
released by the Independent Electoral Commission (IEC) showed.
</P>
<P>
The figure was based on information received from only 9,591 of
the 14,640 polling stations countrywide which made contact with
the IEC's operation center in Pretoria.
</P>
<P>
A total of 5,090 polling stations had yet to report to the IEC,
and voting tallies from these centers could therefore not be
included, officials said.
</P>
<P>
Gauteng, with more than 4.2 million registered voters, the
highest in the country, had the lowest turnout by 4 p.m., with
18.5 percent. In contrast, the Northern Cape, with the lowest
number of registered voters in the country, had the highest
turnout with 30.64 percent.
</P>
<P>
The election is running peacefully across the country although
the process is rather slow. In some places, voters had to wait for
hours before they could cast their ballots.
</P>
<P>
The first results of the vote are expected late Wednesday
night. 
</P>
</TEXT>
