<HEADLINE> Security Council Meets on Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 2 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Security Council on
Wednesday morning met in a closed-door session to hear briefing by
a U.N. fact-finding mission which was sent into Kosovo, a Yugoslav
province, to assess humanitarian situation in Yugoslavia, which
has been under intensified NATO bombing for more than 70 days.
</P>
<P>
Sergio Vieira de Mello, U.N. under-secretary-general for
humanitarian affairs, briefed the Security Council on his mission
to Kosovo and other parts of Yugoslavia. U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan was present at the Council meeting.
</P>
<P>
Speaking in Kosovo in late May, de Mello said his mission had
seen "pretty systematic destruction or burning of private
property. The U.N. team identified the main problems there as the
destruction of basic services, the closure of educational
facilities and unemployment.
</P>
<P>
Annan decided on May 4 to set up the U.N. mission to assess the
humanitarian needs of the people in Kosovo and other parts of
Yugoslavia. The U.N. team is the first of its kinds since the
U.S.-led NATO began its bombing of Yugoslavia on March 24.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. team, composed of some 15 people from a number of U.N.
agencies, visited Serbia, Kosovo and Montenegro during the 10-day
assessment mission, and held talks with the Yugoslav leaders in
Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
De Mello is expected to give a press conference here on
Wednesday afternoon on his mission to Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, de Mello said that he would present the mission's
findings and recommendations to Annan and to the Security Council.
</P>
</TEXT>
