<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NATO's Depleted Uranium Weapons Threaten Danger </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 2 (Xinhua) -- The clouds of radioactive dust
created by the depleted uranium weapons which NATO is using in the
Balkans threaten soldiers on both sides and ordinary Yugoslav
people, Britain's New Scientist magazine warned on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Depleted uranium, a radioactive heavy metal, is the waste left
over when the isotope uranium-235 is extracted from natural
uranium to fuel nuclear power stations and build nuclear bombs.
</P>
<P>
Mike Thorne, a uranium expert from AEA Technology, which is
formerly part of the UK Atomic Energy Authority, told New
Scientist that as an alpha-emitter, depleted uranium poses a
similar risk to plutonium if it gets inside the body.
</P>
<P>
Chemically, depleted uranium poses a great threat to the
kidneys, where high concentrations can lead to organ failure.
</P>
<P>
But according to Thorne, even small amounts could have subtle
but ill-understood effects.
</P>
<P>
As such, even the tiniest amounts of uranium could "cause cell
damage that marginally increases the risk of cancer", the magazine
said.
</P>
<P>
Depleted uranium was used for the first time in Gulf war in
1991. U.S. and British veterans believed exposure to it is one of
the causes of Gulf War Syndrome that has afflicted thousands of
soldiers afterward. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990603.0055 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
