<HEADLINE> One Million New High-tech Jobs Added to U.S.Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, June 2 (Xinhua) -- More than a million new jobs
have been created by the U.S. high-tech industry since 1993,
according to an analytical report issued Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The new report from the American Electronics Association (AEA)
said that the U.S. high-tech industry employed 4.8 million workers
in 1998, making it one of the nation's largest industries.
</P>
<P>
States leading the job growth were Texas, California, Georgia,
Colorado and Washington, indicating the tech-fueled economic boom
has spread far beyond Silicon Valley.
</P>
<P>
"Throughout the mid-1990s," said the report, "the U.S.
high-tech industry has mushroomed, becoming the significant new
component of U.S. business growth." In fact, all but nine states
created new technology jobs between 1996 and 1997.
</P>
<P>
California on the West Coast is by far the U.S. technology
powerhouse, employing 784,000 workers in 1997 and adding 66,000
net new jobs between 1990 and 1997. But California's growth rate
of nine percent during the period lagged behind the growth in
technology jobs of several other states.  
</P>
</TEXT>
