<HEADLINE> FDI Rises in East Europe, Falls in Russia: U.N. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Foreign direct investment
(FDI) flows into Central and Eastern Europe grew to a new high of
16 billion U.S. dollars in 1998 from 13 billion dollars in 1997,
according to U.N. figures released Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In contrast, Russia received FDI of 2 billion dollars in 1998,
falling dramatically from 6 billion dollars a year earlier, the
United Nations Conference on Trade and Development (UNCTAD) said.
</P>
<P>
In 1998, FDI into Central and Eastern Europe other than Russia
was heavily dominated by investors from Western Europe, who
captured 72 percent of the total, against a share of 9 percent for
investors from the United Sates, UNCTAD said.
</P>
<P>
FDI into Russia in 1998 fell back to its 1995 level, following
the country's general economic downturn and the drying up of
privatization-related inflows, the U.N. agency said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
