<DOCNO> XIE19990603.0062 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Palestinians Angry Over Jewish Settlement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HEBRON, West Bank, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Declaring it a "Day of
Anger," Palestinians held demonstrations in the West Bank and the
Gaza Strip Thursday to protest against intensified Jewish
settlement expansion over the last few months.
</P>
<P>
Scores of Palestinian youngsters threw stones at Israeli
soldiers, who responded by firing rubber-bullets towards them.
</P>
<P>
This scene, on the Bab el Zawieh street linking the
Israeli-controlled and Palestinian-controlled areas in this
divided West Bank city, could be seen at many other places
throughout the West Bank and Gaza Strip Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The marches were organized by the Palestinian National
Authority (PNA).
</P>
<P>
The largest demonstration took place at a junction outside the
Gush Katif, a bloc of Jewish settlements in the southern Gaza
Strip, where about 1,000 Palestinians blocked the main road and
chanted "settlers get out."
</P>
<P>
Despite the stone-throwing and rubber bullets-firing, all the
demonstrations were relatively peaceful. In some places,
Palestinian police pushed back marchers who tried to hurl stones
at Israeli soldiers.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian officials said by holding the marches, they were
sending a message to Israeli Prime Minister-elect Ehud Barak,
urging him to halt the settlement expansion which they said will
"kill the peace process" if not halted immediately.
</P>
<P>
In Hebron, hundreds of Palestinians led by officials from
various Palestinian political groups marched along the main
streets, chanting slogans calling for the end of "Israeli
occupations."
</P>
<P>
Home to about 400 Jewish settlers surrounded by some 120,000
Palestinians, Hebron was divided into Israeli-controlled and
Palestinian-controlled parts under an agreement signed two years
ago.
</P>
<P>
"We will not allow the Israelis to draw up the map of the final
status (of the Palestinian entity) by themselves," said Jamal Al
Shoubake, a Palestinian legislator and spokesman for the Fatah
movement.
</P>
<P>
Since outgoing hard-line Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu was
poised to lose in the May 17 polls, Jewish settlers have stepped
up settlement expansion, fearing that a Barak-led government might
freeze these activities.
</P>
<P>
They have set up the nucleus of several new settlements on West
Bank hilltops and resumed construction at several sites in Arab
East Jerusalem, including Har Homa and Ras al-Amoud.
</P>
<P>
In a move further outraging the Palestinians, the parting
Israeli government approved a plan soon after Netanyahu was
crushed in the elections to expand the borders of the biggest
West Bank settlement Maale Adumin to East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Almost doubling the current size of Maale Adumin, which has a
population of about 22,000, the expansion would form a band of
Israeli-held land in East Jerusalem that cuts the West Bank in
half.
</P>
<P>
Nowadays, more than 150 settlements scatter in the West Bank
and Gaza Strip, effectively destroying the geographic continuity
of the Palestinian areas. The expansion of Maale Adumin would
worsen the situation.
</P>
<P>
Barak, who has pledged to revive the peace talks with the
Palestinians, has kept silence on the increasing settlement
activities since the elections. He has until early July to put
together a governing coalition.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians are concerned that he might have his hands
tied if he finally form a coalition including right-wing parties
such as the Likud and the National Religious Party, which favor
expanding Jewish settlement activities.
</P>
<P>
They have repeatedly urged Barak to break his silence to halt
the settlement expansion, saying "peace and settlements could not
co-exist."
</P>
<P>
With the Israeli-controlled part cutting in the center of
Hebron, Palestinians sometimes have to take a big detour if they
want to go from one street to the other in the nearby area, thus
making a five-minute walk into a 40-minute or one-hour journey,
Kawther Salam, a Palestinian journalist, told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
"I've covered Hebron for a long time. My understanding is
that, with this situation going on, there will never be peace in
Hebron," she said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
