<HEADLINE> Tibet Emphasizes New Energy Potential </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Tibet has great prospects for
cooperating with foreign companies in exploiting new energy
resources, according to Yang Chuantang, the executive vice-
chairman of China's Tibet Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
In a meeting with a Japanese delegation here today, Yang said
that Tibet has many solar and subterranean heat resources that
have helped many villages and schools get electricity.
</P>
<P>
He says that the energy issue has long been a major concern of
departments in the Tibetan and Central Chinese governments.
</P>
<P>
At present, some 60 percent of Tibet's small towns and 80
percent of its rural people have no access to electricity.
