<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Lays Ground for "Common Defense" Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOGNE, June 3 (Xinhua) -- The European Union on Thursday laid
the foundations for a "common defense" for the 15-nation bloc,
boosting its image in the field of foreign and security affairs.
</P>
<P>
The two-day European Union Summit, that went underway on
Thursday, approved, as a "decisive step forward", a joint
declaration that said the move intended to give the union
"necessary means and capability to assume its responsibilities
regarding a common European policy on security and defense".
</P>
<P>
"The Union must have the capability for autonomous action,
backed up by credible military forces, the means to decide to use
them and a readiness to do so, in order to respond to
international crises without prejudice to actions by NATO," said
the declaration.
</P>
<P>
The declaration was announced after the heads of state and
government from the European Union nations met in Cologne to
approve the formation of a common foreign and security policy.
</P>
<P>
The approval meant that the European Union would be able to
carry out a range of conflict prevention and crisis management
missions, including such operations as in the Yugoslav province of
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
NATO Secretary General Javier Solana has been hailed as the
most likely candidate for the newly-designated EU common foreign
and security coordinator and officials of the German EU presidency
said that they hoped the 57-year-old Spaniard would be nominated
later in the day.
</P>
<P>
An Italian delegate to the EU Summit said, however, that the EU
might postpone the appointment until after unionwide European
Parliament elections next week to avoid any impression that the
United States-led western military alliance was dominating Europe.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
