<DOCNO> XIE19990603.0065 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Cautions Bangladesh to Reduce Dependence on Garments Sector </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, June 3 (Xinhua) -- The European Union Thursday cautioned
Bangladesh to diversify its export items in order to reduce
dependence on the garments sector, the largest foreign exchange
earner of the country.
</P>
<P>
"It appears essential for Bangladesh to diversify the export
range and to develop industries and service, which can contribute
to export earnings," Jorg V. Ketelsen, counselor of the European
Commission Delegation in Dhaka, said at a seminar here.
</P>
<P>
The heavy reliance on ready-made garments will become
problematic in the medium term, not least because of garments
exports will come under an increasing challenge as the developed
countries are bound to liberalize their respective imports from
other supplying countries by the year 2005, he said.
</P>
<P>
The special export facilities for garments export such as the
Multi-Fiber Agreement for the United States and the General
Preferential System for Europe are due to be phased out by the
year 2005 after the World Trade Organization agreement on tariff
becomes fully operative.
</P>
<P>
The garments sector, which accounts for over 73 percent of the
country's export earnings, earned 3.9 billion U.S. dollars in the
1997-98 fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh is the fifth largest apparel exporter to the
European Union. 
</P>
</TEXT>
