<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Too Soon to Party: Finnish Official Says </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOGNE, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Finnish Prime Minister Paavo
Lipponen warned on Thursday that it was still "too soon to party"
after the European leaders heard of the acceptance by Yugoslavia
of the Group of Eight peace plan.
</P>
<P>
"We can have final confirmation about peace only after
receiving (Finnish) President Martti Athisaari's report," said the
prime minister during the European Union Summit.
</P>
<P>
He told the press in Cologne that June 3 might be a great day
in European history but "this is too serious to start partying
yet".
</P>
<P>
The Finnish president is flying from Belgrade to Cologne after
his talks with Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic for the past
two days.
</P>
<P>
The Yugoslav president has accepted the G8 peace plan after the
Yugoslav Parliament voted on Thursday 250-82 with one abstention
to ratify the plan after two days of negotiations between the
Balkan nation and Russian envoy Viktor Chernomyrdin and EU
President Martti Athisaari.
</P>
<P>
The G8 peace plan, worked out earlier last month in Bonn, calls
for a withdrawal of Yugoslav army and police units from the
Yugoslav province of Kosovo, the deployment in Kosovo of an
international peacekeeping force including NATO troops and the
secure return of refugees to the province.
</P>
<P>
Chernomyrdin and Athisaari went to Belgrade on Wednesday after
they had talked the issue over with United States Deputy Secretary
of State Strobe Talbott in Bonn prior to the European Union
Summit.
</P>
<P>
The three men reached broad agreement on the first joint
initiative from Russia and NATO. 
</P>
</TEXT>
