<HEADLINE> Cabinet Reshuffle Comes Into Effect in Singapore </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, June 3 (Xinhua) -- The cabinet reshuffle announced
by Singapore Prime Minister's Office on May 13 came into effect
Thursday with new faces sworn in at the presidential palace.
</P>
<P>
Two new faces, Minister of State at the Ministry of
Communications and Information Technology (MCIT) as well as for
Trade and Industry Lim Swee Say and Senior Parliamentary Secretary
at the Community Development Ministry Yu Foo Yee Shoon, were sworn
in by President Ong Teng Cheong.
</P>
<P>
Yeo Cheow Tong has assumed the portfolio of MCIT minister after
relinquishing his post as minister for health and environment.
</P>
<P>
MCIT has evolved from the old communications ministry and has
taken on new responsibilities to reflect Singapore's emphasis on
IT.
</P>
<P>
Lim Hng Kiang who gave up the portfolio of minister for
national development replaced Yeo Cheow Tong as minister for
health. He also retains his portfolio as second minister for
finance.
</P>
<P>
Taking over at the National Development Ministry is Mah Bow Tan
who assumed the new post after serving as minister for
communications.
</P>
<P>
Exchanging their portfolios, George Yeo takes over the Ministry
of Trade and Industry while Lee Yock Suan is the new minister for
information and the arts, and also the environment minister.
</P>
<P>
John Chen embarks on the job as minister of state for both
communications and information technology and national development
for a full term instead of half as appointed initially.
</P>
<P>
Senior Minister of State Aline Wong has dropped the health
portfolio and will focus on education.
</P>
<P>
Matthias Yao Chin has become minister of state without
portfolio at the Prime Minister's Office after serving as minister
of state for defense.
</P>
<P>
David Lim, minister of state for defense, now has an additional
portfolio as minister of state for information and the arts.
</P>
</TEXT>
