<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Paper Calls Cox Report Despicable Farce (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 3 (Xinhua) -- The report of the U.S.
Congressional committee led by Christopher Cox is a despicable
anti-Chinese farce, according to China's leading newspaper,
People's Daily.
</P>
<P>
The Cox Report vilifies China for "stealing" U.S. nuclear
secrets and "threatening" its national security and has stirred up
anti-Chinese clamor on Capitol Hill and Cox and the members of his
team have chosen a sensational topic, but without hard evidence,
the paper says in a commentary prepared for its Friday edition.
</P>
<P>
The Cox Report alleges that China has been stealing U.S.
military secrets for the past 20 years, but this is a sheer lie
and everyone knows that, as early as 35 years ago, China
successfully exploded its first nuclear device during a strict
blockade and embargo imposed by the West and, by 1970, had
succeeded in developing its first atomic bomb, H-bomb and
satellite, the paper points out.
</P>
<P>
China had relied completely on its own science and technology
to develop its national defense and the thefts imagined by Cox
underestimates China's scientific and technological capacity, the
paper says.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990603.0071 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Despicable Anti-Chinese Farce (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
China is a large, responsible country and developing a limited
number of nuclear weapons is for self-defense and not an arms race,
the paper says. There is no need to steal nuclear secrets from
other countries.
</P>
<P>
The Cox Report raves from beginning to end, makes groundless
accusations and takes materials that are openly available in
periodicals and on the Internet as secrets and normal academic
exchanges as theft, the commentary says.
</P>
<P>
There has been no evidence after several months of
investigations in the case of a Chinese-American scientist who is
alleged to have passed secrets to China and even the FBI admitted
that the scientist didn't violate any security regulations, let
alone commit espionage.
</P>
<P>
According to the paper, the Cox Report is intended to spread
fallacies to deceive people but has met with criticism from U.S.
politicians, economists, and media people.
</P>
<P>
It says that one Democratic Congressman and member of the Cox
team pointed out that the report's many conclusions are untenable.
He said that since the supposedly stolen missile guidance
technology has been used on commercial aircraft like Boeing 747s
for many years, the accusation that the technology has enhanced
China's missile guidance ability so as to have posed a threat to
the U.S. is "far-fetched".
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990603.0072 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Despicable Anti-Chinese Farce (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The New York Times called the Cox Report a first-class spy
story, whose narration is too bizarre and complicated, the paper
says, adding that all this has shown that any attempt to cheat the
world with lies, no matter when and where, is hard to succeed.
</P>
<P>
In fact, the report has ulterior motives and Cox is doing all
he can to demonize China and to impede China's development. He and
others decided that, rather than talking about the "China threat",
China's stealing of U.S. nuclear secrets would be more exciting
and sensational.
</P>
<P>
However, lies only last for a limited time and all farces end
in due time. There will come a day when the American people make a
clear distinction between truth and falsehood and reach the right
conclusions, the paper says.
</P>
<P>
It is not accidental that the report came out just after the U.
S.-led NATO attacked the Chinese embassy in Belgrade. Just when
the U.S. government is needed to explain clearly to the Chinese
people, the U.S. Congress came up with the report in a move that
is clearly intended to divert people's attention.
</P>
<P>
In the history of Sino-U.S. relations, says the paper, domestic
politics have always been a major influence on ties and it is not
surprising that some people are making a fuss as U.S. election
approaches.
</P>
<P>
The paper says that some people in the United States still
stick to the Cold-War mentality now that the arch-rival of the
former Soviet Union is gone and they see China as an opponent.
</P>
<P>
All the anti-China farces staged by certain people in the
United States in the past ended with failures, and the current one
can not have a different ending, the paper concludes.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
