<DOCNO> XIE19990603.0073 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Supermarkets Withdraw Belgian Food Products </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Supermarkets across Britain started
withdrawing all products containing Belgian eggs, poultry and pork
on Thursday following a cancer food alert and warning from the
government.
</P>
<P>
The discovery of a cancer-causing chemical dioxin in feed for
hens and pigs on some Belgian farms has already caused two Belgian
ministers to resign.
</P>
<P>
The health scare led the British Ministry of Agriculture to
warn food sellers in Britain to stop using all Belgian chicken,
eggs and pork products.
</P>
<P>
British Agriculture Minister Nick Brown admitted authorities
had not acted as quickly as they could have to prevent any risk to
consumers.
</P>
<P>
"My concern is that we've probably got to this later than we
should have done," he said.
</P>
<P>
He agreed this meant some shoppers had probably bought infected
products in the past couple of days.
</P>
<P>
The only way to guarantee not being at risk from eggs, poultry
or pork from Belgium would be not to eat it, he said, and added
that he would not eat Belgium food.
</P>
<P>
France, Germany and the Netherlands are believed to be most at
risk from having imported infected animal feed or products.
</P>
<P>
European Union vets have already ordered the destruction of
millions of pounds worth of chicken and eggs products exported
from Belgium since 15 January. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
