<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1600 GMT, June 3 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD -- The captured Indian pilot, Flight Lieutenant K.
Nachiketa, will be handed over to the Indian High Commissioner
Thursday evening.
</P>
<P>
This was announced Thursday afternoon by Prime Minister Nawaz
Sharif in a press briefing at the Prime Minister's House.
</P>
<P>
A formal handover ceremony will be held at the Foreign Ministry
Thursday evening.
</P>
<P>
Nachiketa was captured by the Pakistani Army on May 27 when his
MiG jet fighter was shot down in the Pakistani side on the Line of
Control (LoC) in the disputed Kashmir region.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan's ground forces claimed to shot down two Indian MiG
jet fighters on May 27. One pilot, Squadron Leader Ajay Ahuja, was
killed and his dead body was returned to the Indian side in Kargil
sector on the LoC last Friday. (Pakistan-India-Captured Pilot)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ZAGREB -- The Yugoslav government on Thursday accepted an
international peace plan for Kosovo, the state-run Tanjug news
agency, monitored here, reported.
</P>
<P>
The Tanjug report came after Serbia's parliament overwhelmingly
approved the peace plan designed to end the Kosovo crisis and the
U.S-led NATO bombardment of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
The peace plan was presented to Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic Wednesday by the Balkans envoys, former Russian premier
Viktor Chernomyrdin and Finnish President Martti Ahtisaari.
</P>
<P>
The plan was approved by 136 members of the 250 seat parliament
while 74 voted against, with three abstentions, the French news
agency AFP quoted Dragan Veselinov, a deputy with the opposition
Coalition Vojvodina, as saying.
</P>
<P>
It also quoted Finnish Foreign Ministry spokesman Yrjo
Lansituro as saying that the talks between the two envoys and
Milosevic would be resumed "as soon as possible" after the
parliamentary vote.
</P>
<P>
Under the peace plan, NATO and Russia would separately send
troops to Kosovo as part of a peacekeeping presence with the
United Nations' approval and support. (Yugoslavia-Kosovo-Peace
Plan)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BRUSSELS -- The spokesman for NATO, Jamie Shea, said here
Thursday that NATO airstrikes against Yugoslavia will continue
until the North Atlantic Council verifies that Belgrade has met
all the required conditions and everything is ready for
implementation.
</P>
<P>
Shea said the air campaign will continue until the North
Atlantic Council, the NATO's decision-making body, decides that
the air raids should stop.
</P>
<P>
Asked if NATO will stop bombing when all the conditions have
been met, Shea said that the prerequisite conditions have not yet
been met so the air campaign will continue as usual with the same
strength.
</P>
<P>
"We have already organized an enabling force for the
implementation of peace, which will be under NATO's control and as
solid as always," he added. (NATO-Yugoslavia-Bombing) 
</P>
</TEXT>
