He is also set to meet with members of Indonesia's General
Election Commission (KPU), representatives of the major political
parties and a number of election monitoring bodies in Jakarta on
June 6 as part of the activities of the 100-member delegation from
the Carter Center, which he leads, and the National Democratic
Institute for International Affairs (NDI).
</P>
<P>
The Carter Center and NDI delegation will include political
leaders, election experts, and experts from 20 countries.
</P>
<P>
During June 7 general election in Indonesia, the delegates will
visit as many polling stations as possible in their assigned areas
to witness their opening, the voting process and the reporting of
the election results.
</P>
<P>
About 128 million eligible voters in Indonesia will elect 462
candidates to the 500-seat House of Representatives (parliament)
in the forthcoming election in which 48 political parties contest.
The remaining 38 seats will be reserved for the Armed Forces whose
members do not vote. 
</P>
</TEXT>
