<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Eastern Chinese Province Makes Project Quality Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Legislators in eastern China's
Zhejiang Province today passed a law on quality control over
construction projects that is to go into effect as of October 1
this year.
</P>
<P>
Under the new law, what will be subject to quality inspections
and controls includes key state and provincial construction
projects, important public facilities, infrastructure projects,
big and medium-sized industrial projects, apartment buildings,
underground projects costing more than 500,000 yuan (about 60,000
U.S. dollars) each, and projects funded by loans from foreign
governments or international organizations, donations or grants.
</P>
<P>
The law says that companies involved in these projects will
need to deal with inspection and control agencies through bids and
if an overseas inspection and control agency wants to get involved
it needs to have a Chinese partner.
</P>
<P>
The province already has some 130 inspection and control
agencies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
