<HEADLINE> British Fund Helping Train Teachers in Tibet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Lhasa, June 3 (Xinhua) -- The British Save The Children Fund
has spent over six million yuan (723,000 U.S. dollars) helping
education and health programs for children in the Tibet Autonomous
Region, southwest China, over the past decade.
</P>
<P>
According to Zhang Dajun, who is responsible for the fund's
education program in Tibet, the fund has over the past eight years
put one million yuan into training more than 1,000 teachers and
setting up 19 preschool classes in five counties in Tibet.
</P>
<P>
The fund was set up in 1919 primarily to help children affected
by wars and natural disasters. It has helped children's education
and health programs in China in the city of Beijing and in Anhui
and Yunnan provinces.  
