<HEADLINE> U.N. Assessment Mission in East Timor Hoists Flag </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 3 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Assessment
Mission in East Timor (UNAMET) hosted the blue and white U.N. flag
over its headquarters in Dili, capital of East Timor, Thursday in
a ceremony led by mission chief Ian Martin.
</P>
<P>
The flag-raising ceremony marks the official start of the
team's work on the implementation of a direct balloting on a
wide-ranging autonomy package offered by the Indonesian government
to East Timor.
</P>
<P>
"It is an honor for us to welcome you all in the name of the
U.N. secretary general, with the establishment of our new office
for our mission in East Timor. We have the support of the
government to carry out the mission," Martin was quoted by Antara
News Agency as saying.
</P>
<P>
Present at the ceremony were East Timor Governor Abilio Jose
Osorio Soares, Dili Bishop Carlos Belo and other officials.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Portuguese envoy to Indonesia Anna Gomes said U.N.
presence is needed in East Timor.
</P>
<P>
"At last, the tripartite agreement signed in New York on May 5
could be implemented. The agreement has decided on a popular
consultation of the East Timorese this August to know their will,"
Gomes said.
</P>
<P>
According to Antara, pro-independence supporters kicked and
smashed the cars of three government officials following the
flag-raising ceremony at the headquarters of the UNAMET in Dili.
</P>
<P>
No one was injured, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Under a U.N.-brokered agreement with Portugal, Indonesia agreed
to hold the direct ballot in East Timor on August 8.
</P>
<P>
East Timor, with a population of some 800,000 and an area of
15,000 square kilometers, had been a Portuguese colony until 1975.
It became an Indonesian province in 1976, but the U.N. never
recognized the move.
</P>
<P>
On January 27, the Indonesian government announced that it is
ready to release East Timor if the alternative to provide wider
autonomy is refused by the people in the region and the
international community. 
</P>
</TEXT>
