<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 3 (Xinhua) -- The Clinton administration
reacted cautiously Thursday to Yugoslavia's reported acceptance of
an international peace plan for Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
"It's a hopeful sign, but we need to see more details," said
Pentagon spokesman Kenneth Bacon.
</P>
<P>
A White House spokesman told Xinhua that the U.S. will make
further comment after Finnish President Martti Ahtisaari and U.S.
Deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbott meet in Bonn.
</P>
<P>
White House officials said they were monitoring the reports out
of Belgrade but wanted to hear directly from Ahtisaari, who is
representing the European Union in talks with Slobodan Milosevic's
government.
</P>
<P>
White House spokesman Joe Lockhart told reporters that
President Bill Clinton is waiting for a telephone call from
Talbott to update the development.
</P>
<P>
Reports from Belgrade said that both the Yugoslav government
and parliament approved an international peace plan for Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Clinton is expected to meet the military leaders at the White
House and review the crisis. Defense Secretary William Cohen said
while ground forces would come up during the meeting, the Clinton
administration remained committed to the NATO strategy of
airstrikes.
</P>
<P>
Cohen said that "there is no other planning" for ground troops
apart from those involved in peacekeeping. 
</P>
