<DOCNO> XIE19990603.0093 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Bangladesh Estimates 5.2 Percent Growth This Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, June 3 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladeshi government has upped
its economic growth projection for the 1998-99 fiscal year from a
previously-anticipated less than 4 percent to a surprising 5.2
percent, which officials said was due to a bumper crop harvest.
</P>
<P>
Defending the achievement of 5.2 percent growth rate for the
current fiscal ending on June 30, 1999, State Minister for
Planning Mahiuddin Khan Alamgir told reporters Thursday that the
estimate was made "on the basis of correct and realistic data."
</P>
<P>
"There's no scope at all to brand this estimate as miraculous
or otherwise since it was based on realistic data available up to
May this year," he told a press conference.
</P>
<P>
The unexpected development in the agriculture sector and other
key sectors had generated a kind of confidence to achieve a higher
growth of 7 percent next year, he said.
</P>
<P>
Agriculture and Food Minister Motia Chowdhury said, "The heavy
amount of silt carried by last year's flood has helped a lot side
by side the government's efforts" for the country to have a good
harvest. She put the estimated food cereals production at 21.358
million tons, a 5 percent increase over that of last year.
</P>
<P>
The output of boro crop, an irrigational paddy variety, would
stand at 10.3 million tons, she said.
</P>
<P>
Normally, the country's GDP growth rate is announced in the
finance minister's budget speech before the parliament in June
each year. The early announcement of the growth rate this year has
surprised many people, who expressed doubt about the figures.
</P>
<P>
"5.2 percent looks miraculous, if you look at broad economic
situation and the last floods," World Bank country director
Federick Temple said last Sunday at a meeting with members of the
Foreign Investors' Chamber of Commerce and Industry.
</P>
<P>
He said the bank had estimated the growth rate would be around
3-4 percent supplemented by good boro crops.
</P>
<P>
Although the economy saw good development in boro crops, the
donor representative said, the manufacturing sector and exports
did pick the way everybody thought.
</P>
<P>
Official figures show that the country fetched 2.98 billion
dollars during the July-January period, the first seven months of
the current fiscal, trailing the target of 3.28 billion dollars by
9 percent, and 1 percent less than the figure of the corresponding
period of the previous fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
Primary commodity exports slumped in both volume and value, by
14 percent and 18 percent respectively, while industrial exports
marked a slight upturn. Officials said the country lost 350
million to 500 million dollars in exports during the
three-month-long flood.
</P>
<P>
A report in Wednesday's edition of the Daily Star newspaper
said that the Agriculture Ministry originally set a target of 8.2
million tons of boro production this year, but raised it to 8.7
million tons in mid-February and further increased it to 9 million
tons in April.
</P>
<P>
The government fixed a target for this year crop production at
21 million tons, including 1.9 million tons of aus (a variety of
rice), 9.5 million tons of rain-fed aman rice, 7.8 million tons of
boro, and 1.8 million tons of wheat. But there was already a 0.3
million ton-loss in aus and 1.8 million tons of aman was wiped
away by floods, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
The government had originally estimated a growth rate of 3.8
percent at the donors' consortium meeting in April this year,
which was revised to 4.5 percent in May keeping in mind a bumper
boro crop, and was later increased to 5.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
The report, quoting sources, said the Bangladesh Bureau of
Statistics had been asked to "back calculate" the other figures to
match the 5.2 growth rate and the boro output had been refixed at
over 10 million tons.
</P>
<P>
And a source in the government was quoted by the Financial
Express newspaper Tuesday as saying that the growth estimate might
have to be revised downward at a later stage.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh was severely hit by a prolonged flood in 1998, which
lasted from July to September, affecting over 30 million people,
resulting in more than 1,000 deaths and causing an estimated
overall loss of 4.3 billion U.S. dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
