<HEADLINE> Balkans Conference Scheduled in Cologne </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOGNE, June 3 (Xinhua) -- A Balkans conference will be held
in Cologne soon to focus on the stability of the peninsula,
delegates to the current European Union summit said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Representatives from southeast European nations will meet in
Cologne next week to found a stability pact for the Balkans and
the meeting was decided by Austria, Germany and Finland, known as
the EU troika.
</P>
<P>
The trio represent the country that currently holds the
six-month rotating EU presidency, its predecessor and its
successor.
</P>
<P>
The foreign ministers of the Group of Seven plus Russia are to
meet after the conference to cement the stability pact.
</P>
<P>
The two-day European Summit, that went underway in Cologne on
Thursday, was to discuss and hear the report by EU envoy to
Yugoslavia, Finnish President Martti Ahtisaari who went to the
Yugoslav capital on Wednesday after having talked with Russian
envoy Viktor Chernomyrdin and United States Deputy Secretary of
State Strobe Talbott in Bonn.
</P>
<P>
It will be the fourth time in four months for the EU leaders to
discuss the issue of Kosovo where NATO warplanes have been
dropping missiles and bombs since March 24.
</P>
<P>
The EU leaders have tasked the Finnish president to go to
Belgrade to gauge how Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic would
accept the peace plan worked out by the Group of Seven and Russia
last month.
</P>
<P>
Summit host, German Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder said prior to
the summit meeting that there had been "substantial progress" in
bringing together the positions of the EU, United States and
Russia over how to end the NATO air campaign. 
</P>
</TEXT>
