<DOCNO> XIE19990603.0098 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong's Readiness for Y2K Problem </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong is one of the two best
places in terms of the Y2K readiness, according to the latest
assessment by the Global 2000 Coordinating Group.
</P>
<P>
The group monitors the readiness of the Year 2000 (Y2K) problem
for computer systems and embedded systems and progress of
compliance work in 43 countries and cities in the world.
</P>
<P>
According to Hong Kong Health Welfare Bureau and Information
Technology Bureau, 96 percent of mission-critical computer and
embedded systems within the government are confirmed to be Y2K
compliant or have been rectified by May 15 this year. Most of the
remaining systems will be rectified by the end of June.
</P>
<P>
All government departments are formulating business contingency
plans to ensure that the departments' operation and services
provided to the public will not be disrupted.
</P>
<P>
In the run-up to 2000, the government will launch a range of
publicity activities to enhance public understanding of the
possible impact of the Y2K problem so as to prepare the general
public for a smooth transition to the next century.
</P>
<P>
The Global 2000 Coordinating Group is composed of 250
international banks, securities firms and insurance companies.
</P>
<P>
Its assessment is made on the basis of Y2K readiness of seven
critical sectors in a place, including financial services,
settlement and clearing, telecommunications, public transport,
power supply, water supply and government services. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
