<DOCNO> XIE19990603.0107 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 13:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 3 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israeli government's tax collection increased only
0.2 percent to reach 50.6 billion shekels (about 12.3 billion
U.S. dollars) in the first five months of the year compared with
the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
The low collection led to a shortage of 1.4 billion shekels
(340 million dollars) from the projected tax revenues in the 1999
state budget, The Jerusalem Post reported on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israel's polished diamond exports reached 379
million dollars in May, a 13 percent increase over May 1998.
</P>
<P>
The total diamond exports for the first five months of this
year amounted to 1.721 billion dollars, a 4 percent growth over
the same period last year, The Jerusalem Post reported on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- U.S. multinational 3M Company has invested 10
million dollars in Israeli BATM Advanced Communications company,
which is 3M's first-ever investment in Israel.
</P>
<P>
The deal, which was announced earlier this week, grants 3M the
option of raising its holdings in BATM from 4.5 percent to 9.9
percent in a year's time.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Iraq's losses from the U.N.-imposed oil embargo has
amounted to about 160 billion dollars by the end of April, and are
expected to rise in the coming months after the renewal of the
oil-for-food deal.
</P>
<P>
The world energy studies center said the losses are estimated
based on Iraq's oil exporting capacity of 3 million barrels per
day before the imposition of the sanctions in 1990.
</P>
<P>
Iraq is currently producing 2.5 million barrels of petroleum
per day, 2 million of which are exported under the oil-for-food
deal with the U.N., the Arabic daily Al Hayat reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The deal, which started in 1996, allowed Iraq to export limited
amount of oil to buy food, medicine and other humanitarian goods
for its 22 million people.
</P>
<P>
Iraq is the second largest petroleum producing country in the
world after Saudi Arabia, with reserves estimated at 112 billion
barrels.
</P>
<P>
RIYADH -- Saudi Arabia has lifted the temporary embargo imposed
against the import of sheep, goats and camels from Djibouti,
Somalia, Ethiopia, Kenya, Yemen, Mauritania, Tanzania and
Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
But it maintains ban on importing cows from these states and
all African countries on account of the cattle plague, the Arabic
economic daily Alam Al Yom reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Saudi sources said the embargo was lifted after the Ministry of
Agriculture and Water received assurance reports from the
U.N. Food and Agriculture Organization, the World Health
Organization and the International Organization on Animal Health.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Five-star Heliopolis in the suburbs of Cairo led
hotels in occupancy rate, which averages 87 percent, as against 65
percent in the Pyramid district and 79 percent in downtown Cairo.
</P>
<P>
The report attributed the distinguished performance of the
Heliopolis hotel to boosting conference-tourism, fairs and other
international events taking place in Cairo, the Alam Al Yom
reported Thursday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990603.0108 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yugoslavia Accepts Peace Plan for Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZAGREB, June 3 (Xinhua) -- The Yugoslav government on Thursday
accepted an international peace plan for Kosovo, the state-run
Tanjug news agency, monitored here, reported.
</P>
<P>
The Tanjug report came after Serbia's parliament overwhelmingly
approved the peace plan designed to end the Kosovo crisis and the
U.S-led NATO bombardment of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
The peace plan was presented to Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic Wednesday by the Balkans envoys, former Russian premier
Viktor Chernomyrdin and Finnish President Martti Ahtisaari.
</P>
<P>
The plan was approved by 136 members of the 250 seat parliament
while 74 voted against, with three abstentions, the French news
agency AFP quoted Dragan Veselinov, a deputy with the opposition
Coalition Vojvodina, as saying.
</P>
<P>
It also quoted Finnish Foreign Ministry spokesman Yrjo
Lansituro as saying that the talks between the two envoys and
Milosevic would be resumed "as soon as possible" after the
parliamentary vote.
</P>
<P>
Under the peace plan, NATO and Russia would separately send
troops to Kosovo as part of a peacekeeping presence with the
United Nations' approval and support.
</P>
<P>
NATO and Yugoslavia would have to hammer out a document on the
withdrawal of Yugoslav troops from Kosovo so that NATO would end
its bombing that started on March 24.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was reached during talks near Bonn among
Chernomyrdin, his EU counterpart and Finnish President Ahtisaari
and U.S. Deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbott earlier
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The outlines of the peace plan were agreed on May 6 by foreign
ministers of the seven most industrialized nations -- Britain,
Canada, France, Germany, Italy, Japan and the United States -- and
Russia, which form what is called the Group of Eight. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990603.0109 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HKSAR Chief Executive on Civil Service Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Tung Chee Hwa, chief executive of
the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region, Thursday stressed the
six primary principles on the civil service reform.
</P>
<P>
These include changing amidst stability; reforming step by step;
taking a comprehensive overview; holding wide consultation;
adopting practicable measures; and ensuring that the reform is
reasonable and lawful.
</P>
<P>
Tung made these remarks at the 85th anniversary reception of
the Hong Kong Chinese Civil Servants' Association Thursday
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Since the proposed civil service reform was announced by the
government in March this year, members of all civil service unions
and bodies have been very active in joining discussions and
voicing their opinions.
</P>
<P>
He said Hong Kong has an excellent team of civil servants and
all its people should take pride in. With the approach of the 21
st century and a rapidly changing external environment, he said: "
We are undergoing a difficult process of economic recovery."
</P>
<P>
It is indeed essential that the civil service keeps pace with
the community it serves, improves itself and enhances its
efficiency so that services of better quality can be made
available to the community, he said.
</P>
<P>
"We will put special emphasis on the introduction of changes
amidst stability, the step-by-step implementation of reforms and
the reasonableness and lawfulness of reform," he said.
</P>
<P>
Noting that civil service reform is of course a complicated
process with far-reaching impact, he expressed the hope that
members of the staff unions and their colleagues will continue to
put forward their views and take part in discussions actively so
that practical and feasible proposals will be worked out with
concerted efforts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
