<HEADLINE> France Confirms Yugoslavia Has Accepted Peace Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 3 (Xinhua) -- France confirmed on Thursday that
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic and the Yugoslav parliament
have accepted the international peace plan for Kosovo jointly
presented by Russia, the European Union and the United States.
</P>
<P>
French Foreign Minister Hubert Vedrine said in a published
statement that France pays homage to EU envoy, Finnish President
Martti Ahtisaari, and Russian envoy Viktor Chernomyrdin for their
diplomatic maneuvers in Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
He said that "determined, persevering and convergent actions by
Europeans and Americans" have resulted in the acceptance of the
peace plan by President Milosevic and the Serb parliament.
</P>
<P>
"The priority now is to inscribe the solution of peace in a
United Nations Security Council resolution, to begin implementing
it and to arrange a stop of military operations (by NATO)," he
said.
</P>
<P>
He said that officials of the so-called Group of Eight
countries will begin working "in this perspective" from Thursday
evening.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the French Defense Ministry announced that it will
send 6,000 French troops to join the future Kosovo Peace Force (
KFOR). 
</P>
