<HEADLINE> Pak Committed to Dialogue Process With India: PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz
Sharif Thursday stressed that his country is still looking forward
to peaceful dialogue with India and defusing of tension in
Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
Despite the current fire exchanges in Kashmir, Sharif said that
he still hopes that the Lahore Declaration which he signed with
his Indian counterpart Atal Bihari Vajpayee "would prove to be a
milestone in their efforts to banish conflict, dissipate tension
and promote meaningful dialogue for a just and final settlement of
the Kashmir dispute".
</P>
<P>
Addressing a press briefing at the Prime Minister's House
Thursday afternoon, Sharif blamed India for initiating military
action in Kashmir, the disputed area which has brought India and
Pakistan into two wars.
</P>
<P>
The situation now is "fraught with dangers and serious risks,"
observed the prime minister.
</P>
<P>
Since early May, troops of Pakistan and India began exchanging
fire across the Line of Control (LoC). India went so far as to
launch air strikes on May 26 in the LoC area, which was claimed to
be aimed at eliminating so-called "Pakistan-backed Muslim
infiltrators."
</P>
<P>
Pakistan shot down two Indian MiG jets on May 27, alleging they
violated Pakistan's air space.
</P>
<P>
"We want to prevent any further escalation and to defuse this
situation," said Sharif, adding that India has escalated military
action on both sides of the LoC in the past two weeks.
</P>
<P>
He also condemned the killing of ten school children in India's
artillery shelling on schools. 
</P>
</TEXT>
