<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Sets Common Strategy for Cooperation With Russia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOGNE, June 3 (Xinhua) -- During its summit in Cologne, the
European Union (EU) adopted a foreign policy strategy that will
enable Europe to work more effectively with Russia.
</P>
<P>
State and government leaders from the 15 EU members have
devised a "strategic partnership" with Russia, said Uwe-Karsten
Heye, a German government spokesman.
</P>
<P>
The Goal of EU's "common strategy plan toward Russia" is to
develop a durable and close partnership that will provide Russia
with an opportunity for "greater participation in the European
continent's future," Heye said.
</P>
<P>
EU members will coordinate their Russian policy more closely,
and it will provide Russia with more experience in building modern
political, economic, social and managerial institutions.
</P>
<P>
The EU called for more enduring political and security
dialogues, strengthened contacts, and more frequent visits between
the countries' peoples International organizations such as the U.N.
, the Organization of Security and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE),
the European Council, and International financial institutions,
should strive to cooperate with each other more intensively.
</P>
<P>
The common strategy underlines the importance of stabilizing
Russia's energy policy, its nuclear security, and its battles
against organized crimes.
</P>
<P>
On the Kosovo issue, Heye said EU leaders insist that all
peacekeeping troops to be deployed in Kosovo, including Russians,
be put under a unified military command.
</P>
<P>
Under the peace plan worked out by the Group of Eight, NATO and
Russia will separately send troops to Kosovo as part of a
peacekeeping presence with the approval and support of the United
Nations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
