<HEADLINE> Shanghai Trade Symposium Closes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, June 3 (Xinhua) -- A trade symposium attended by
experts from the United Nations Conference on Trade and
Development (UNCTAD) and Chinese trade officials and personnel
ended today in Shanghai, China's largest city and a major import
and export base.
</P>
<P>
The three-day symposium has focused on the universal favorable
treatment system of the UNCTAD and relevant trade laws and
regulations. The system requires developed countries to grant
preferential treatment such as tariff reductions for the exports
of developing countries.
</P>
<P>
During the symposium, eight officials and experts from the
UNCTAD delivered speeches introducing the latest policies of the
European Union, Japan, Canada, Norway, Switzerland and other
developed nations in adopting the universal favorable treatment
system.
</P>
<P>
The 200-strong Chinese audience later drew the conclusion that
China still has great potentials in expanding its exports through
a better use of the universal favorable treatment system.
</P>
<P>
Chinese exports have fallen for three consecutive months this
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
