<DOCNO> XIE19990603.0121 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State-Level Arts Festivals To Introduce Market Competition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Competition is to become an element
of the only two state-level arts festivals in China, the National
Arts Festival and the Shanghai International Arts Festival, in
order to explore a new market-oriented mechanism for the country's
cultural sector.
</P>
<P>
This will take the form of fund-raising, advertising and box
office receipts, according to the organizing committee of the 6th
China National Arts Festival.
</P>
<P>
The committee will also seek opinions from the general public
through public bidding to select the best scheme.
</P>
<P>
The festival, to be held in October 2000, will raise funds from
the government reserves, social investment, box office receipts
from performances and a range of other sources.
</P>
<P>
A high profile broadcast during TV's prime time or an eye-
catching page in the print media could also attract funds from
advertisement income.
</P>
<P>
"The Shanghai International Arts Festival is to be run as a
business enterprise and the Ministry of Culture and Shanghai
Municipal Government will not invest even a single cent," said
Zhou Muyao, Vice-Mayor of Shanghai, in a recent news release.
</P>
<P>
"Invitations to artistic groups and box office management will
be controlled by agents and intermediary companies who will
compete to win the business and be responsible for either profits
or losses," according to Zhou.
</P>
<P>
China's international performing arts fair will also be held
during the festival and many cultural agents worldwide will be
invited with the hope of promoting future cultural trade between
China and the rest of the world.
</P>
<P>
"The key to the development of China's cultural sector is the
renewal of ideas, management and technology," as Li Yuanchao, Vice
Minister of Culture, puts it.
</P>
<P>
"The government is shifting its role to a more macroscopical
supervision and a system of modern enterprise is under way, with
more versatile and wide-ranged cultural products to meet the
increasing demand of the public," Li said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
