<HEADLINE> Cartoons Help In China's Drug Crack Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 3 (Xinhua) -- A hard-hitting book of cartoons has
been published by China's Ministry of Public Security as part of
its crack down on narcotics and to boost its campaign to warn
young people about the dangers of drug use and abuse.
</P>
<P>
Last year the ministry sponsored the National Anti-Narcotics
Exhibition in Beijing which received a record shattering 1.6
million visitors. The new book incorporates some of the best
illustrations and cartoons which were on display.
</P>
<P>
Deng Ming, an official with the ministry's narcotics bureau,
said the new book was aimed at helping China's young people
understand the evils of drugtaking and urge them to keep away from
them throughout their lives.
</P>
<P>
"It also looks at the current domestic and international
narcotics situation and outlines the policies adopted by Chinese
government in its anti-drug campaign," added Deng.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese central government has been striking hard at the
narcotics trade, while some local governments such as southwest
China's Yunnan Province have injected hundreds of millions of yuan
to persuade peasants in the notorious "Golden Triangle" area to
plant grain and cash crops instead of opium poppies, which was
their primary source of income for generations.
</P>
<P>
Deng said that the Chinese government also helps drug-addicts
to quit their bad habit through medical treatment and
psychological rehabilitation, as well as providing overall
assistance from society.
</P>
<P>
"China now has a registered drug population of some 600,000,
four-fifths of them youngsters and children," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
