<HEADLINE> Three African Clubs Face CAF Sanctions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Three African soccer clubs are
facing sanctions this week as the Confederation of African
Football were investigating their irregularities.
</P>
<P>
The three leading clubs are CAF Cup holders CS Sfaxien of
Tunisia, Orlando Pirates of South Africa and the Ghanaian club
Asante Kotoko.
</P>
<P>
All the clubs face possible fines or suspensions if found
guilty by the CAF's competition committee who were helding
meetings in Cairo on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
CS Sfaxien was charged of trying to bribe the referee ahead of
its CAF Cup second round second leg match against Nkana FC of
Zambia in Ndola last month, while the other two clubs face charges
of using banned or ineligible players.
</P>
<P>
Sfax vice-chairman Fakhri Yaiche and committee member Fethi
Boucetta were arrested and banned for life, together with official
Salaheddine Zahaf.
</P>
<P>
CAF officials hinted that Sfax faced a heavy fine and possible
suspension from future African club competitions if found guilty,
but were unlikely to be kicked out of this year's tournament.
</P>
</TEXT>
