<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Military Experts Refute COX Report (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Chinese military experts said today
that accusations of China's alleged "theft" of classified U.S.
military information contained in the Cox Report are not only
ridiculous, but also an intentional insult designed to show
contempt for Chinese scientists.
</P>
<P>
The report uses ambiguous language, rather than specific and
persuasive evidence, to accuse China of stealing the U.S. nuclear,
missile and satellite technology.
</P>
<P>
A special committee chaired by Representative Christopher Cox
recently released the report on China's alleged "theft" of U.S.
military technology.
</P>
<P>
Wang Fei, a nuclear scientist with the Chinese Defense
Scientific and Technical Information Center, said that U.S.
nuclear threats and blackmail in the early 1950s forced China to
develop nuclear weapons. China successfully tested the atom bomb
and H-bomb and launched its own satellite long before establishing
diplomatic relations with the United States.
</P>
<P>
"The strict blockade at the time made it impossible for China
to acquire the nuclear technology from the United States and we
relied solely on our own strength to develop limited self-defense
nuclear power," said Wang.
</P>
<P>
He noted that China has many excellent missile experts and
nuclear researchers with high-level innovative capacity. China has
never in the past, nor will it in the future base its development
of nuclear weapons on foreign technology.
</P>
<P>
The Cox Report quite simply contains outrageous fabricated
accusations that China stole classified data for seven types of
nuclear warheads, according to Wang.
</P>
<P>
In fact, the performance data of the warheads in question was
published in public periodicals in the United States in the 1970s
and 1980s. Therefore, the theft of such information was both
impossible and unnecessary.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990603.0135 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Serbian Parliament Approves Peace Plan for Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZAGREB, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Serbia's parliament Thursday
overwhelmingly approved an international peace plan for Kosovo
designed to end the Kosovo crisis and the U.S-led NATO bombardment
of Yugoslavia, news reaching here said.
</P>
<P>
The peace plan was presented to Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic Wednesday by the Balkans envoys, former Russian premier
Viktor Chernomyrdin and Finnish President Martti Ahtisaari.
</P>
<P>
The plan was approved by 136 members of the 250 seat parliament
while 74 voted against, with three abstentions, the French news
agency AFP quoted Dragan Veselinov, a deputy with the opposition
Coalition Vojvodina, as saying.
</P>
<P>
It also quoted Finnish Foreign Ministry spokesman Yrjo
Lansituro as saying that the talks between the two envoys and
Milosevic would be resumed "as soon as possible" after the
parliamentary vote.
</P>
<P>
Under the peace plan, NATO and Russia would separately send
troops to Kosovo as part of a peacekeeping presence with the
United Nations' approval and support.
</P>
<P>
NATO and Yugoslavia would have to hammer out a document on the
withdrawal of Yugoslav troops from Kosovo so that NATO would end
its bombing that started on March 24.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was reached during talks near Bonn among
Chernomyrdin, his EU counterpart and Finnish President Ahtisaari
and U.S. Deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbott earlier
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The outlines of the peace plan were agreed on May 6 by foreign
ministers of the seven most industrialized nations -- Britain,
Canada, France, Germany, Italy, Japan and the United States -- and
Russia, which form what is called the Group of Eight. 
</P>
</TEXT>
