<DOCNO> XIE19990603.0138 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Military Experts Refute COX Report (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
One unnamed Chinese space technology expert pointed out that
China successfully launched 30 satellites with constantly
improving precision rates prior to 1992.
</P>
<P>
The expert cited the fact that satellite launches require
highly sophisticated technology and are thus subject to normal
successes and failures.
</P>
<P>
Just as their foreign counterparts, Chinese experts have
continued to improve the design and management of satellites.
Therefore, rising precision rates are quite natural, according to
the expert.
</P>
<P>
He asked: "Has the high U.S. success rate for satellite
launches resulted from the theft of outside technology?"
</P>
<P>
Chinese experts have independently conducted extensive
investigations of all failure of attempts to launch commercial U.S.
satellites with Chinese carrier rockets, he said.
</P>
<P>
Calculation and analysis of telemetry data and recovered debris,
as well as simulations, have enabled Chinese experts to determine
the cause of problems and introduce technological upgrades, the
expert said. And it is totally groundless that the Cox Report
alleged the cause was determined with the help of U.S. experts.
</P>
<P>
"How can we expect help from any U.S. company in the
investigations after the foiled attempts to launch U.S. commercial
satellite since it is impossible for us to provide our state-of-
the-art rocket manufacturing technology to the United States?"
according to the expert.
</P>
<P>
"As a matter of fact, China has never received technological
support from a U.S. satellite manufacturing company in this
respect."
</P>
<P>
Yet another veteran expert who has been observed launches on
several occasions pointed out that the tight security system
implemented by the U.S. side makes it impossible for the Chinese
side to gain access to satellite technology during the launch of U.
S. commercial satellites.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that U.S. satellites are subject to tight security
after entering Chinese territory. U.S. aircraft deliver satellites
to the Chinese launch site and all containers are immune from
customs inspections. The launching site is totally isolated from
the outside and the U.S. side controls access to all workshops. In
fact, it is the U.S. side that is responsible for round-the-clock
security.
</P>
<P>
What's more, he said, all satellite test facilities are linked
to an electronic supervision system under U.S. supervision.  (
more)
nnnn
</P>
</TEXT>
