<HEADLINE> Tan Certain of Raising Required Money for Philippines Airlines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Philippine Airlines Chairman Lucio
Tan said Thursday that he can now raise the 200 million U.S.
dollars before the June 4 deadline imposed by the Securities and
Exchange Commission to keep the flag carrier in business.
</P>
<P>
Philippine Presidential Palace said in a news release that Tan
informed Philippine President Joseph Estrada of the new
development Thursday afternoon in Japan, where Estrada is on a
working visit and Tan is part of the business delegation
accompanying the president.
</P>
<P>
Estrada said Tan was able to raise the entire 200 million U.S.
dollars without tapping government financial institutions for help
in coming up with the amount that would pave the way for the
implementation of PAL's rehabilitation plan.
</P>
<P>
Trade and Industry Secretary Jose Pardo said the infusion of
fresh capital into PAL is part of the final step that will signal
the start of the airline's rehabilitation program on June 5.
</P>
<P>
He said Tan and his group will have to deposit the amount with
a bank in the Philippines, after which the interim receiver for
PAL will inform the SEC of the deposit.
</P>
<P>
The SEC in turn will appoint a permanent receiver, which, along
with the new PAL management group, would implement the
rehabilitation plan.
</P>
<P>
Estrada said earlier the government would take over the task of
looking for new PAL investors should Tan fail to raise the
required amount to keep PAL flying. 
</P>
</TEXT>
