<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank: Angola's End of Foreign Exchange </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, June 3 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank representative to
Angola, Philipe Owsu, said that Angolan government's removal of
its foreign exchange control is "important and timely".
</P>
<P>
Owsu said that the measure has brought "active influence" to
the macro-economy of the country, and has temporarily stopped the
drop of the local currency kwanza, the Angola Daily reported
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Angolan State Bank, the central bank, announced on May 21
the end of fixed exchange rate system, and let the market adjust
the exchange rate, in consideration that the country's foreign
reserve was on the brink of exhaustion.
</P>
<P>
Owsu said that the World Bank will continue to negotiate with
the Angolan government to find out solutions for the serious
economic problems in the country.
</P>
<P>
The official also said that the Angolan government must take
further actions to improve the macro-economic situation in the
country before the World Bank start its aid plan to the country.
</P>
<P>
The actions which are taken as pre-conditions for the World
Bank aid, Owsu said, include a strict control of financial
spending, the cut of inflation, the realization of a transparency
system for the finance.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank has finished three of the 10 aid programs in
the country, which cover basic education, energy, transportation,
water supply and health projects. The programs will cost 250
million U.S. dollars, for which the World Bank will spend 90
percent of the total and the rest come from the Angolan
government.
</P>
<P>
Since 1997, Angola has fallen into serious economic crisis with
the fall of oil price in the world market and the re-start of
civil war in the country.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
