<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Private Businesses Booming in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 3 (Xinhua) -- China's private sector has
maintained an upbeat momentum this year, with the number of newly-
emerged businesses surging in the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
According to a report of the State Administration for Industry
and Commerce (SAIC) available today, China had 67,100 new private
firms during the January-March period, with the average registered
capital of each private firm hitting 616,500 yuan.
</P>
<P>
During the same period, the crop farming and animal husbandry
sectors of the primary industry had 1,055 newly-added enterprises,
accounting for 65 percent of the total increase in the sector.
</P>
<P>
The manufacturing sector embraced over 20,000 new firms, while
the wholesales and retail sales sector as well as the catering
industry had 32,000 newly established businesses.
</P>
<P>
China re-defined the status and role of the private sector in
March by adding to the Constitution that the non-public sector is
"an important component of the country's socialist market economy".
This has strongly boosted the development of the private sector.
</P>
<P>
SAIC sources indicate that China had a total of over 1.23
million private companies by March this year, with combined
registered capital exceeding 750 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Up to March, more than 16 million people were employed in the
sector, slightly down from the figure in December last year.
</P>
<P>
Analysts say that the drop in employees is only seasonal, as
large numbers of floating employees in the catering sector
returned home for reunions during China's traditional Spring
Festival which fell on February 16 this year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
