<DOCNO> XIE19990603.0147 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Erect Environmental Monument at Source of Yangtze River </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 3 (Xinhua) -- China will erect an environmental
protection monument at the source of the Yangtze River, China's
longest river, on June 5 which is International Environment Day.
</P>
<P>
An official from the State Environmental Protection
Administration said at a news conference here today that the
building of the monument aims to emphasize the importance of
protecting the environment and ecology along the river and improve
public awareness of environmental protection.
</P>
<P>
The 6,300-kilometer-long Yangtze River starts at the
Jianggendiru Glacier on the southwestern foothills of the 6,621-
meter-high snow-covered Geladandong Mountain, the main peak of the
Tanggula Mountains in northwestern Qinghai Province. About one
third of the Chinese population live along the valley of the river.
</P>
<P>
In the past one hundred years the environment of the river has
deteriorated rapidly, with forest coverage areas dropping to 10
percent of the original figure. And the soil erosion areas now
exceed 570,000 square kilometers.
</P>
<P>
Last year's devastating floods along the Yangtze River caused
heavy economic losses. In addition to abnormal climatic conditions,
environmental and ecological deterioration is an explanation for
the floods, experts say. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
