<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Coastal Stretch to Be Improved for Fisheries in S.Lanka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, June 3 (Xinhua) -- From January next year a project
involving the improvement of vital locations along Sri Lanka's
60-mile northwestern coastal stretch will be carried out for
fisheries, informed sources here said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The project to be carried out by the Coastal Resources
Management will be completed in 2005. It involves a loan of an
estimated 79 million U.S. dollars from the Asian Development Bank,
said the sources.
</P>
<P>
The project will include development of nine lagoons,
construction of fisheries harbors at Chilaw in the Western
province and Hambantota in the Southern Province, and four
anchorages.
</P>
<P>
The project will also include the construction of roads, health
centers, drinking water and recreation facilities, the sources
added. 
</P>
