<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigerian Legislators Turn Elections into Fracas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Legislators in Lagos and Imo State in
Nigeria Wednesday turned their inauguration into a free-for-all
fight as they tried to protest against the election of the House
President.
</P>
<P>
The confusion in Lagos State Assembly started as 14 of the
State's 40 legislators protested what they termed as the
"imposition" of a "non- indigene" on them as the speaker of the
House.
</P>
<P>
As the clerk of the house Lamidi Gbadamosi was to introduce the
 proceeding after the State Governor, Chief Justice took seat in
the Assembly house, some of the aggrieved legislators swooped on
him to snatch the microphone.
</P>
<P>
They shouted "no proclamation today. Nothing will happen here
today." Then came the flying of chairs, tables, broken pieces
of glass, which had lasted several hours, before the Lagos
Governor, Ahaji Ahmed Bota Tnubu and his aged mother Abibat
Mogaji, tried to get out from the back door.
</P>
<P>
Several persons including the deputy speaker of the house were
injured in the chaotic event.
</P>
<P>
Armed police were ushered in to chase out some protesting
legislators to allow the governor to proclaim the opening of the
State Assembly before his escaping from the back door.
</P>
<P>
The newly-elected speaker, Adeleke Olorunimbe Mamowora,
explained afterwards that the trouble was caused by some group of
disgruntled legislators who wanted to conduct a shadow election
and impose a speaker on the house.
</P>
<P>
He described the incident as "not unusual in a democratic
setting" but said he felt "embarrassed" by the incident.
</P>
<P>
Equally embarrassing was the incident in Owerri, the lmo State
Capital where legislators also engaged in a fight over the
election of the speaker. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
