<DOCNO> XIE19990603.0155 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Coalition in Sight for Two S. African Provinces </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Coalition governments are in
the offing in South Africa's Western Cape and KwaZulu-Natal as it
appears that none of the parties could win a simple majority.
</P>
<P>
The African National Congress (ANC) and the Inkatha Freedom
Party (IFP) are in a neck-to-neck race in KwaZulu-Natal. In the
Western Cape, the New National Party (NNP) is leading by a small
margin, but is unlikely to be heading for a simple majority.
</P>
<P>
According to preliminary results by noon Thursday based on 61
percent of the votes, the IFP has 40 percent of support in
KwaZulu-Natal and the ANC, 39 percent. In the Western Cape, the
NNP has gained 42 percent, compared with 38 percent for the ANC.
</P>
<P>
The Democratic Party secured a third place in both provinces,
with 13 percent of the vote in the Western Cape and 10 percent in
KwaZulu-Natal.
</P>
<P>
Analysts say there is a fair chance of ANC-IFP coalition in
KwaZulu- Natal while the form of coalition in the Western Cape is
still not clear.
</P>
<P>
During its election campaign, the DP has categorically ruled
out coalition with the ANC in the Western Cape, saying that an
opposition party should be strengthened instead of the ANC.
</P>
<P>
According to initial results, the ANC has won all the other
seven provinces.
</P>
<P>
Nationally, the ANC is heading for a two-thirds majority,
according to projections by the South African Broadcasting
Corporation television.
</P>
<P>
With 62 percent of the votes counted by Thursday morning, the
ANC won 64 percent of the vote, followed by the DP with 11
percent. Both the NNP and IFP got eight percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
