<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain Says Serbian Resolution Not Enough to Stop Bombing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Britain said on Thursday that a vote
by the Serbian parliament to accept an international peace plan
for Kosovo was "an interesting development," but was not enough to
persuade NATO to call off its airstrikes.
</P>
<P>
"A simple resolution of the Serbian parliament is not going to
be enough to persuade a single refugee to go back into Kosovo so
there is still a lot of water to go under that particular bridge,"
Defense Secretary George Robertson told a briefing.
</P>
<P>
The remark was made shortly after Serbia's parliament on
Thursday accepted the "international peace plan for Kosovo."
</P>
<P>
Britain, the most hawkish in the NATO nations, repeatedly said
that the bombing should keep on "until Yugoslavia accepted all the
terms of the military alliance."
</P>
<P>
Serbia's parliament overwhelmingly approved the peace plan for
Kosovo designed to end the Kosovo crisis and the U.S-led NATO
bombardment of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
The peace plan was presented to Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic Wednesday by the Balkans envoys, former Russian premier
Viktor Chernomyrdin and Finnish President Martti Ahtisaari.
</P>
<P>
Under the peace plan, NATO and Russia would separately send
troops to Kosovo as part of a peacekeeping presence with the
United Nations' approval and support.
</P>
<P>
NATO and Yugoslavia would have to hammer out a document on the
withdrawal of Yugoslav troops from Kosovo so that NATO would end
its bombing that started on March 24.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was reached during talks near Bonn among
Chernomyrdin, his EU counterpart and Finnish President Ahtisaari
and U.S. Deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbott earlier
Wednesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
