<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading French Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 3 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news items in
leading French newspapers on Thursday:
</P>
<P>
Liberation:
</P>
<P>
-- The French capital Paris was paralyzed on Wednesday by an
abrupt and total strike of public transport workers, after a
security agent of the subway network died following a
confrontation with peddlers in a subway station on Tuesday. The
cause of his death was yet to be decided.
</P>
<P>
-- For the first time since the beginning of NATO bombings
against Yugoslavia, a representative of Western countries met with
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic on Wednesday. The European
Union's envoy for Kosovo, Finnish President Martti Ahtisaari,
arrived in Belgrade with Russian envoy Viktor Chernomyrdin in
order to obtain the agreement from the Yugoslav president on the
latest proposals of Russia and Western countries on solving the
crisis.
</P>
<P>
Le Figaro:
</P>
<P>
-- The networks of subway trains, fast speed trains linking
Paris with its suburban areas, and buses in the Parisian region
were totally paralyzed on Wednesday a surprise strike of their
staff, while the main unions of the public transport company RATP
called for the continuation of the strike on Thursday. The strike
was caused by the death of a control agent of the subway security
authorities after a brawl with peddlers at a subway station on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
-- Optimism reigned Wednesday night over the chances of a
solution to the Kosovo crisis, after the adoption of a common text
of proposals by Russia, the United States and the European Union.
French President Jacques Chirac said that this text has opened the
door for a political agreement with Yugoslavia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
