<DOCNO> XIE19990603.0167 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Summit to Deal With Kosovo, Employment Issues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOGNE, GERMANY, June 3 (Xinhua) -- The two-day European Union
summit, due to kick off Thursday, will focus on the issues of
Kosovo and a unionwide employment pact.
</P>
<P>
The summit attendants are expected to discuss and hear a report
by EU envoy to Yugoslavia, Finnish President Martti Ahtisaari, who
went to the Yugoslav capital Wednesday after talking with Russian
envoy Viktor Chernomyrdin and United States Deputy Secretary of
State Strobe Talbot in Bonn.
</P>
<P>
It will be the fourth time in four months for the EU leaders to
discuss the issue of Kosovo where NATO warplanes have been
dropping missiles and bombs since March 24.
</P>
<P>
The EU leaders have tasked the Finnish president to go to
Belgrade to gauge how Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic would
accept the peace plan worked out by the Group of Seven and Russia
last month.
</P>
<P>
The Summit host, German Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder, said
prior to the summit meeting that there had been "substantial
progress" in bringing together the positions of the EU, the United
States and Russia over how to end the NATO air campaign.
</P>
<P>
The EU leaders are also expected to approve a European defense
and security initiative which is to choose a European to serve as
the union's foreign and security policy chief. The initiative will
also give the union the capability to use NATO military assets for
regional peacekeeping operations without involving the United
States.
</P>
<P>
NATO Secretary General Javier Solana has been hailed as the
most likely candidate for the post.
</P>
<P>
The two-day summit is due to endorse a European Employment Pact,
which was brought forward by Schroeder as one of the main tasks
for the German EU presidency, which ends in June. The rotating
presidency will be taking over by Finland for the next six months.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, however, different statements, aired by the Union
of Industrial and Employers' Confederations of Europe and the
European Trades Union Confederation showed that the parties of
labor and management are still way from agreeing on how to deal
with the problem of joblessness.
</P>
<P>
Within the 15-nation union, one out of every 10 workers are now
without a job. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990603.0168 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thorough Probe into UNSCOM in Baghdad Urged </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 3 (Xinhua) -- China urged the UN Special
Commission (UNSCOM) in Baghdad to give "detailed and satisfactory
explanations" to the UN Security Council about recent finding of
sarin and VX nerve toxic in its office.
</P>
<P>
The UN secretary-general should promptly make thorough
investigation into the case and put forward to the Security
Council suggestions on how to handle it, said Chinese Foreign
Ministry spokesman Zhu Bangzao here today.
</P>
<P>
"We are highly concerned over coverage of the case, and approve
of a serious investigation into it," said Zhu.
</P>
<P>
"If it is true, it is a serious and extremely vile case
demonstrating that UNSCOM Executive Chairman Richard Butler holds
in contempt of the authority of the Security Council, which is
absolutely unbearable," added Zhu.
</P>
<P>
"The fact that those in charge of the UNSCOM have hidden such a
serious case for so long despite early awareness of it, can only
arouse strong suspicion about their motives," added Zhu.  
</P>
