<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Euro Drops to New Low </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOGNE, June 3 (Xinhua) -- The euro plummeted to a new low as
the European Union summit opened here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
It dropped to 1.0303 U.S. dollars early Thursday in the Tokyo
foreign exchange market despite the remarks by European Central
Bank Governor Wim Duisenberg Wednesday to boost the currency.
</P>
<P>
It was the lowest point for the single currency since it was
first launched in January this year. It has by now lost one tenth
of its original value.
</P>
<P>
The New York exchange market closed around one euro to 1.0345
dollars Wednesday for an earlier record decline.
</P>
<P>
The European leaders are now under added pressure to find ways
to bolster the European Union's faltering single currency which is
in use now in 11 of the 15 EU states.
</P>
<P>
Foreign exchange traders in Tokyo said that they had been
unimpressed by the remarks of the European central banker, which
pushed the fledgling currency further down.
</P>
<P>
The European leaders are expected to discuss, during their two-
day meeting, issues of Kosovo, common employment policy and common
defense policy.
</P>
<P>
They are scheduled to name a unionwide foreign and security
coordinator. NATO Secretary General Javier Solana is the most
likely candidate for the post. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
