<DOCNO> XIE19990603.0174 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysian Manufacturers Urged to Improve Product Quality </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA KANGSAR, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian International Trade
and Industry Minister Datuk Seri Rafidah Aziz called on
manufacturers in the country to Improve the quality of their
products so as to make them more competitive in the international
markets.
</P>
<P>
She said this to reporters after attending a four-hour briefing
on the Kuala Kangsar parliamentary development projects at the
District Office here on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Rafidah said local manufacturers have increased their
production and export capacity since middle of last year,
especially towards the last quarter, which had helped to increase
Malaysia's trade surplus this year.
</P>
<P>
"The local manufacturers are really taking advantage of the
competitive edge Malaysia has now in terms of cheaper ringgit, but
they cannot expect the situation to last forever since other
countries would also be equally competitive when once their
economy turns around," she said.
</P>
<P>
She said the local manufacturers should produce quality
products at a competitive pricing and with aggressive promotion,
market them abroad.
</P>
<P>
"If we have pricing and cost competitiveness, it will be easier
to maintain our trade surplus situation," she added.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia's trade surplus in April this year grew by 6.2 billion
ringgit (about 1.63 billion U.S. dollars) compared with 3.4
billion ringgit (0.9 billion dollars) recorded in the same month
last year.
</P>
<P>
Touching on the coming Asia Pacific Economic Cooperation (APEC)
meeting in Auckland, New Zealand on June 29-30, Rafidah said,
apart from the follow-up plans decided at the meeting last year,
she would also brief the APEC members on the current economic
situation in the country,
</P>
<P>
It is important among APEC members that there is a clear
understanding of what is happening with each member, said Rafidah,
who is leading the Malaysian delegation to the meeting.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, Malaysia would also look at the progress of
the individual and collective action plans, and to what extent
they have been implemented by the members, she said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
