<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Share Prices Up on Singapore Stock Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Share prices continued to climb
for the third consecutive day this week on Singapore Stock Market
as retail investors locked in profits on their speculative plays.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark Straits Times Index picked up 14.74 points to
close at 1,942.10 points Thursday.
</P>
<P>
A total of 850.24 million units valued at 965.33 million
Singapore dollars (about 559.19 million U.S. dollars) changed
hands. Falls outpaced rises by 227 to 116 with 100 counters
unchanged.
</P>
<P>
Teamsphere topped the volume list as it had 31.59 million
shares traded. 2nd Chance was the second most heavily traded stock
that had 28.30 million units done. KepTl BK was the next with
24.99 million counters changing hands.
</P>
<P>
OUB F headed ascent of the day surging up 70 cents to 9.35
Singapore dollars. C &AMP; C, Creative 50 and Venture ran up 50 cents
each to close at 10.00, 23.00 and 11.60 Singapore dollars
separately. SIA F, SPH, SPH 100 and Semblog were all up 40 cents
and ended at 15.90, 25.40, 25.40 and 5.70 Singapore dollars
respectively.
</P>
<P>
On the downside, Bukit Sem, GE Life, KhongGuan and NatElect
sank 30 cents each and they ended at 18.70, 21.00, 2.40 and 5.50
Singapore dollars respectively. OCBC F ended at 13.90 Singapore
dollars while UOB F closed at 11.60 Singapore dollars, both
retreating 20 cents.
</P>
<P>
Dealers noted Keppel TatLee Bank shares tumbled four percent
after strong opening as the market took a closer look at its
alliance with the Allied Irish Banks.
</P>
<P>
Market observers said the structure of the deal between the two
banks disappointed many investors since it is not a direct stake
sale.  
</P>
</TEXT>
