<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Seoul, Pyongyang to Resume Talks on June 21 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, June 3 (Xinhua) -- South Korea and the Democratic
People's Republic of Korea (DPRK) have agreed to resume their vice-
ministerial talks in Beijing on June 21, said South Korean
Unification Minister Lim Dong-won Thursday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Lim told a press conference that the agreement was signed by
Kim Bo-hyon, special assistant to South Korean Prime Minister Kim
Jong-pil, and Chon Kum-chol, chief councilor of the DPRK's
Administration Council, Thursday morning in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
The June 21 talks will focus on reunion of separated family
members and other mutually-concerned issues.
</P>
<P>
The forthcoming talks resulted from the dialogues between the
two sides in Beijing three times from May 12 to June 3 to prepare
for the official restoration of the suspended talks.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, Seoul will provide Pyongyang with 200,000
tons of fertilizer in June and July this year, of which 100,000
tons will be supplied before June 20.
</P>
<P>
The unification minister's press conference came one day later
than scheduled.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday morning, Shin Eon-sang, spokesman of the
unification ministry, said Seoul and Pyongyang would sign an
agreement in China Wednesday morning to resume the suspended vice-
ministerial meetings.
</P>
<P>
"If the pact is concluded as scheduled, Unification Minister
Lim Dong-won will announce the reopening of governmental level
talks Wednesday afternoon," said Shin.
</P>
<P>
The inter-Korean talks were suspended in Beijing in April 1998
when Seoul and Pyongyang failed to reach agreement over
preconditions such as reunion of separated family members and the
amount of fertilizer provision. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
