<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Barak Asks for Delay on IAF Jet Purchase </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister-elect
Ehud Barak has proposed Israeli Air Force (IAF) postpone plans
to purchase a new generation of fighter planes.
</P>
<P>
Barak put forward his proposal after senior defense officials
briefed him on the IAF's purchase plans, Israeli Ha'aretz daily
reported on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The daily quoted outgoing Defense Minister Moshe Arens as
saying Barak demanded the final decision on the deals be
delayed because he was not sure if the decision to be made
by the defense establishment was correct.
</P>
<P>
IAF has recommended that Arens sign an order to buy 50 F-16
fighter jets from Lockheed-Martin Company for 2.5 billion
U.S. dollars rather than Boeing-made F-15 jets.
</P>
<P>
Arens has not yet voiced his position publicly, but it appears
that talks on buying planes from Boeing or Lockheed-Martin have
been shelved.
</P>
<P>
Defense sources said the decision has to be made in the next
few weeks as any additional delays will result in extra payments
to the American manufacturers and also could deter the delivery of
the chosen planes.
</P>
<P>
Barak won a landslide victory in May 17 elections and he will
have to form a coalition government by July 6. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990603.0186 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Establishes Banking Supervision System (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 3 (Xinhua) -- China has basically established a
banking supervision system in line with Basle Core Principles for
Effective Banking Supervision, according to Chinese and foreign
financial experts and officials.
</P>
<P>
The Basle Committee on Banking Supervision (BCBS), sponsored by
the Bank for International Settlements (BIS), is an international
institution which focuses on developing banking supervision.
</P>
<P>
Related experts point out that reforms in the financial sector
in China over the past few years have helped create an effective
central bank supervision system which continues to reinforce risk
management in the banking sector.
</P>
<P>
Major reforms in the fields of central bank restructuring,
supervision methods, the commercialization of state-owned banks,
financial risk management, and financial laws and regulations have
largely improved the rationality and effectiveness of banking
supervision.
</P>
<P>
The BCBS introduced 25 core principles for effective banking
supervision in September 1997 as part of an effort to provide
effective measures designed to enable various countries to
reinforce their financial stability.
</P>
<P>
The People's Bank of China (PBOC), China's central bank and a
member of BIS, participated in drafting and revising of related
core principles.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990603.0187 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
