<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990603.0188 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Establishes Banking Supervision System (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PBOC Professor Tang Xu said China has introduced reforms of its
financial sector in accordance with the Basle core principles and
has worked diligently to establish modern banking regulations and
supervision principles.
</P>
<P>
"China has established an effective banking supervision system
in line with Basle core principles," said Xu.
</P>
<P>
A primary requirement of the core principles states that
commercial banks must have a capital adequacy rate of at least
eight percent. The fact that assets of Chinese banks have grown in
tandem with the nation's opening and reform drive over the past 20
years has led to relative decline in their capital adequacy rate.
</P>
<P>
China issued 270 billion yuan in special treasury bonds in 1998
in order to replenish capital of state-owned commercial banks and
raise their capital adequacy rate to the standards required by the
core principles, according to Xu.
</P>
<P>
Kathie Krumm, World Bank lead economist for China, said China
has worked to stem problems to the flow of non-performing loans by
introducing a risk-based loan classification system, consolidating
the central bank's network of branches along regional lines to
enhance supervision and reduce local government interference, and
resolving problems at some small troubled financial institutions.
</P>
<P>
She noted that related measures endorse the core principles and
are effectively addressing the weaknesses of the financial sector.
However, she warned that continued efforts will be a critical
factor in further minimizing financial risks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990603.0189 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Establishes Banking Supervision System (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Davin Mackenzie, chief China representative for International
Finance Corporation (IFC), said the affirmative results of China's
banking reform are beginning to surface, with state-owned banks
gradually acting as commercial entities.
</P>
<P>
He said the establishment of Cinda Asset Management Corp.,
which will assume non-performing loans held by the China
Construction Bank, represents a giant step forward in the
government's effort to tackle the bad loans of state-owned
commercial banks.
</P>
<P>
Tang said that the revocation of the credit ceiling on
commercial banks in early 1998 was a significant step toward the
commercialization of banks. The adoption of asset-liability
management represented a fundamental transition from a planned to
a market system and has enabled the central bank to use more
indirect tools to control the financial market.
</P>
<P>
The central bank's financial supervision currently enjoys an
appropriate legal environment, according to Tang. China has
adopted over 200 laws and regulations directly related to
financial supervision since 1995, including central bank,
commercial bank and insurance laws.
</P>
<P>
Experts point out that China's banking reforms have not only
followed the core principles, but have also fully considered the
country's special conditions and are thus crucial for ensuring the
steady and healthy development of the banking sector.
</P>
<P>
However, they point out that challenges surrounding the
effective implementation of reform initiatives require skill and
good judgment on the part of bank officials and regulators. They
also note that extensive training will be required to ensure
further development. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
