<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Government to Boost Vocational Education </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 3 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government has
allocated 1.07 billion pesos (26.75 million U.S. dollars) this
year to boost development of human resources through formal
technical-vocational education and training.
</P>
<P>
The Department of Labor and Employment (DOLE) said Thursday
that the amount comprised about 50 percent of the 2.1 billion peso
(52.5 million U.S. dollar) budget which the Congress allotted to
DOLE's Technical and Skills Development Authority (TESDA) this
year.
</P>
<P>
Labor Secretary Bienvenido Laguesma said that overall, TESDA's
thrusts and programs are geared at developing the right skills to
maximize gainful employment while helping uplift the country's
poor and disadvantaged communities.
</P>
<P>
He emphasized that technical-vocational schools are important
in pushing the emergence of world-class Filipino workers crucial
to the country's economic progress.
</P>
<P>
Specifically, the 1.07 billion pesos (26.75 million U.S.
dollars) was intended mainly for the operation of 28 trade and 30
agricultural, agro-industrial, fishery and home industry schools
in various regions of the country.
</P>
<P>
Clifford Paragua, executive director of TESDA's Office of
Formal Technical-Vocational Education and Training said around
9,980 students graduated from these 58 TESDA-supervised schools in
secondary and post-secondary levels in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Paragua said their enrollees are expected to approach 50,000 in
1999.
</P>
<P>
Apart from TESDA-supervised institutions, there were also more
than 1,300 private and 700 public institutions providing
technical-vocational education and training to people in the
country last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
