<DOCNO> XIE19990603.0201 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pro-Israeli Militia Completes Pullout from Jezzine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, June 3 (Xinhua) -- The pro-Israeli South Lebanon Army
(SLA) early Thursday completed its three-day withdrawal
from Jezzine, a town in south Lebanon it has held for 14 years.
</P>
<P>
Truck convoys were seen streaming out of the beleaguered town,
carrying artillery and mortar guns, equipment, ammunition and
household furniture to the Israeli occupied border zone southeast
of Jezzine.
</P>
<P>
Following the withdrawal widely seen as a prelude to the
Israeli pullout from Lebanon, Lebanese police units crossed into
Jezzine and set up checkpoints at the entrance of the town.
</P>
<P>
Lebanese policemen have been sent to take over the security of
more than 20 villages around the town, which were vacated by the
SLA in the past two days.
</P>
<P>
Although Israeli warplanes provided air cover for the
withdrawal, the retreating SLA still met with Hezbollah
guerrilla's attacks, in which three militiamen were killed and
another one wounded in the past two days.
</P>
<P>
Israeli forces retaliated by staging dozens of air raids on
Hezbollah targets close to the withdrawal route, wounding three
Syrian laborers and a Lebanese woman.
</P>
<P>
The SLA decided to withdraw from Jezzine due to Lebanese
guerrillas' attacks that have killed more than 100 SLA militiamen
and wounded about 400 others around Jezzine in the past 14 years.
</P>
<P>
The 2,500-strong SLA, financed and trained by the Israeli
forces, was established in 1985 with an aim of helping Israel
soldiers patrol the security zone which it set up in south Lebanon
to shield its northern area from Lebanese guerrilla cross-border
attacks.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian-backed Hezbollah, or Party of God, has been
leading a war of attrition trying to oust the Israeli occupation
forces and its proxy SLA out of the country.
</P>
<P>
After the SLA departure, the most pressing issue in Jezzine is
the fate of 203 SLA militiamen who opted to turn themselves over
to the Lebanese authorities.
</P>
<P>
Lebanese Prime Minister Salim Hoss has pledged that they will
not be revenged and will be dealt with by the judiciary according
to their various circumstances.
</P>
<P>
Judicial sources said that the defected SLA members will be
tried before court on charges of collaborating with Israel but
all will be provided with extenuating circumstances. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990603.0202 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China To Carry Out Lightning Tests </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Chinese scientists are to carry out
a series of experiments to artificially induce lightning in a bid
to study its reactions and effects in order to test the capability
of conductors and to try and prevent future disasters and
accidents from lightning strikes.
</P>
<P>
The experiments will be conducted in the vicinity of Guangzhou,
capital of south China's Guangdong Province, where lightning
happens frequently from mid-June to July.
</P>
<P>
Zhou Liangcai, a leading researcher from the Guangdong
Electronic Power Research Institute, explained that small rockets
with long, metal wire tails will be fired into the clouds which
will hopefully create the conditions which encourage lightning.
</P>
<P>
The position and time of the artificially induced lightning can
therefore be predicted, and will thus enable analysis and tests on
the actual mechanism and force of lightning, according to Zhou and
his colleagues.
</P>
<P>
"The small rockets, no larger than winebottles, can travel as
high as 1.23 kilometers into the clouds," said Zhou.
</P>
<P>
But he admitted that the experiment is often very difficult
because the rockets sometimes fail to induce lightning. Last year
the institute carried out five successful trial experiments.
</P>
<P>
According to Yao Jianguo, an expert with the Science and
Environmental Protection Department of China State Power
Corporation (CSPC), micro-electronic technology has been developed
rapidly and used widely in recent years.
</P>
<P>
"At the same time, the threats from lightning strikes to the
electronic power system, communications, aviation and other high-
tech fields are becoming more serious," said Yao.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that economic losses caused by lightning
strikes in China exceeds one billion yuan (about 120 million US
dollars) every year.
</P>
<P>
Yao said that although many lightning conductors have been
developed, they have not been properly tested under real and
natural conditions.
</P>
<P>
In addition, detailed research on lightning is difficult and
complicated to carry out because of its very random nature.
</P>
<P>
According to Zhou Liangcai, many advanced observation and
recording facilities will be used in this latest experiment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990603.0203 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China, Ford Develop Luxury Car </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 3 (Xinhua) -- A new luxury car for the China
market is being jointly developed by the US Ford Motor Company and
the China First Automobile Group which hopes that the new Red Flag
model will be launched by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
Hua Shaozhong, deputy director of the Technical Center of China
First Automobile Group Corporation announced details of the
project at the Auto Parts, Manufacturing and Related Products Show
which is being held here this week.
</P>
<P>
The car will be based on Ford's well known Lincoln model and
will also use some of the technical features of the existing Red
Flag luxury cars manufactured by the Chinese company.
</P>
<P>
Hua explained that the look of the new car will not be exactly
like the Lincoln. And it will be significantly distinct from
conventional Red Flag cars which are modified versions of
Germany's Volkswagen Audi models.
</P>
<P>
The new Red Flag car will be the top grade luxury car made in
China.
</P>
<P>
The First Automobile Group Corporation is the largest
automotive company in China and like the Shanghai Automotive
Industry Corporation (SAIC), China's second largest car
manufacturer, has set up a joint venture with Volkswagen.
</P>
<P>
SAIC has already jointly developed a B5 car with Volkswagen for
the China market. The B5 car is a modified version of the Passatt
car that Volkswagen developed in the mid 1990s.
</P>
<P>
The decision by the First Automobile Group Corp. to jointly
develop new cars is because it feels its current range based on
the Volkswagen is relatively outdated; hence its decision to
choose Ford and the Lincoln. The company is also looking for
further opportunities to jointly develop more advanced cars with
foreign auto makers.
</P>
<P>
Ford has also now begun manufacturing Transit vans in China.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
