<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0900 GMT, June 3 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
VIENNA -- Austrian Prime Minister Viktor Klima said here
Wednesday that the European Union (EU) would not turn itself into
a military bloc even if it made considerable progress in mutual
diplomatic and security policies.
</P>
<P>
Before leaving for the forthcoming EU Summit in Koln, Germany,
Klima told reporters that if the regional organization appeared as
a military group with mutual commitments, it would bring no good
to the group itself, to its enlargement and to Europe as a whole.
(Klima-EU)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ZAGREB -- The talks between Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic and the Balkans envoys from Russia and the European
Union (EU) entered the second day, in which the peace plan agreed
by the West and Russia was discussed, said reports reaching here
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The plan, the exact details of which remained unclear, had been
delivered by Russia's Balkans envoy Viktor Chernomyrdin and
Finnish President Martti Ahtisaar, who represents the EU, to
Milosevic when they arrived in Belgrade on Wednesday. (Yugoslavia-
Peace Talks)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
HARARE -- Zimbabwe has accused Rwanda of violating its
unilateral cease-fire declaration in Congo (K) by attacking
Southern African Development Community allied forces positions in
Kalanga, Manono and Lusambo.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe Defense Forces spokesman Colonel Chancellor Diye said
Wednesday a Rwandan brigade had attacked the allied forces'
position near Lake Tanganyika over the weekend, resulting in a
four-day battle. (Zimbabwe-Rwandan Violation)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- A Palestinian man was killed by Israeli soldiers
Thursday in the West Bank town of Hebron, a Palestinian source
said.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli soldiers shot dead the man at a military checkpoint
outside his village of Sammou in Hebron, saying he is trying to
break into the checkpoint, the Palestinian news service the
Jerusalem Media and Communication Center said. (Israel-
Palestinian)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MANILA -- The Philippine Government declared Thursday the 22-
day strike by the Airline Pilots Association of the Philippines (
ALPAP) last year as "illegal" and affirmed that the strikers had
lost their employment status with Philippine Airlines (PAL).
</P>
<P>
The Department of Labor and Employment (DOLE) said in a seven-
page decision that the strike was "procedurally infirm" and in "
open defiance" of DOLE's return-to-work order. (Philippines-PAL
Strike)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
SEOUL -- South Korea and the Democratic People's Republic of
Korea (DPRK) have agreed to resume their vice- ministerial talks
in Beijing on June 21, said South Korean Unification Minister Lim
Dong-won Thursday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Lim told a press conference that the agreement was signed by
Kim Bo-hyon, special assistant to South Korean Prime Minister Kim
Jong-pil, and Chon Kum-chol, chief councilor of the DPRK's
Administration Council, Thursday morning in Beijing. (Korea-Talks)
