<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Successful Cloud Seeding Ensures HK's Water Supply </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGCHUN, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Successful cloud seeding above
Shenzhen City of south China's Guangdong Province in the past
month has alleviated city's eight month long water shortages and
has ensured water supplies to Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Shenzhen has been hit by a severe drought since last September.
In the first four months of the year, the volume of rainfall was
just 75 mm, a quarter of the previous level for the same period.
</P>
<P>
The water, stored in different reservoirs in Shenzhen, dropped
to its lowest level ever, causing water shortages throughout the
city and affecting people's daily life. The water crisis in
Shenzhen, a major fresh-water base, also affected its water supply
to the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region.
</P>
<P>
From April 24, six experts from the Cloud Seeding and Hail
Prevention Office of Jilin Province were called in and carried out
16 successful cloud seeding operations in the skies above
Shenzhen's reservoirs, producing an average of 124 mm of rainfall
and enormously alleviating the drought in this special economic
zone.
</P>
<P>
The Jilin Cloud Seeding Office is the oldest in China and also
boasts the only open laboratory in China which can influence the
weather. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
