<HEADLINE> Duty-Free Stores Sell More Domestic Consumer Goods </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Chinese-manufactured commodities
currently account for 15 percent of the total sale volume for
China's duty-free stores, according to Gai Zhixin, president of
the China National Duty-Free Corporation.
</P>
<P>
The State Council has granted approval for duty-free stores to
sell six categories of Chinese products, including tobacco, wine,
handicrafts, silk and garments.
</P>
<P>
Sales of Chinese manufactured products in duty-free stores not
only promotes related items, but also places constraints on the
ability of some foreign suppliers to demand irrational prices.
</P>
<P>
China had 140 duty-free outlets by the end of May this year,
with stores in operation prior to 1997 limited to sales of foreign
products.
</P>
<P>
The duty-free sector has generated foreign exchange of over 1.7
billion US dollars over the past 20 years, according to Gai.
</P>
</TEXT>
