<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Results of S. African Election to Be Out Thursday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
At some stations balloting extended into late night, several
hours later than the 9:00 p.m. regulation time because of long
queues.
</P>
<P>
Political parties were almost unanimous in agreement, saying
their agents at voting stations had reported very high turn-outs
and enthusiastic voters.
</P>
<P>
Early Thursday morning, the fortunes of the political parties
changed second by second as the first results of the election
started flashing on the giant electronic screen at the Independent
Electoral Commission (IEC) center in Pretoria.
</P>
<P>
As expected, the African National Congress (ANC) took the
lead, followed by the New National Party (NNP) and Democratic
Party (DP). But analysts warned it was far too early to predict
the outcome.
</P>
<P>
The IEC had decided not to delay the counting process, even in
areas where the polls closed long after the regulation time to
prevent a recurrence of incidents in 1994 when ballot boxes, left
at voting stations overnight, were tampered with, election
officials said.
</P>
<P>
The officials said verified result will be announced at the
earliest at 9 p.m. Thursday. This gives political parties enough
time to object to aspects of the electoral process.
</P>
<P>
The IEC, however, may delay the announcement of the result for
seven days to deal with possible objections. The IEC expected the
bulk of the counting to be completed by Thursday afternoon.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
