<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa's ANC Leads in Poll </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 3 (Xinhua) -- As expected, South Africa's
African National Congress (ANC) is leading in the second
democratic general election, but a two-thirds majority seems out
of reach, initial results show.
</P>
<P>
With 54 percent of the country's voting districts declared
Thursday morning, the ANC won 62 percent of the eight million
votes counted so far.
</P>
<P>
The Democratic Party (DP) came in as the second, with 12
percent. This may well indicate that the DP is going to replace
the New National Party (NNP) as the new official opposition. The
NNP got nine percent of the eight million votes, followed by the
Inkatha Freedom Party (IFP) with eight percent.
</P>
<P>
Although more than 18.1 million people had registered to vote,
it was not clear what the voter turn-out was by Thursday morning.
</P>
<P>
In the provincial elections, the ANC has secured seven of the
country's nine provinces, according to projections by the South
African Broadcasting Corporation television.
</P>
<P>
The seven provinces are Northern Province, North-West,
Mpumalanga, Free State, Northern Cape, Gauteng and Eastern Cape.
</P>
<P>
The other two provinces, the Western Cape and KwaZulu-Natal,
are still hotly contested between the ANC and the NNP, and the ANC
and the IFP respectively. 
</P>
</TEXT>
