<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 07:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dubai Bans Entry of Poultry Products From Belgium </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DAHBI, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Municipality of Dubai, the second
largest emirate of the United Arab Emirate (UAE), has instructed
all its ports to ban the entry of poultry products from Belgium
following the dioxin-contaminated chicken scandal.
</P>
<P>
"As soon as the municipality learned of the possibility of
contamination in chicken products from Belgium, it stopped the
entry of these products into Dubai," said Rashid Ahmad bin Fahad,
head of the Food and Environment Lab at the Dubai Central
Laboratory.
</P>
<P>
Fahad said a meeting will be held at the General Secretariat of
UAE Municipalities next week to discuss the issue, the Khaleej
Times daily reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
He assured consumers that no contaminated products will be sold
in the market of Dubai, which is also an important commercial and
trade center in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, the European Union has decided to trace and
destroy all eggs and chicken-based foodstuffs which could be
contaminated with the cancer-causing chemical dioxin.
</P>
<P>
The chicken crisis was caused by a Belgian company, which has
been providing contaminated fat to European feed manufacturers
since January. Many farms in Belgium and other European countries
have been affected. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
