<BODY>
<HEADLINE> COMESA to Monitor Money Laundering: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, June 3 (Xinhua) -- A senior official of the Common
Market for Eastern and Southern Africa (COMESA) has said the issue
of money laundering is challenging the regional grouping which
intends to establish a free trade area in October next year.
</P>
<P>
However, said Sindiso Ngwenya, deputy secretary-general of
COMESA, the problem of money laundering in COMESA member states
will not disrupt the achieving of a free trade area, Thursday's
Zambia Daily Mail reported.
</P>
<P>
Making the assurance here Wednesday, the deputy
secretary-general said working committees which comprise bank
governors of member states were working round the clock to check
the illegal operations.
</P>
<P>
The committee of bank governors always exchanges information
from their various countries on financial problems like money
laundering, he added.
</P>
<P>
"Member countries are already monitoring the issue of money
laundering in their respective countries and the information is
usually exchanged with their fellow partners during regular
meeting," Ngwenya said.
</P>
<P>
International Criminal Police Organization also helps in
tracking down dealers in the illegal trade, he said.
</P>
<P>
Ngwenya observed that with the cooperation of law enforcement
agencies within member states, the region has been able to put in
check the levels of money laundering.
</P>
<P>
"It is a collective effort which needs collaboration with all
stake- holders in the region because the people laundering money
are always ahead which makes it difficult if information is not
shared among member states," he said.
</P>
<P>
Ngwenya said the malpractice should be dealt with viciously in
the various member states because it is a danger to their
economies which in turn will affect their partnership within
COMESA since their economies will be distorted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990603.0219 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya Sets Economic Growth Target for 1999 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 3 (Xinhua) -- The Kenyan government has set an
economic growth target of 2.3 percent for 1999, Vice-President
George Saitoti said here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
This is a radical departure from the under two percent that was
 predicted by a top official from the Central Bank of Kenya just
two weeks ago, the Daily Nation newspaper reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The official had based his evaluation on the performance of the
economy for the past five months of 1999, during which economic
growth had stagnated in the lower 1.7 percent range.
</P>
<P>
The 1999 economic survey report released by Saitoti Wednesday
said that last year the economy grew by 1.8 percent against an
economic survey projection of three percent.
</P>
<P>
According to this year's survey report, the 2.3 percent rate is
pegged on hopes that the country will receive adequate and
reliable rains, tight monetary policies will be followed and
donors will renew disbursement of aid to Kenya.
</P>
<P>
Saitoti said the factors which resulted in a decline in the
economic growth were mainly the continued unreliable
infrastructure, depressed investment, declining tourism
activities, a slump in manufacturing production, high interest
rates, rising costs of farm inputs and a fall in world prices of
coffee and horticulture.
</P>
<P>
He added that the Nairobi bomb blast and increased insecurity
generally also combined to stem the flow of tourists to the
country.
</P>
<P>
However, the vice-president expressed his optimism that with
the expected major reforms in the government finances aimed at
reducing the public domestic debt and budget deficit, and the
improvement of the revenue collection system, the country's
economic performance would be enhanced.
</P>
<P>
Local analysts have said the country needs to attain an annual
growth rate of six to eight percent to realize the proposed
newly-industrialized
nation status by 2020. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
