<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kaunda not allowed to Stand for Zambian Presidency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Former Zambian President Kenneth
Kaunda will not be allowed to stand for presidency in the
elections in 2001 because of his stateless status, a senior
government minister has said.
</P>
<P>
Minister Without Portfolio Michael Sata said Wednesday in
Ndola, northern Zambia, that Kaunda is aware of his predicament
and the best way for him is to regularize his nationality because
he is neither Zambian nor Malawian.
</P>
<P>
Sata, who is national secretary of the country's ruling party,
said, "if he wants to stand in 2001, let him regularize his
nationality first because he knows the requirements of our
constitution."
</P>
<P>
Kaunda's United National Independence Party (UNIP) insists it
will field Kaunda in the elections.
</P>
<P>
UNIP information secretary Bwendo Mulengela said here Wednesday
that Kaunda has indicated that he would like to retire from
politics after spearheading the comeback of his party to
government.
</P>
<P>
In March this year Kaunda, who had been ruling the country
since its independence in 1964 until 1991, when he was defeated by
current President Frederick Chiluba, was declared stateless by
the Ndola High Court.
</P>
<P>
The judgement means Kaunda, who was born of Malawian parents,
is neither a Zambian nor a Malawian.
</P>
<P>
Kaunda was barred from running for the presidency in the
elections held in 1996, when a constitutional amendment was
adopted under which foreign nationals and those with foreign
parentage are prohibited from contesting the position.
</P>
<P>
Kaunda has vowed to contest the post in the next elections in
2001. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990603.0224 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraqi Deputy PM Slams NATO Aggression on Yugoslavia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Iraq's Deputy Prime Minister Tariq
Aziz has described the U.S.-led NATO aggression on Yugoslavia as a
terroristic act and an attempt to eliminate any independent
tendency in the world.
</P>
<P>
In a televised interview aired on Wednesday evening, Aziz said
the U.S.-NATO aggression on an independent state does not bear
any legitimacy, adding each independent state has become
threatened in a deal or another by the American arrogance.
</P>
<P>
Aziz said Europe's involvement in the aggression on Yugoslavia
has led to the refugees crisis.
</P>
<P>
He affirmed that so many European states would sustain
problems due to the U.S.-NATO aggression on Yugoslavia, pointing
out that Romania is now suffering from suffocating economic
crisis.
</P>
