<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila Declares PAL Pilots' Strike Illegal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 3 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine Government declared
Thursday the 22-day strike by the Airline Pilots Association of
the Philippines (ALPAP) last year as "illegal" and affirmed that
the strikers had lost their employment status with Philippine
Airlines (PAL).
</P>
<P>
The Department of Labor and Employment (DOLE) said in a
seven-page decision that the strike was "procedurally infirm" and
in "open defiance" of DOLE's return-to-work order.
</P>
<P>
The decision also dismissed ALPAP's complaint that PAL
management had illegally locked them out.
</P>
<P>
"This Office hereby declares the loss of employment status of
all officers and members who participated in the strike in
defiance of the return-to-work order of June 7, 1998.
Concomitantly, PAL cannot be deemed to have illegally locked out
the striking pilots as it was their collective will to defy the
said Order," the DOLE ruled.
</P>
<P>
ALPAP staged the strike on June 5, 1998 despite two previous
orders from the DOLE strictly prohibiting such action while it
assumed jurisdiction over the dispute.
</P>
<P>
On June 7, 1998, the DOLE issued a return-to-work order,
expiring 24 hours later, but the department was unable to serve
this on ALPAP because the latter's counsel repeatedly snubbed it.
</P>
<P>
ALPAP finally consented to receive the DOLE's return-to-work
order on June 26, 1998, when it unilaterally declared an end to
the strike.
</P>
<P>
The strike stemmed from a dispute on the retirement of an ALPAP
member, Capt. Albino Collantes, whom PAL management retired based
on a provision of the PAL-ALPAP Retirement Plan, which is part of
the Collective Bargaining Agreement between the two parties.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
