<HEADLINE> No Change To Overseas Investment Policy: Minister (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The MOFTEC minister said that the success of the two companies
shows that while overseas invested companies have gained profits
in China, they have also helped the country's economic growth.
</P>
<P>
"China will continue to improve its investment environment,
both soft and hard," he pledged. "We will also make the investment
policy stable and continue to refine the policy."
</P>
<P>
Overseas investments in China declined both in contractual and
materialized volume in the first four months of the year. By the
end of April, there were nearly 330,000 overseas-funded firms in
China, involving a total contractual investment volume of 580
billion US dollars, and arrived investment of 270 billion US
dollars.
</P>
<P>
The minister said that China regards foreign-invested companies
as its own as they were registered in China. "We will try our best
to serve them and protect their legitimate interests and rights,"
he added.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile the minister urged overseas-invested ventures to
explore markets not only within China, but also in Asia and the
entire world. He also urged them to pay attention to technology
upgrading and China's industrial restructuring so as to have a
better development.
</P>
<P>
In addition, he hoped that joint ventures like Nokia and
Ericsson can use more locally-made instruments and parts. 
</P>
