<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe has accused Rwanda of
violating its unilateral cease-fire declaration in Congo (K) by
attacking Southern African Development Community allied forces
positions in Kalanga, Manono and Lusambo.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe Defense Forces spokesman Colonel Chancellor Diye said
Wednesday a Rwandan brigade had attacked the allied forces'
position near Lake Tanganyika over the weekend, resulting in a
four-day battle.
</P>
<P>
Up to 86 Rwandans were killed in the battle and an assortment
of military hardware, including picks and shovels the enemy used
to dig trenches, were recovered, the daily Herald reported
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said the rebels have been trying to capture the
diamond- rich town of Mbuji-Mayi and Manono, the birthplace of
Congolese President Laurent Kabila, to use as bargaining chips
during talks scheduled for Lusaka, Zambia, on June 26.
</P>
<P>
"The Rwandans are breaching their own cease-fire declaration.
They have made several attempts to take control of Manono, but
they have been denied on several occasions," said Diye.
</P>
<P>
Last Friday, Rwanda proclaimed a unilateral cease-fire in Congo
(K), where it has deployed thousands of troops in support of
rebels fighting to oust President Kabila, said the report.
</P>
<P>
However, Congolese Deputy Minister of Defense Dieudonne Kayembe
told a press briefing in Kinshasa Tuesday that Rwandan troops
launched "offensive actions" in central Kasai and south-eastern
Katanga provinces following heavy losses they suffered last month.
</P>
<P>
He accused Rwanda of seeking to use last Friday's announcement
of a unilateral cessation of hostilities to buy "time to breathe"
following military setbacks in the fighting. 
</P>
