<HEADLINE> S. Leone Rebels Removes Roadblock </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Sierra Leonean rebels have removed a
roadblock on a highway serving as the supply line for the west
African peace keeping force ECOMOG, local radio reported.
</P>
<P>
But travellers in this west African country said tension
remained high in other parts of the country, and the two sides
has been accusing each other of truce violations.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the ECOMOG force confirmed the removal of the
block the rebels erected Tuesday at Okra Hill, about 60 kms from
capital Freetown.
</P>
<P>
The highway which was blocked is used by the Nigeria-led ECOMOG
force backing the Sierra Leonean government to provide supplies
for its troops in the country's interior areas.
</P>
<P>
The rebels had once guarded their blocks with heavy machine
guns, said the report.
</P>
<P>
The ECOMOG force had complained to the U.N. Observer Mission in
Sierra Leone and warned that the ECOMOG may strike in the next
few days if the United Nations failed in mediation.
</P>
<P>
The rebels followed the U.N.'s suggestions and removed the
blocks thus saving the fragile cease fire.
</P>
<P>
The cease fire taking effect on May 24 in a bid to nurture
atmosphere for peace talks held in Togo has been largely
respected, reports said.
</P>
<P>
The talks, jointly brokered by the Economic Community of West
Africa States (ECOWAS) and United Nations have made some progress
though the thorny dispute on a transitional government remains.
</P>
<P>
The rebels suggest that they must share power with President
Tejan Kabbah in a transitional government until a new election is
held, while Kabbah insists that the rebels must transform
themselves into a political party and compete in the general
election. 
</P>
</TEXT>
