<HEADLINE> Fuel Prices Go Up In Zimbabwe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Petrol price in Zimbabwe rose by 27
percent from 9.67 Zimbabwean dollars (25 U.S. cents) to 12.25
Zimbabwean dollars (32 U.S. cents) a litre Thursday to cope with
the devaluation of the Zimbabwean dollar and the cost of fuel at
its source.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, diesel price was up by 32 percent from 8.1 Zimbabwean
dollars (21 U.S. cents) to 10.68 Zimbabwean dollars (28 U.S.
cents) a litre.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Transport and Energy Enos Chikowore said in a
statement Wednesday night that two critical factors have
necessitated the present adjustment of fuel prices.
</P>
<P>
They are the depreciation of the Zimbabwean dollar by 107
percent since July 1998 to the current rate of some 38.7
Zimbabwean dollars to the U.S. dollar; and the marked increased
cost of fuel product at source, which left the National Oil
Company of Zimbabwe (NOCZIM) selling fuel at 30 to 40 percent
below cost.
</P>
<P>
Despite the increase, he said, the price of local fuel was
still far below prices in other countries in the region. 
</P>
