<DOCNO> XIE19990603.0242 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya's Inflation Up in May </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Kenya's average month on month
inflation in May rose to 4.5 percent, up from 2.5 percent in
April, the Central Bank of Kenya (CBK) has said.
</P>
<P>
The central bank said Wednesday that the underlying average
annual inflation fell to 6. 7 percent in May from 7.3 percent in
April and the overall average inflation fell to 3.3 percent from
3.5 percent, the East African Standard reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The bank's chief economist Maurice Kanga said liquidity on the
domestic market tightened in the week to May 28 and the interbank
interest rate increased from 5.59 percent at the beginning of the
week to 7.09 percent at the end of the week.
</P>
<P>
Economists here said the inflationary rate was pushed up
largely by the high cost of foodstuffs due to the prevailing dry
conditions and the weakening shilling which was also pushing
inflation up since imports are more expensive compared to a month
or two ago.
</P>
<P>
The week saw the base lending rate in commercial banks declined
from 19. 15 percent to 19.07 percent, with the lowest at 15
percent and the highest standing at 25 percent.
</P>
<P>
On exchange rates, the shilling continued receiving a battering
from the main hard currencies.
</P>
<P>
The average exchange rates in the week were 70.46 shillings to
the U. S. dollar, 112.87 shillings to the pound and 73.48
shillings to the euro compared to 69.57 shillings, 111.91
shillings and 73.91 shillings to the dollar, the pound and the
euro respectively in the previous week, said the bank. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
