<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Intestine Transplant Reported Successful </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Beijing-based Guangming Daily quoted a surgery team at
Xijing Hospital, in northwest China's Xi'an City, as saying that a
150 centimeter long small intestine, provided by the recipient's
father, has survived in his body, which enables him to now take
food and to walk.
</P>
<P>
"However, he will have to endure a process of rejection
reaction, which is expected to be very strong due to abundant
lymphocyte contained in the small intestine, thus making the
recovery fairly difficult," said Wang Weizhong, who led the 60-
person team.
</P>
<P>
The surgery on May 20 was unusual for the transplanted small
intestine was taken from a living person. "Only five similar
transplants have taken place: in the United States, Britain and
Japan, and this one marks a prominent breakthrough in human organ
transplants in China," the newspaper said today.
</P>
<P>
The recipient, Yang Feng, a farmer of Lushi County of Henan
Province, had most of his small intestine removed last September
as a result of obstruction. He suffered from serious diarrhea and
weight loss, the report said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
