<HEADLINE> Peace Talks Continue in Belgrade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZAGREB, June 3 (Xinhua) -- The talks between Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milosevic and the Balkans envoys from Russia and the
European Union (EU) entered the second day, in which the peace
plan agreed by the West and Russia was discussed, said reports
reaching here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The plan, the exact details of which remained unclear, had been
delivered by Russia's Balkans envoy Viktor Chernomyrdin and
Finnish President Martti Ahtisaar, who represents the EU, to
Milosevic when they arrived in Belgrade on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The NATO-Russia agreement on the plan was reached during the
talks near Bonn among Chernomyrdin, Ahtisaar and U.S. Deputy
Secretary of State Strobe Talbott. ITAR-Tass quoted Chernomyrdin
as saying that the agreement calls on Yugoslavia and NATO to work
out a formula for the withdrawal of Serbian troops from Kosovo and
deployment of "an international presence," which will be followed
by a "bombing pause."
</P>
<P>
Chernomyrdin said NATO and Russia would send troops to Kosovo
as part of a peacekeeping presence with the United Nations'
approval and support. However, he ruled out the West option of
putting the Russian peacekeepers under the NATO command.
</P>
<P>
Until now, Yugoslavia rejects any foreign military presence on
its soil with NATO at the core and calls on NATO to stop bombing
before any peace deal is clinched.
</P>
<P>
In Belgrade, an official accompanying Ahtisaar was quoted as
saying that the Yugoslav leadership raised some questions during
Wednesday's talks. But he declined to elaborate.
</P>
<P>
Chernomyrdin was quoted as saying after the talks that "It's
hard to talk about chances, but there is hope."
</P>
<P>
Another report said that the Serbian parliament would discuss
the plan on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
However, NATO did not stop its fierce bombardment amid the
ongoing peace efforts. NATO jets had raided Serb forces in Kosovo
on Tuesday and Wednesday and U.S. President Bill Clinton had
ordered to dispatch 7,000 more troops to the Balkans. 
</P>
</TEXT>
