<HEADLINE> NZ State-Owned Coal Company to Cut Staff </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Solid Energy, a state-owned coal
company in New Zealand, is laying off 120 of its 536 staff across
the country.
</P>
<P>
The company has been hit by a big slump in world coal prices
and a depressed steel industry, one of its main customers. It lost
34 million NZ dollars (18.5 million U.S. dollars) in the second
half of last year.
</P>
<P>
The New Zealand government tried to sell Solid Energy last
year, but failed to get the price it wanted. The company had a
book value of 120 million NZ dollars (66 million U.S. dollars),
but bids fell well below 100 million NZ dollars (55 million U.S.
dollars).
</P>
<P>
"Without restructuring, the company would not be able to
exist," Chairman Tim Saunders of the company was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The Dominion, a Wellington-based newspaper, reported Thursday
that the company has announced it would lay off 120 staff
including 68 miners by the end of the year. It would also shut
down offices in Wellington, Auckland and Huntly. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
