<DOCNO> XIE19990603.0249 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Zealand Expects Increase in Wine Exports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, June 3 (Xinhua) -- New Zealand expects to double
its
wine exports to 33.7 million liters worth 275 million NZ dollars
(151
million U.S. dollars) by the year 2003.
</P>
<P>
The projections are based on the present 10 tons a hectare
average grape yield, according to a survey by the Wine Institute
of
New Zealand of owners of the country's 14 largest vineyards,
representing 88 percent of New Zealand wine production.
</P>
<P>
The survey, which was made public Thursday, said the value is a

giant leap from 1990 when 4 million liters of wine worth 18.4
million
NZ dollars (10 million U.S. dollars) were exported. Last year, New

Zealand exported about 16 million liters of wine worth more than
100
million NZ dollars (55 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Chief Executive Philip Gregan of the Wine Institute said export

wine is rapidly becoming the dominant part of production in New
Zealand.
</P>
<P>
More than half of the total New Zealand sales would be in
export
wine by 2003, compared with 30 percent this year and only 20
percent
in 1995, he said.
</P>
<P>
The main markets -- Britain, Australia and the United States --

are expected to continue to dominate the export trade, according
to
Gregan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
