<HEADLINE> New Zealand Businesses Urged to Assess Y2K Bug </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, June 3 (Xinhua) -- New Zealand's many small and
medium-sized businesses with computer equipment have not yet
started
assessing the risk of being affected by the millennium bug.
</P>
<P>
In its surveys, New Zealand Y2K Readiness Commission said
Thursday that 17 percent of small and medium-sized businesses with

computers and electronic equipment have still not started to
assess
their risk.
</P>
<P>
Y2K Readiness Commissioner Basil Logan said he was particularly

concerned by the slow rate of progress by small and medium-sized
businesses.
</P>
<P>
Many companies including some large ones, he added, have over-
estimated their ability to deal with the threat or underestimated
the
complexity of the problem.
</P>
<P>
However, Logan said he is pleased that local authorities can
express "a high level of confidence in their ability to provide
water and waste water services."
</P>
<P>
"They are also expressing confidence in the providers of other
essential services such as power and telecommunication companies,"
he
added. 
</P>
