<DOCNO> XIE19990603.0256 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Work-for-Food Program Yields Benefits </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 3 (Xinhua) -- China's "Work-for-Food Program", an
innovative poverty relief program designed to assist backward
inland areas, has proved highly successful, according to the State
Development Planning Commission (SDPC).
</P>
<P>
Recent SDPC statistics show that some 80 billion yuan (9.7
billion US dollars) flowed into the program between 1984 to 1998,
with some 50 percent of the funding coming from the central
government.
</P>
<P>
The Work-for-Food Program contrasts sharply to the former
method of simply distributing relief funds to poverty-stricken
areas. Instead, the program provides employment and wages for
people living in related areas.
</P>
<P>
Analysts note that the program has played a pivotal role in
improving the infrastructure in China's poverty-stricken areas.
</P>
<P>
Roads stretching 300,000 km. have been built or renovated, and
irrigation facilities serving over five million ha have been
either been constructed or upgraded over the past 15 years.
</P>
<P>
The program has been a major factor in helping to control
erosion in areas covering 42,000 sq.km. and in providing potable
water to over 63 million people.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government previously provided subsidies in the
form of various goods to poverty-stricken areas. Since 1996,
however, the Work-for-Food Program has transformed in-kind good
into wages. Last year alone the government issued one billion yuan
in treasury bonds to support poverty relief efforts in related
areas.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990603.0257 </DOCNO>
