held in November at a Las Vegas casino.
</P>
<P>
"There's no deal," HBO vice president Lou DiBella said. "There
are some problematic issues that need to be worked out. We're
hopeful we can work them out, but they haven't been resolved yet."
</P>
<P>
Attorneys for Lewis and his promoter sent a letter to Park
Place Entertainment on Wednesday telling the casino operator to
stop giving the public "a false impression that the fight is made,
which is consistent with the current state of facts."
</P>
<P>
Lewis and Holyfield have both agreed to $15 million paydays for
the proposed November fight and Park Place has signed a deal with
Kings to hold it at one of its Las Vegas casinos, but so far, no
contracts for the fight have actually been signed.
</P>
<P>
"Evander wants this fight to happen very badly and so, we think,
does Lennox," said Holyfield's attorney Jim Thomas.
</P>
<P>
The main issue to be resolved is HBO's insistence that Kings
step aside as the fight promoter if he were to be indicted on
charges stemming from a number of ongoing investigations into
boxing, sources close to the negotiations, speaking on condition
of anonymity, said King has refused such a clause in the contract.
</P>
<P>
"We've settled basically on the money," said Lewis attorney
Milton Chwasky. "There's only one hindrance to this. It's Don's
thing with HBO." 
