<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladeshi Politicians Play Game With Cricketers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, June 3 (Xinhua) -- While ordinary Bangladeshis are
singing the same tune celebrating the country's cricket team's
victories at the World Cup Cricket in England, politicians here
have refused to share a common platform to greet the national
cricket "heroes."
</P>
<P>
The government has planned a public reception for the
cricketers at the National Parade Square at Sher-e-Bangla Nagar on
Friday at 10:00 a.m. while the main opposition - the Bangladesh
Nationalist Party (BNP has decided to greet them at Zia
International Airport.
</P>
<P>
The BNP also plans to arrange a public reception for the team
when they will return after the June 20 World Cup final, party
sources said.
</P>
<P>
The players are coming to Dhaka to attend Friday's reception
and will go back to England next Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Dhaka Mayor Mohammad Hanif called an all-party meting on
Wednesday evening to discuss the reception preparations, but none
from the major opposition parties, including the BNP, the Jatiya
Party (Ershad) and Jamaat-e-Islami turned up, The Daily Star
newspaper reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Only representatives of the Jatiya Party faction led by Mizan
Chowdhury and Anwar Hossain Manju, the communication minister, and
other smaller parties came to the meeting.
</P>
<P>
The two major parties, the ruling Awami League (AL) and the BNP,
behaved in a similar manner two years ago when Bangladesh won the
International Cricket Committee (ICC) Trophy.
</P>
<P>
The BNP boycotted the civic reception for the ICC Trophy
winners,organized by an AL-led national committee in April 1997,
and organized a separate reception a few days later.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina on Wednesday drew a similarity
between this year's bumper harvest and the stunning win by the
Bangladeshi team on Monday against Pakistan at the World Cup
Cricket, the BSS news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
"We did not expect a bumper harvest this year after the
protracted floods of 1998," and "we also did not expect that our
boys would win against Pakistan," she said.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh won two matches at the World Cup Cricket, first
against Scotland on May 25 and then against Pakistan on May 31.
</P>
<P>
Cricket is the most popular sport in Bangladesh, and this is
the first time that the Bangladeshi squad has been qualified to
contest with 11 other world-class teams in the Cricket World Cup.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
