<HEADLINE> Gas Field Discovered at "Fault Block" in Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh has for the first time
discovered a gas field at a "fault block" in Capna of the
northeastern district of Sylhet, opening a new horizon for its gas
sector, The Financial Express daily newspaper reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
In the past, gas fields had been discovered only in the
"anticline" structure in this gas-rich South Asian country.
</P>
<P>
There are huge "fault blocks" throughout the country, but these
blocks were not considered for the discovery of gas or oil in the
past because earlier test results were not good. The Capna
discovery however has been an eye-opener for both private- and
public-sector gas developers, sources were quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The Capna gas field, situated between Sylhet and the
Kailashtila gas field, might be one of the largest gas fields in
the country, they said.
</P>
<P>
The Capna discovery might increase the country's gas reserves
to around 80 trillion cubic feet, they added.
</P>
<P>
The current estimate is that the country has a gas reserve of
30 trillion to 40 trillion cubic feet including the 13 trillion
cubic feet already discovered, according to a senior executive of
a multinational oil company.
</P>
<P>
For the expeditious exploration and expansion of gas resources,
the whole country has been divided into 23 blocks, which have been
offered for investment by local and foreign investors. In the
meantime, agreements have been concluded with four foreign
companies for eight blocks, on which work is in full swing.
Besides, negotiations are being conducted for the signing of
contracts for 12 more locks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990603.0265 </DOCNO>
