<HEADLINE> Thailand, Cambodia to Discuss Border Demarcation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Thailand and Cambodia will meet for
the first time later this month to discuss border demarcation
after recent disputes along the their border, the local television
station TV 9 quoted the Thai Army as saying Thursday.
</P>
<P>
A meeting of the joint boundary committee has been set for June
29 and 30 in Bangkok, the army said.
</P>
<P>
It was reported earlier that the Thai Army had sent
reinforcements to the Thai-Cambodian border in the northeastern
province of Buri Ram after the Cambodian government claimed an
undemarcated area there.
</P>
<P>
Cambodian soldiers have alleged that the area, known as
Checkpoint 27, belongs to Cambodia.
</P>
<P>
However, the Thai Army had denied any confrontation or violence
along the border.
</P>
<P>
Before last year's election in Cambodia, areas along the
Thai-Cambodian border had been under the control of the
now-defunct Khmer Rouge guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
The formation of a new Cambodian government and the collapse of
the Khmer Rouge guerrilla movement paved the way for the start of
demarcation talks. 
</P>
