<HEADLINE> Sino-U.S. Venture Set to Mine Germanium </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HOHHOT, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Companies from China and the United
States recently established a joint venture to mine germanium, a
rare chemical element that can be used in a variety of high-tech
areas.
</P>
<P>
The new venture is located in north China's Inner Mongolia
Autonomous Region. U.S.-based AXT Corp. and two Chinese companies
will invest 10 million yuan (1.2 million US dollars) to develop
China's largest germanium mine near Xilin Gol League, some 400 km
from Beijing.
</P>
<P>
The mine has germanium reserves of over 1,600 tons, or some 30
percent of the national total. The joint venture will produce an
estimated five tons of germanium annually during a 25-year
cooperative period.
</P>
<P>
Germanium, a rare and expensive mineral, is used to produce
optical fiber cables, electronic equipment and semiconductors.
</P>
</TEXT>
