<HEADLINE> Myanmar to Expedite Completion of Special Projects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar leader Senior-General Than
Shwe Wednesday called for expediting the completion of special
projects being implemented in the country, saying these projects
are basically indispensable for the nation's development.
</P>
<P>
"If these projects can be completed rapidly, they can be
beneficial to the nation quickly," said Than Shwe, chairman of the
Myanmar State Peace and Development Council, at a coordination
meeting of the country's Special Projects Implementation Committee
 (SPIC) here Wednesday, official newspaper The New Light of
Myanmar reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Than Shwe, who is also chairman of the SPIC, stressed the
importance to use funds allocated by the government for the
respective projects without causing losses and wastage and urged
that  priority be given to qualitative improvement.
</P>
<P>
The meeting discussed projects of eight reservoirs being built
in six states and divisions, 17 bridges to be built in other
regions, and diversion weirs to be constructed on the eastern and
western parts of the Bago Yoma mountain range and on the western
bank of the Ayeyawaddy River.
</P>
<P>
A project for establishment of teak plantations was also
discussed.
</P>
<P>
In 1994, Myanmar's SPIC approved numerous special projects to
be further carried out in the country in an effort to promote
infrastructure development.
</P>
<P>
Under the impact of the Asian financial crisis, Myanmar has
intensified efforts in the agricultural sector as part of its
economic recovery measures by reclaiming fallow, vacant, virgin
and wet lands and building indispensable dams and reservoirs
while restricting new larger infrastructure projects. 
</P>
</TEXT>
