<HEADLINE> Mexico's International Reserves Drop </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Mexico's international reserves
dropped 70 million U.S. dollars during the week from May 21 to 28,
reducing the total reserves to 30.18 billion dollars, said the
Bank of Mexico on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The central bank said the Mexico's net international assets
dropped 87 million dollars in the same period, due to a fall in
the net income of Petroleos Mexicanos (Pemex) and changes in the
government's outlays.
</P>
<P>
The Bank of Mexico attributed the last factor to the lower net
yields from purchases and sales of metals and stocks abroad.
</P>
<P>
The situation was aggravated by the variation of the commercial
banks' deposits in dollars in the Bank of Mexico and the change of
the currency value against the dollar. 
</P>
