<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ewing out for Rest of Playoffs with Tear of Left Achilles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 2 (Xinhua) -- In a 14-year NBA career that has
been epitomized by playoff disappointment, New York Knicks
superstar center Patrick Ewing faced a heartbreaking dose of
reality today when an MRI revealed a partial tear of his left
Achilles tendon.
</P>
<P>
The Knicks announced today Ewing will miss the remainder of the
postseason due to the injury suffered Tuesday night in Game 2 of
the Eastern Conference finals against the Indiana Pacers.
</P>
<P>
"Patrick had a tearing sensation in his left Achilles during
warmups prior to last night's game," Knicks team physician Dr.
Norman Scott said. "Following the game, Patrick showed signs of
swelling in his Achilles that we have not previously seen.
</P>
<P>
"This morning, Patrick underwent an MRI, which showed a partial
tear of his left Achilles tendon. This is not a career-threatening
injury, and we expect Patrick to make a complete recovery."
</P>
<P>
Ewing, 36, has hobbled through most of the lockout-shortened
season due to left Archilles tendinitis. The pain was so severe
before Tuesday's game that Ewing told coach Jeff van Gundy that he
"didn't know what he could give" the team.
</P>
<P>
Ewing ended up playing 25 minutes, finishing with 10 points on
2-of-7 shooting and three rebounds in New York's 88-86 loss at
Indiana. However, with a chance to tie the game in the final
seconds, Ewing missed a 5-meter off a court-length pass from
Charlie Ward.
</P>
<P>
Ewing's disappointment after the missed shot turned into a
bitter pill to swallow this morning after the MRI administered
today revealed the tendon tear. Ewing was devastated by the news.
</P>
<P>
"His reaction was like, 'You're kidding.' He just didn't
believe me," said Dr. Scott. "He was despondent, really depressed.
"
</P>
<P>
Ewing's Achilles will be immobilized in a camwalker for six
weeks before he is re-examined.
</P>
<P>
"It's frustrating to work so hard and to be so close to
something I've dreamed about for so many years," said Ewing. "To
not be able to be on the floor to help my teammates is very
frustrating and disappointing, but if my Achilles ruptures
completely, it would end my career."
</P>
<P>
The Knicks will have to beat the favored Pacers without Ewing,
who has seen his role reduced but nevertheless is a vital piece to
the team's success. His absence leaves defensive-minded and foul-
prone Chris Dudley as New York's starting center for the rest of
the best-of-seven series.
</P>
<P>
Van Gundy, who has coached the Knicks to the conference finals
despite swirling rumors that he will not be retained, was
especially sympathetic to Ewing's plight.
</P>
<P>
"I just felt very bad for him because it seems he's being
cheated out of another opportunity," said Van Gundy. "I'm just
terribly disappointed for him. I know how hard he rehabbed from
his wrist injury from last season and how much he struggled
through this season on his knee. I just hope in his last two years
on a Knicks contract he could be healthy."
</P>
<P>
Last year, Ewing missed the majority of the regular season with
a dislocated wrist. He returned for the last four games of the
conference semifinals against the Pacers. During the regular
season, he missed 12 games due to Achilles tendinitis and averaged
17.3 points and 9.9 rebounds. The scoring average was a career
low and the rebounding average his lowest in 10 years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990603.0280 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
