<HEADLINE> NBA Playoffs Resume Friday After Two-Day Break </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 2 (Xinhua) -- After a two-day break, the NBA
playoffs will resume Friday night with the Western Conference
finals.
</P>
<P>
The Portland Trail Blazers will use the time to regroup after
an especially painful 86-85 loss to the San Antonio Spurs in Game
2 of the West finals on Monday. The Trail Blazers did not trail
until Sean Elliott's miraculous 3-pointer with 9.9 seconds left
gave the Spurs the win and a 2-0 lead in the series, which shifts
to Portland for Game 3 on Friday and Game 4 on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The Indiana Pacers and New York Knicks are tied at one game
apiece in the Eastern Conference finals. The series heads to New
York for Game 3 on Saturday and Game 4 on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Knicks will be without ailing superstar center Patrick
Ewing, whose body finally gave in to a series of injuries. Ewing
has a partial tear of his left Archilles tendon and is done for
the season.
</P>
<P>
The Spurs won the first game 80-76, but appeared headed for
defeat in Game 2 until Elliott's miracle shot. The Blazers are
faced with having to beat the Spurs four times in the next five
games, a tall order considering San Antonio had lost four times in
its last 32 games.
</P>
<P>
This is San Antonio's fifth trip to the conference finals but
the first time it has held a 2-0 lead. The Spurs never have been
to the NBA Finals.
</P>
<P>
The Knicks overcame a 17-point deficit and a hostile crowd
against the Indiana Pacers on Tuesday. But they were still nipped
by the Pacers 86-88. The Knicks had won a franchise-record six
straight playoff games, but without Ewing, they are facing a tough
task to crack the experienced Pacers in the remaining games.
</P>
