<HEADLINE> Hungary to Send Engineering, Security Troops to Kosovo Peace Mission </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUDAPEST, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Hungarian Foreign Minister
Martonyi Janos said that Hungary would send engineering and
security troops to the peace-keeping mission if a peace deal could
be reached on Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
He made the statement at a press conference after party leaders
in the parliament ended consultations on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Before this, Hungary expressed it would send no troops to
Kosovo in any circumstances.
</P>
<P>
Now that with changes in the situation, it seemed likely the
warring sides could reach a peace deal, and Hungary would like to
discharge its obligation in the process, he added.
</P>
<P>
He noted Hungary would discuss with NATO on the specifics of
the troops, which would have to be approved by two thirds in the
parliament.
</P>
<P>
Also speaking at the conference, Commander and Chief of General
Staff Vegh Ferenc said that Hungary would send in 120 to 250
security and engineering troops, who would be equipped with
weapons for self defense. 
