<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Brazilian, Thai Leaders Urge Regulating Hedge Funds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRASILIA, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Brazilian President Fernando
Henrique Cardoso and visiting Thai Prime Minister Chuan Leekpai on
Wednesday agreed that the international community must reach
consensus on regulating hedge funds, as their entry and departure
can destabilize the world financial systems.
</P>
<P>
Hedge funds are speculative investments that seek quick gains
in financial markets.
</P>
<P>
During their talks, the two leaders reviewed the impacts of the
two-year-old international financial turmoil on their countries,
both of which bore the brunt of the global financial crunches
originating from Southeast Asia in the second half of 1997.
</P>
<P>
Chuan Leekpai said emerging Asian economies and members of the
Southern Common Market (Mercosur) should increase mutual visits,
exchange experience and take joint actions against speculative
attacks on their financial markets.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders also discussed the presidency of the World
Trade Organization (WTO), which is sought by, among others, Thai
Commerce Minister Supachai Panitchpakdi, according to a Brazilian
Foreign Ministry spokesman.
</P>
<P>
But he did not indicate whether Cardoso committed his support
for the Thai candidate.
</P>
<P>
Chuan Leekpai arrived here Sunday for a three-day visit to
Brazil and will continue his week-long Latin American tour to Peru
and Chile. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990603.0283 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Slim Hope for Breaking WTO Leadership Deadlock </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 3 (Xinhua) -- The Thai government Wednesday once
again stressed that its candidate for the top post of the World
Trade Organization (WTO), Commerce Minister Supachai Panitchpakdi,
would not withdraw from the bitter race.
</P>
<P>
A government statement said Thailand still believed Supachai,
who is also one of the deputy prime ministers of the government,
could win the WTO leadership battle against his rival, New
Zealander Mike Moore.
</P>
<P>
It was the second attempt for the Thai government to brush off
rumors that Thailand may have admitted it cannot win the
leadership race after a campaign which has dragged for months and
paralyzed the world trade body.
</P>
<P>
The process of selecting a new director-general for the WTO has
been in a deadlock ever since the world trade body missed its last
deadline when the term of former Director-General Renato Ruggiero
expired on April 30.
</P>
<P>
The latest meeting among representatives of the 134 members in
the WTO headquarters in Geneva did nothing effective to mend the
rift between supporters of Moore and the so-called "Friends of
Supachai."
</P>
<P>
Backers of the two candidates have refused to budge from their
choices and bitter bickering and allegations are close to
derailing other crucial trade agenda issues.
</P>
<P>
Supachai is supported unanimously by Asian countries and is
also backed by Australia, some European Union countries and some
African members while Moore mainly has the backing of the United
States and Latin America.
</P>
<P>
As Supachai had been leading in every poll held before April 30
and Thailand thought he deserved the top post when Ruggiero left.
</P>
<P>
However, opposition from the United States made Supachai's
bidding for the leadership almost a "mission impossible."
</P>
<P>
The U.S. stance has aroused fierce indignation in Thailand,
which considers itself a U.S. ally.
</P>
<P>
Thai ministers, citing promises made by U.S. President Bill
Clinton and Secretary of State Madeleine Albright not to block
Supachai, have repeatedly called for transparency of the WTO
selection process and a neutral U.S. stance.
</P>
<P>
Some Thai politicians have urged the government to reconsider
its policies toward the United States and some of them even joined
the public to rally in front of the U.S. Embassy in Bangkok to
protesting against what they called the U.S. "foul play" in the
matter.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said the United States chooses Moore partly because he
has ingratiated himself with the most powerful U.S. labor lobby,
the AFL-CIO.
</P>
<P>
In a U.S. election season, labor's vote matters to Democrats
and Republicans alike, they said.
</P>
<P>
The United States also worried that if Supachai becomes
Ruggiero's successor, he could hurt U.S. interests in the WTO by
listening more to the less-developed countries' concerns about the
WTO statutes on anti-dumping.
</P>
<P>
The huge differences between the United States and Asian
members over many trade issues are reasons behind the unbreakable
impasse of the director-generalship race.
</P>
<P>
While the United States calls for linking trade with labor and
environmental issues at the WTO's Seattle ministerial meeting in
November, the Asians want the issues to be tackled by the
International Labor Organization and the United Nation's
environmental agency respectively.
</P>
<P>
Eager to have their voice heard, the Asian nations find that
the most effective way is to have a director-general from the
region.
</P>
<P>
The WTO has the tradition of reaching accords by
"consensus-building." Despite Thailand's and the Asians' repeated
calls for a vote to end the deadlock, the United States cited the
tradition to avoid it.
</P>
<P>
As both the Americans and the Asians are unlikely to soften
their stances on the new director-general of the world trade body,
hope is slim for either Supachai or Moore to finally get the top
post.
</P>
<P>
Diplomats in Geneva had predicted that the selection process
may end with the emergence of a third candidate who would command
support from a majority of the WTO members.
</P>
<P>
But, to start the selection process all over again will take a
long time, which is something that the WTO can not afford.
</P>
</TEXT>
