<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mexican Peso Devaluation Termed Positive </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, June 2 (Xinhua) -- The devaluation of the Mexican
currency, the Peso, against the U.S. dollar in the last week is
positive, said the BBV Probursa Financial Group Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Financial Group said in its most recent report that the
peso devaluation last week, which amounted to 3.5 percent, will
check the aggravating imbalance of trade.
</P>
<P>
It added that the national currency devaluation in the past
weeks will prevent an expansion in a short time of the trade
deficit and that of the current account, especially when a "bigger
economic growth" is expected in the second half of the year.
</P>
<P>
The Peso fell as rising U.S. interest rates lured investors
from Mexican securities, cutting demand for pesos.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that investors cashed their pesos for dollars
as the interest rate of the U.S. 30-year Treasury bond rose 10
basis points to 5.93 percent following a higher-than-expected
increase in the May manufacturing index reported by the National
Association of Purchasing Management.
</P>
<P>
The Group said that the impact on the official inflation goal
of 13 percent by the end of this year will be minimal.
</P>
<P>
The national currency performance against the dollar is natural
in the floating system in this field, said the Group. 
</P>
</TEXT>
