<HEADLINE> Cuban Parliament Speaker Leaves for Talks with US on Migration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, June 2 (Xinhua) -- President of the Cuban National
Assembly of People's Power (parliament) Richardo Alarcon has left
for New York for talks with U.S. authorities aimed at examining
compliance by both sides with the migration agreements signed in
1994 and 1995.
</P>
<P>
This, or the 11th, round of the biannual talks are scheduled to
start on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Before leaving for New York, Alarcon said here that bilateral
commitment will work for the creation of orderly and legitimate
migratory flows.
</P>
<P>
Under agreements signed in 1994 and 1995, the United States
shall repatriate to the island country all illegal immigrants
trying to enter the U.S. by sea.
</P>
<P>
In compliance with the accords, 1,905 Cubans have been sent
back to Cuba in the past four years, of whom 1,515 by the U.S.
Coast Guard Service and 390 from the U.S. naval base in Guantanamo,
in the eastern end of the island.
</P>
<P>
Cuba has signed similar migratory agreements with other
Caribbean nations including Bahamas, Belize and the Dominican
Republic. 
</P>
</TEXT>
