<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Voter Registration Reaches 91.14 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 3 (Xinhua) -- The voter registration throughout
Indonesia has reached 91.14 percent or 116,254,217 voters,
according to spokesman of the General Elections Commission
Djohermansyah Djohan.
</P>
<P>
Data collected by the commission show that West Java Province
has the highest number of registered voters (96.16 percent),
followed by Central Sulawesi and North Sulawesi (95.54 percent and
94.87 percent respectively).
</P>
<P>
The areas with the smallest number of registered voters are
East Timor and Aceh, with 43.9 percent and 56.76 percent
respectively, Djohan was quoted Thursday by Antara News Agency as
saying.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, the overseas general elections bureau reported
that voter registration has reached 74 percent or 579,318 voters.
</P>
<P>
Despite mushrooming complaints from election officials about
the ill-prepared polls, the General Election Commission
Secretary-General Amur Muchasim insisted that preparations were
"running smoothly."
</P>
<P>
Reports from poll officials throughout the country said various
technical disruptions were found only four days ahead of the poll,
such as misprinted ballot papers and inferior ink in Jakarta,
Central and East Java as well as in Kalimantan, Lampung and North
Sumatera.
</P>
<P>
"All elections tool kits consisting of ballot papers, ink,
ballot pads up to the nails used to punch the ballot papers have
been distributed to all regencies," Amur said.
</P>
<P>
Separately, Information Minister Yunus Yosfiah Wednesday said
the government will soon issue a presidential decree to declare
June 7, 1999, a holiday to give the people ample time to go to the
polls.
</P>
<P>
During the former President Soeharto administration, polling
was always done on workdays, compelling civil servants to cast
their ballots at polling stations set up on the premises of their
offices. 
</P>
</TEXT>
