<HEADLINE> Indonesian Billiard Body to Choose 14 Players for SEA Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 3 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian Billiard and Snooker
Association (POBSI) was ready to select 14 of 20 players for
preparations for the 20th Southeast Asian (SEA) Games.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia's snooker coach Hendro T. Nuraji said the national
team, to compete in the biennial event in Brunei Darussalam from
August 7 to August 15, will comprise three players in the snooker
event, three players in the English billiard event, four players
in the nine-ball event and another four in the 15-ball event.
</P>
<P>
"In the snooker event, Rudi Sulaeman has been training in
Australia at his own expense for several months. Other candidates
are Sayumin, Peng K. Sen, Bernhard and Hek Ta," Nuraji was quoted
by The Jakarta Post Thursday as saying.
</P>
<P>
Brunei, which will host the Games for the first time, will not
feature all billiard events, unlike the Indonesian hosting of the
1997 SEA Games.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia will miss opportunities to win gold from carom events
as they will not be featured at the event.
</P>
<P>
"If we could compete in carom, we could win two golds as
promised by POBSI chairman Putera Astaman earlier," Nuraji said.
</P>
<P>
Due to limited finances, POBSI is yet to announce any plans to
send players for tryouts abroad. Indonesia made a clean sweep of
12 golds in the 1997 SEA Games here. 
</P>
</TEXT>
