<HEADLINE> Bulgaria Studies Way of Logistic Support to Kosovo Peacekeeping </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Bulgaria is studying the way in which
it could provide logistic support for future NATO peacekeeping
operation in Kosovo, but has not yet begun negotiations with NATO
on the matter, Foreign Ministry said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Ministry spokesman Radko Vlaikov said several Bulgarian
departments are coordinating efforts in which the country could
logistically support the operation following the possible signing
of a peace accord on Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
However, a document on the logistic support, which is worked on
by the departments, is not the subject of negotiations, the
spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Vlaikov admitted that about a dozen NATO representatives are
currently in Bulgaria, familiarizing themselves with the
infrastructures in all sites that could be useful for the
realization of the logistic support.
</P>
<P>
He recalled that as of this February, the Bulgarian government
was principally ready to support the operation once a Kosovo peace
accord was signed and also voiced its readiness to take part in
the operation with non-combat units.
</P>
<P>
Back then, the foreign and defense ministers were assigned to
negotiate with NATO on the matter, he said, noting if an agreement
is reached thereby, it still has to be ratified by the National
Assembly.  
</P>
</TEXT>
