<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italians Urge Limiting Auto Traffic in City Centers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, June 2 (Xinhua) -- More than 88 percent of Italians are
in favor of banning auto vehicles in city centers to reduce noise
pollution and improve the quality of the air.
</P>
<P>
According to a study by the Demoskopea group, 70 percent of
Italians favor banning the smoky, two-cycle motors, and 80 percent
are ready to back banning cars without catalytic converters from
downtown.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the report, Environment Minister Edo Ronchi said,
"These findings demonstrate that Italians are in agreement with
the measures we have been proposing for some time, and those who
view them as too drastic must now rethink their position after
these results, which clearly indicate that traffic in cities has
become unbearable."
</P>
<P>
On the question of how to improve urban traffic, 97 percent of
those surveyed proposed creating parking lots outside city centers
and 94 percent called for greater investment in public transport.
</P>
<P>
Although Italians have strong opinions on anti-smog measures,
they are apparently not well informed on what measures are already
in force. Only 22 percent of the respondents knew that a law
against the use of benzene exists. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
