<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> D'Alema: Ground Invasion of Sovereign State "Unimaginable" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, June 2 (Xinhua) -- It would be "unimaginable" for NATO to
decide on its own to invade a sovereign state, Italian Prime
Minister Massimo D'Alema said Wednesday amid growing controversies
over NATO's sending ground troops to the troubled Serbian province
of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Speaking on a TV talk show, D'Alema said NATO member countries
have not started discussions on sending ground troops to Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
He said if the ongoing mediation could not get along, the
United Nations should be called in to approve a resolution, which
would be the only way out of the Balkan war.
</P>
<P>
He noted that Italy hopes for an immediate halt to the bombing
of Yugoslavia to facilitate the search for a peaceful solution.
</P>
<P>
Italian President Carlo Azeglio Ciampi, in his speech to
foreign ambassadors in Rome on the National Day on Wednesday,
expressed deep concerns over the "terrible" state of affairs in
the Balkans and called for negotiations to solve the crisis.
</P>
<P>
Chairman of the Party of Italian Communists Armando Cossutta
said Wednesday that whenever there is hope for peace, the United
States would always come up with new obstacles because it wants to
continue this war. He urged the Italian government to let people
hear its peace calls on every occasion.
</P>
<P>
On the same day, demonstrations were staged in Rome, Milan,
Naples, Venice and Brescia in protest against NATO's protracted
bombing of Yugoslavia, calling for a quick end to the bombing and
a negotiated solution to the crisis.
</P>
<P>
Demonstrators in Milan set up 400 crosses in a park and placed
toys in front of them in memory of innocent Yugoslav children
killed by NATO bombings. 
</P>
</TEXT>
