<DOCNO> XIE19990603.0299 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Will not Become Military Group: Klima </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
VIENNA, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Austrian Prime Minister Viktor Klima
said here Wednesday that the European Union (EU) would not turn
itself into a military bloc even if it made considerable progress
in mutual diplomatic and security policies.
</P>
<P>
Before leaving for the forthcoming EU Summit in Koln, Germany,
Klima told reporters that if the regional organization appeared as
a military group with mutual commitments, it would bring no good
to the group itself, to its enlargement and to Europe as a whole.
</P>
<P>
Klima noted that the government of Austria, a neutral member of
the 15-nation bloc, had affirmed its position in the document on
mutual diplomatic and security policies, which had been drafted
for the summit by EU's current rotating presidency Germany.
</P>
<P>
Further evolution of these policies conformed to the Austrian
Constitution and could not change a jot of the neutral status of
Austria, the prime minister held.
</P>
<P>
Referring to reports that NATO's Secretary-General Javier
Solana would assume the post of EU's representative for mutual
diplomatic and security policies, Klima expressed his disapproval
that Solana should hold the two positions concurrently.
</P>
<P>
But in principle, Klima went on, he welcomed the nomination of
Solana for the EU post, who is a member of the Spanish Workers'
Socialist Party.
</P>
<P>
Solana's term as the NATO chief expires at the end of the year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
