<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia Urges U.S. Apology for Chinese Embassy Attack </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Australian Defense Minister John
Moore urged the United States to quickly apologize to China over
the missile attack on its Belgrade embassy, The Australian
newspaper reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the paper, the minister warned that
relations between the United States and China were crucial to the
stability of the Asia-Pacific region and would worsen further if
the United States did not respond promptly to China's four
demands, including an official apology and a briefing on the
subsequent investigation into the incident.
</P>
<P>
NATO warplanes bombed the Chinese Embassy in a May 7 raid,
killing three Chinese journalists and wounding more than 20
Chinese diplomats.
</P>
<P>
"I think it's not at all unreasonable for them to ask for a
proper response to the bombing and I'd urge America to respond,"
Moore told The Australian, a leading national newspaper in
Australia.
</P>
<P>
"It's not only important to Asia-Pacific relations but to world
relations."
</P>
<P>
The defense minister has just returned from a visit to China,
where he met top defense and political leaders in a bid to
strengthen Australia's relationship with China. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
