<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Peruvian Customs Seize Contraband Historical Books </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LIMA, June 2 (Xinhua) -- The Peruvian customs authorities have
seized a cargo of more than 840 books printed in the 17th and 18th
centuries, and library experts confirmed Wednesday that they are
cultural inheritance which should be kept by the General Archives
of the Nation.
</P>
<P>
The invaluable books, to be sent to the United States, were
discovered by customs agents in the four chests whose contents had
been declared to be simple books valued at 900 U.S. dollars by
their owner, U.S. citizen Bruce Headfitz.
</P>
<P>
The National Library experts supposed that the books were from
a private library owned by the Prado family, one of the most
traditional families of Peru, from which at least two presidents
of this Andean country came. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990603.0311 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Spain's United Left: Put NATO on Trial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MADRID, June 2 (Xinhua) -- General Coordinator of Spain's
United Left (UL), Julio Anguita, demanded Wednesday The Hague
International Court to put on the defendant's seat all those who
lead the NATO aggression against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
Anguita condemned the NATO bombings of civilian targets, saying
that in these actions nobody can talk of "collateral damages"
since "they are deliberate bombings."
</P>
<P>
He added that the decision to bomb Yugoslavia was made last
January by United States President Bill Clinton and British Prime
Minister Tony Blair.
</P>
<P>
He denounced that the decision was proposed in Rambouillet to
force Yugoslavia to permit the NATO troops to enter the country
and detain any person.
</P>
<P>
"Spaniards have been systematically misled and that they must
refuse their confidence to those who lie," he said.
</P>
<P>
Anguita insisted in demanding The Hague International Court to
give an order to persecute and capture "all the criminals of the
zone," and to analyze the action of the allied bombings, to which
he referred as "acts of international terrorism."
</P>
<P>
Anguita said that the allied bombings are a cover to hide the
goal of "sinking Europe's political projects," because the United
States does not want to permit it that a politically strong and
socially united European Union will become "an alternate power"
after the disappearance of the Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
The general coordinator said that after 71 days of bombings,
NATO countries "do not know what to do" and are forced to
negotiate with Milosevic, after the Serb president was declared "
war criminal." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990603.0312 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mexico-U.S. Binational Commission to Meet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, June 2 (Xinhua) -- The Mexico-U.S. Binational
Commission will meet here Thursday to discuss issues including the
war against drug trafficking, illegal migration and the North
American Free Trade Agreement (NAFT), according to the Mexican
foreign ministry Monday.
</P>
<P>
Also high on the agenda will be the creation of working groups
on agriculture, culture, science and technology, energy,
environment, business promotion, health, housing and urban
development, said the ministry.
</P>
<P>
Headed by Foreign Secretary Madeleine Albright, the U.S.
delegation will include the Attorney General and secretaries of
Commerce, Transports, Interior, and Agriculture, while the Mexican
side will include Attorney General Jorge Madrazo, Foreign Minister
Rosario Green, and ministers of Social Development, Environment,
Trade and others.
</P>
<P>
Founded in 1983, the Commission is one of the most important
links between the two countries that share a common border of more
than 3,000 kilometers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990603.0313 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> American Continent Faces Serious Environmental Problems </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANAMA CITY, June 2 (Xinhua) -- The American continent faces
serious environmental problems that endangered the population's
health, a United Nations Environment Program (UNEP) official
warned here Wednesday at the opening of a regional environmental
forum.
</P>
<P>
Enrique Leff, representative of the UNEP, told Xinhua that "the
environmental problems are very acute and they are touching basic
aspects of human survival."
</P>
<P>
The accelerated environmental pollution in the last decade in
the continent has caused epidemics, respiratory diseases, and
intoxication with deadly substances, and it did not only affect
the big cities, but also spread toxic and dangerous substances in
agricultural production, said Leff.
</P>
<P>
In the American continent's rural areas, the chemicals applied
to the agriculture damaged seriously the soil and affected the
agricultural workers' health, Leff added.
</P>
<P>
Representatives of Colombia, Chile, Ecuador, Peru, and Panama
attended the three-day international forum on the environment,
aiming at designing new strategies of environmental preservation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990603.0314 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NATO Carries on Extensive Bombardment of Yugoslavia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZAGREB, June 2 (Xinhua) -- NATO continued to bomb military and
civilian targets across Yugoslavia overnight Tuesday and Wednesday,
pounding heavily on Yugoslav armed forces in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Media reports here said NATO blasted 32 heavy artillery
positions and eight mortar positions of the Yugoslav military,
which were deployed against the separatist Kosovo Liberation Army
in the southern Serbian province. The bombing destroyed 15 armored
vehicles of the Yugoslav forces.
</P>
<P>
The Croatian Radio and Television, quoting a report from
Belgrade Radio, said the Yugoslav air defense forces shot down a
NATO plane in Panchevo and were looking for the pilot who bailed
out.
</P>
<P>
On the same day, NATO warplanes again bombed power relay
transmitters in Belgrade, a military airport in Batajnica, a
military camp in Obrenovac and eight radio-television transmitters
throughout Serbia.
</P>
<P>
NATO also raided the Yugoslav air defense headquarters in Novi
Sad, two fuel bunkers in northern Serbia, an arms depot and a
bridge for highway and railway.
</P>
<P>
The Croatian Radio and Television, citing Yugoslav military
sources, said the second-in-command of the Yugoslav air force,
General Ljubisha Velickovich, was killed in action when he visited
the front-line on Wednesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
