<DOCNO> XIE19990603.0315 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Economists Sign Open Letter on Antitrust Cases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, June 2 (Xinhua) -- The long-drawn-out war between
Microsoft and the U.S. Department of Justice and 19 states has
prompted heated arguments in and out of the court. An open letter
published Tuesday added something new.
</P>
<P>
The Independent Institute, an Oakland, California-based
scholarly public policy institution published the letter to
President Bill Clinton. It was signed by 240 leading economists
addressing "runaway antitrust protectionism" and calling for an
end to speculative enforcement efforts.
</P>
<P>
Citing recent high-profile litigation against Microsoft, Intel,
Cisco Systems, Visa and MasterCard, the letter said that the cases
were instigated by rival business firms instead of consumers.
</P>
<P>
"Where antitrust authorities respond to these protectionism
demands, the workings of markets are short-circuited," the letter
said. "Antitrust protectionism means that market decisions about
how to compete for consumers' favor are displaced by bureaucrat ic
and political decisions."
</P>
<P>
Antitrust is supposed to be about protecting consumers against
higher prices and other consequences of monopoly power, said the
letter, adding that it was not consumers but rival firms that
asked for these antitrust actions. In fact, the letter said,
consumers of high technology have enjoyed falling prices,
expanding outputs and array of new products and innovations.
</P>
<P>
The letter said that more of the energies of firms are now
directed to politics, less to production and innovation.
"Successful innovators are penalized, scales economies are lost,
and competitions thwarted," said the letter, warning that these
cases would weaken U.S. firms and reduce their international
competitiveness.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
