<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IOC 2000 Commission Holds First Meeting on Reforms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAUSANNE, Switzerland, June 2 (Xinhua) -- The International
Olympic Committee (IOC) 2000 Commission recommended here Wednesday
that a new procedure be introduced for electing the host city of
the 2008 Olympic Games after the commission met for the first time
here on June 1-2 on the IOC reforms.
</P>
<P>
For bidding cities, the new procedure will be "easier and less
expensive," IOC President Juan Antonio Samaranch told Xinhua at a
press conference held at the end of the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Up to now, Samaranch disclosed, some 10 cities have shown
intention to host the 2008 games. They are Beijing of China, Osaka
of Japan, Kuala Lumpur of Malaysia, Buenos Aires of Argentina,
Toronto of Canada, Cairo of Egypt, Cape Town of South Africa,
Sevilla of Spain, Istanbul of Turkey and Paris of France.
</P>
<P>
During the two-day meeting, the IOC 2000 commission will set up
an executive committee in charge of the coordination of the
proceedings and three working groups with missions to study
respectively the compositon, structure and organizaton of the IOC;
the role of the IOC; and the designation of the host of the
Olympic Games.
</P>
<P>
The commission will be presenting an initial preliminary report
to the 109th IOC session which opens at Seoul of South Korea on
June 17. The three working groups will continue their activity
throughout the summer.
</P>
<P>
The commission is expected to have prepared its conclusions and
final recommendatons by the end of October 1999. These will then
be presented to the IOC at an extraordinary session planned for
the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
Besides IOC officials, those present at the two-day meeting
include former United Natons Secretary General Boutros Boutros
Ghali, former United States Secretary of State Henry Kinssinger,
Italian senator and industrialist Gianni Agnelli, French senator
Michel Barnier, and former Norwegian Foreign Minister Thomas
Stoltenberg. 
</P>
</TEXT>
