<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Air Traffic Grows 1 Percent in 1998: ICAO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Total scheduled traffic of
the world's airlines recorded only 1 percent growth in 1998 over
1997, the International Civil Aviation Organization (ICAO)
reported on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The world's scheduled airlines fetched an operating profits of
5.5 percent of revenues in 1998, the Montreal-based ICAO said.
</P>
<P>
Operating revenues and expenses both rose by 3 percent over
1997, with 298.5 billion U.S. dollars and 282.0 billion dollars
reached respectively, it said.
</P>
<P>
The results reflected a generally healthy world economy, said
ICAO, adding that setbacks in several major economies notably in
Asia resulted in a substantial slowdown in traffic growth.
</P>
<P>
The airlines of Europe and Latin America/Caribbean showed
growth well above world average in 1998, while growth of the
Middle East and North America was close to world average and
Africa below the world average, ICAO added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990603.0326 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NATO Bombing Has Adversary Impact on Yugoslavia, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 2 (Xinhua) -- The first U.N. humanitarian
assessment mission said Wednesday that the on-going NATO bombing
against Yugoslavia has created civilian deaths, massive
unemployment and has adversary impact on health care and
environment in the Balkan country.
</P>
<P>
Sergio Vieira de Mello, U.N. undersecretary for humanitarian
affairs, told a closed-door Security Council session that "the
assessment mission saw ample evidence of serious additional damage
inflicted by the NATO air strikes on an economy already
debilitated as a result of sanctions and the break up of the
former Yugoslavia."
</P>
<P>
The Balkan country met with "civilian casualties as a result of
NATO bombardments," and "unemployment reaching crisis proportions,
due to the destruction of industrial plants and enterprises and
the collapse of the country's economy," he said.
</P>
<P>
Priority concerns throughout Yugoslavia are also the "health
and environmental impact of the destruction of chemical and other
plants producing hazardous materials contamination," and "damage
to infrastructure providing basic services -- health, water
supply, education, transport, telecommunications," he said.
</P>
<P>
Beginning May 15, de Mello led a U.N. team, composed of some 15
people from a number of U.N. agencies, in making a 11-day
fact-finding tour in Kosovo and other parts of Yugoslavia, and
held talks with Yugoslav leaders in Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
The NATO bombing also "has serious impact on the educational
system" in the country because "schools and universities have been
closed throughout the FRY (the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia)
since March 24," he said.
</P>
<P>
The air strikes had "adverse effects on medium-term
agricultural production, especially in view of the destruction of
the largest fertilizer plant near Pancevo," he said.
</P>
<P>
Even worse, NATO has created "a serious landmine problems in
Kosovo and the threat posed by unexploded ordnance in the country
as a whole," he said.
</P>
<P>
Annan decided on May 4 to set up the U.N. mission to assess
the humanitarian needs of the people in Kosovo and other parts
of Yugoslavia. De Mello said that he would offer suggestions on
how to help Kosovar refugees return home in safety.
</P>
<P>
NATO, under the pretext of humanitarianism, has created a most
serious humanitarian catastrophe in Yugoslavia since the end of
World War II. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990603.0327 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cooked Vegetables Better in Fighting Cancer: Study </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Cooked vegetables give people
considerably more protection against heart disease and cancer than
raw ones, a Europe-wide study has found.
</P>
<P>
The researchers, from Britain, the Netherlands, Spain, Ireland
and France, studied an active ingredient in vegetables called
carotenoid, which is one of a group of chemicals known as
antioxidants that are thought to protect against cancer.
</P>
<P>
The study, published Wednesday in New Scientist magazine,
showed that by softening up plant cells, cooking makes carotenoids
more easily absorbed by gut.
</P>
<P>
"Absorption of carotenoids from raw carrots is about three or
four percent, but if you cook and mash them, absorption increases
by four or fivefold," said Sue Southon, at the Institute of Food
Research in Britain, who is coordinator of the project.
</P>
<P>
The research suggested that cooking can improve the performance
of carrots, broccoli and spinach when it comes to protecting
health.
</P>
<P>
The scientists, conducting their study using an artificial gut,
also found that it was easier for the body to absorb vitamins from
vegetables than from supplements. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990603.0328 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Smart Microwave Oven Makes Cooking More Simple </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 2 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Scientists are developing a
smart microwave oven that knows how to cook foods and can also
give warning about unhealthy ingredients, Britain's New Scientist
magazine reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Many microwave ovens are hard to operate as their front panels
often contain confusing arrays of badly labelled buttons.
</P>
<P>
The so-called Intelligent Microwave Oven, developed by
scientists at Rutgers University in New Jersey, the United States,
aims to end that problem using bar code technology.
</P>
<P>
With the smart oven, people can cook their ready meal by simply
swiping the packaging over a bar-code scanner on the oven's front
panel.
</P>
<P>
The bar code will contain information telling the oven how to
cook the food, ensuring that the food is cooked at the right
temperature for the right amount of time as the maker intended.
</P>
<P>
The Intelligent Microwave Oven, funded by Samsung, the Korean
consumer electronics company, is due to go on trial in six months,
according to New Scientist. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
