<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clark Says NATO Troops to Enter Kosovo in "Days" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, June 2 (Xinhua) -- The supreme commander of NATO,
Wesley Clark, said Wednesday in the Macedonian capital of Skopje
that NATO troops will enter Kosovo in just a few days.
</P>
<P>
He made the remark after meeting with Macedonian President Kiro
Gligorov.
</P>
<P>
Clark said that he discussed with Gligorov the issue of
increasing NATO troops in the country and the situation in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
He said that Macedonia has agreed to admit additional 14,000
NATO troops for peacekeeping mission in the southern Serbian
province of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
If the situation turns complicated, the NATO troops can force
their way into Kosovo without agreement from Yugoslavia, he
threatened.
</P>
<P>
With the new deployment, which Clark said will take several
weeks to complete, the total NATO troops in Macedonia will amount
to 30,000.
</P>
<P>
He said that air strikes will continue until Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milosevic accepts all the conditions set by NATO.
</P>
<P>
U.S. President Bill Clinton announced Wednesday to send 7,000
U.S. soldiers to Macedonia, half of the additional 14,000 troops
NATO has planned to deploy in the former republic of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
From Skopje, Clark flew to Tirana's Rinas Airport, "the hawk
base" of NATO troops in Albania, to conduct his routine weekly
visit.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the NATO troops in Albania said that Clark made
a detailed assessment on the troops' preparedness for their
missions in Yugoslavia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
