<DOCNO> XIE19990603.0333 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Jones Moves lower On Wall Street </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
NEW YORK, June 2 (Xinhua) -- The Dow Jones industrial
average moved lower Wednesday as investors pondered whether the
Federal Reserve will raise interest rates.
</P>
<P>
The Dow closed down 18.37 at 10,577.89. The index gained
36.52 points Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Investors' worries about higher interest rates pulled the
Dow average as much as 131 points lower in the trading.
The market was calmed down after the speech given by the
Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan in Boston, erasing most
of the losses for the index in the late afternoon trading.
</P>
<P>
In his speech, Greenspan focused his remarks on free trade
and gave no word on interest rates. The Federal Reserve warned
two weeks ago that it would raise interest rates to cool off
the economy if inflation is building up.
</P>
<P>
But investors moved into technology sector to search
bargains, pushing the technology heavy Nasdaq index and The
Standard &AMP; Poor's 5000 index higher. The Nasdaq rose 20.38 at
2,432.41 and the S&AMP;P rose 0.55 at 1294.81.
</P>
<P>
Other stock indicators were lower. The NYSE composite
index fell 0.78 at 620.50 and the American Stock Exchange
composite index fell 4.88 at 771.23. The Russell 2000 index of
smaller companies fell 0.72 at 436.74.
</P>
<P>
Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 6-to-5 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, with 1,635 dow, 1,358 up and 570
unchanged.
</P>
<P>
NYSE volume increased to 726.14 million shares from 681.99
million in the previous session. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
