<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FAO Calls for Final Push to Eliminate Rinderpest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 2 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Food and
Agriculture Organization (FAO) on Wednesday called for more
efforts to make rinderpest or cattle plague the first animal
disease to be eradicated from the earth.
</P>
<P>
Animal health officials suspect that cattle plague persists in
only three isolated areas of the world, including southern Sudan,
southern Somalia and parts of Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
However, they have reported the occurrence of the disease in
other areas within the last five years. The areas include the far
eastern Russia, the southern Arabian Peninsula and the Kurdish
area along the border between Turkey and Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Rinderpest is a contagious disease, characterized by
fever,focal erosive lesions in the mount and throughout the
alimentary tract, and by diarrhoea and a high fatality rate.
</P>
<P>
Rinderpest pandemics have killed millions of cattle, buffalo,
yaks and their wild relatives for many decades.
</P>
<P>
In the 1970s and 1980s, devastating epidemics spread in South
Asia, the Middle East and Africa, with the latest case taking
place in Pakistan in 1994, killing over 50,000 cattle and buffalo
before being brought under control.
</P>
<P>
FAO urged donor countries to provide immediate support for
rinderpest eradication programs including intensive vaccination.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
